<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MovieCow     04-16 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Movie Cow,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dairy's Beef Forces Zarda Movie To Change Name</HEAD>
<DATELINE>IOWA CITY, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the Duck's Breath Mystery
Theater say they were trying to conjure up memories of old Japanese
horror movies when they struck on the title ``Zarda, Cow From
Hell.''
   But the name for the movie involving a giant, demonic bovine
didn't get any laughs from Ben Zarda, owner of the Zarda Dairy in
Shawnee, Kan.
   ``The Zarda people decided they'd rather we not use that name.
It's unfortunate because we'd grown attached to it,'' said
executive producer Scott Smith, who went along with Zarda's wishes.
   The company learned of Zarda, the dairy, from director Robert C.
Hughes, a native of Kansas City, Kan.
   ``The cow connection just blew us away,'' Smith said.
   ``We took the name out of the blue,'' he said. ``We wanted it to
sound like a Japanese horror movie. It was supposed to be a
nonsensical name.''
   Duck's Breath Mystery Theater, a band of offbeat comics who got
their start at the University of Iowa and came back to Iowa City to
make the movie, has been working on the Zarda concept for some time.
   ``Its something we've been kicking around for about 10 years,''
said Duck's Breath manager Steve Baker of San Francisco.
   ``The story line has a film company from Hollywood coming to
Iowa to make a sleazy horror film about a giant cow,'' Baker said.
``The film company has such exaggerated characters, so absurd, that
it turns out the good folks of Iowa are more qualified to make the
movie than Hollywood types.''
   More than 600 people showed up in Iowa City this week to
audition for about 40 parts in the film. Smith said the movie
should be in the can by August.
   Meanwhile, the group is considering another name for the
production.
   ``Something equally Japanese horror movie-like, something like
Zorka,'' Smith said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
