<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Canada-Autos     04-16 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Canada-Autos,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Critics Charge Canada Trade Pact Good for Automakers, Bad for
Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives of organized labor, the state
of Michigan and parts manufacturers continued their criticism of
the U.S. free-trade agreement with Canada, telling a Senate panel
it benefits big automakers but no one else.
   ``The Big Three is very happy with the agreement, and they
should be,'' said Marc Santucci, trade representative for Michigan,
where the large automakers have their headquarters. ``It is a very
good agreement for the companies. It is not such a good agreement
for the country.
   ``As we become a global economy, we have companies no longer
speaking for the best interests of the country,'' Santucci told the
Senate Finance Committee.
   But Thomas Hanna, president of the Motor Vehicles Manufacturers
Association, which represents the major automakers, called the
treaty ``one that we believe advances U.S. national interests''
while helping the industry.
   The agreement, which requires passage by both houses of Congress
without amendment, would eliminate trade barriers between the two
nations on a wide range of goods and services. The automotive
sector accounts for about one-third of trade between the United
States and Canada.
   One provision of the agreement strongly criticized by the United
Auto Workers, parts makers and the Michigan representative allows
Canada to retain until 1996 agreements giving preferential duty
treatment to manufacturers from outside North America having
Canadian production.
   Sen. Donald Riegle, a Michigan Democrat and member of the
Finance Committee, said that provision would have effects lasting
far beyond 1996.
   ``It is widely acknowledged that, particularly in the case of
Japanese manufacturers, once a part supplier is chosen, it is a
relationship of long standing,'' Riegle said. ``By providing
Canadian suppliers with this advantage for the next seven years,
U.S. parts producers are cut out of future opportunities to supply
these plants.''
   Hanna said the manufacturers supported immediate elimination of
duty remissions, but he called the delay ``a compromise worth
accepting and supporting.''
   A second provision the UAW and parts suppliers would like to see
removed requires vehicles shipped duty-free between the two nations
to have 50 percent North American content.
   The UAW believes the content figure in the agreement ``is not
high enough to assure the use of locally produced engines,
transmission and other major components,'' said Steve Beckman, the
international economist for the UAW.
   ``It would allow the Big Three to shrink the North American
content of their vehicles down to the new standard, which is far
below the present level,'' he said.
   The manufacturers believe a 50 percent rule of origin is
sufficiently high to ``do the job it was designed to do, and that
is to ensure that the benefits of the agreement accrue to those
companies and products which can reasonably and fairly be
considered as Canadian or American in origin,'' Hanna said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880416-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-88 0309EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     04-16 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Rice Growers Expected To Benefit From Lower Production In Rice
Bowl</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world's rice bowl is skimpier this year,
and the Agriculture Department says that could help American rice
growers export more in the early months of the 1988-89 season.
   World rice production from the 1987-88 harvests is forecast at
304 million metric tons, milled equivalent, down 4 percent from
last year, the department's Economic Research Service said Friday.
Weak monsoons left Asian producers with limited exportable supplies.
   Meanwhile, global rice consumption is expected to increase 3
percent, leaving world stockpiles at their lowest level relative to
use since 1974.
   ``Recently, world production shortfalls and declining stocks in
major importing countries have led to large world imports,'' the
report said. ``However, world trade in 1988 is expected to decline
18 percent because high prices and reduced supplies in major
exporting countries have deterred imports.''
   The U.S. rice supply also has tightened, reflecting a 6 percent
reduction in last year's harvest.
   But the department's planting survey in early March indicated
American producers intend to boost 1988 rice plantings by 19
percent to 2.8 million acres. That could boost this year's output
to around 155 million hundredweight from 128 million in 1987.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds, and there are slightly more
than 22 hundredweight in a ton.
   ``U.S. farmers will harvest rice crops at least four months
ahead of their Asian competitors,'' the report said. ``Since the
United States will be the major source of supply during those
months, some increased export opportunities may exist towards the
end of 1988.''
   However, analysts cautioned that some foreign importers, if
possible, may ``choose to wait until the beginning of 1989, when
prices are likely to decline during the Asian harvest.''
   The report said some foreign importers also have been
substituting wheat for higher-priced rice.
   ``In addition, shipments of U.S. rice under food aid are
expected to decrease this year because of high prices,'' the report
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department's conservation
chief says more volunteers are needed to help carry out a massive
program aimed at protecting the nation's soil and water resources.
   Wilson Scaling, head of the Soil Conservation Service, says that
in 1987 some 2,200 volunteers provided more than $1 million worth
of assistance to agency field offices.
   This ``Earth Team,'' he said Friday, put in more than 132,000
hours in helping with tree planting, making inventories of
wetlands, conservation education, telephoning landowners to inform
them of the Conservervation Reserve Program, and providing clerical
and other office work.
   Many of the volunteers have expertise in geology, biology,
botany, surveying, mapping, and soil and erodibility
determinations, Scaling said.
   Under 1985 farm law, farmers with highly erodible cropland must
have a conservation plan approved by Dec. 31, 1989, and have it
implemented by Dec. 31, 1994, or lose USDA benefits such as price
support loans, payments and insurance.
   Scaling said the agency estimates that 800,000 conservation
plans still need to be developed nationwide.
   Anyone interested in volunteering for the Earth Team, he said,
can call 1-800-THE SOIL for the location of the local office.
Volunteers receive coverage for injury claims, are compensated for
travel expenses, and have their contributions made part of a
permanent work record, Scaling said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng says he
will appoint a former career employee, Ronald Dean Plowman of
Logan, Utah, as head of the Agriculture Department's biggest
science agency.
   Plowman, 59, will succeed Terry B. Kinney as administrator of
the Agricultural Research Service, Lyng announced Friday. Kinney is
retiring. The job pays $77,500 a year.
   Plowman has been head of Utah State University's department of
animal, dairy and veterinary sciences since 1984. For 27 years
before that, he worked for the USDA agency he will now supervise.
</TEXT>
