<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-88 0309EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AlternativeFuels     04-16 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Alternative Fuels,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congress Looking to Home-Grown Alternatives to Persian Gulf Oil</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress is moving the nation on a path some
lawmakers say will switch the U.S. energy appetite from the
political quagmire of the Persian Gulf to the more inviting
mountains of West Virginia and cornfields of Iowa.
   The path is alternative motor fuels, substances like methanol
and ethanol that advocates say can curb growing U.S. dependence on
imported petroleum and cut the trade deficit.
   Conversion of the U.S. car and light truck fleet to methanol
``means that the energy crisis would be over for generations,''
says a principal backer of the switch, Sen. Jack Danforth, R-Mo.
   On Friday, the Senate gave voice-vote approval to legislation by
Danforth and Sen. Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va., designed to encourage
automakers to begin mass-producing alternative fuel vehicles by
1993.
   Although there are concerns about the effects of some fuels on
the environment, it is all but certain that Congress will enact
alternative fuels legislation in 1988.
   A similar bill was passed overwhelmingly by the House earlier
this year. The bills' differences will have to be resolved by
negotiators from both chambers.
   The proposals envision an America where cars are powered by fuel
produced by abundant domestic resources. Ethanol is made from
grains like corn. Methanol, which powers Indianapolis 500 race
cars, is produced from coal or natural gas.
   But Senate Environment Committee members are warning that
alternative fuels are not a nirvana. They say coal-based methanol
will increase emissions of carbon dioxide, the ``greenhouse'' gas
that some scientists say contributes to a dangerous overheating of
the Earth's atmosphere.
   Danforth says the legislation would break an impasse that now
prevents any widespread switchover from gasoline to alternative
fuels.
   ``Automakers are unwilling to produce (alternative fuel) cars
for which there is no current demand,'' he said. ``Consumers are
unwilling to purchase cars for which there is no readily available
fuel supply, and service stations are unwilling to provide fuel for
cars that are not on the road.''
   Rockefeller said that besides lessening the growing U.S. need
for imported oil, a conversion of just 10 percent of the U.S.
vehicle fleet to coal-based methanol would mean jobs for 20,000
miners in the depressed coal industry.
   The senators say the legislation would make it easier for
automakers to meet the federal requirement that their fleets have
an average fuel economy of at least 26 miles per gallon,
encouraging the use of the alternative fuels.
   Sens. Robert Stafford, R-Vt., and John Chafee, R-R.I., members
of the Environment Committee, are urging caution, however, because
of possible environmental and health problems.
   Stafford said coal-derived methanol would double emissions of
carbon dioxide and bring a tenfold increase in tailpipe emissions
of formaldehyde, a cancer-causing chemical.
   He said a growing number of scientists are warning that man's
production of greenhouse gases is overloading the atmosphere,
trapping heat around the Earth and threatening major climate
changes.
   ``Once we commit to a program like this, it will be too late,''
said Stafford.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
