<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Gulf     04-16 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Gulf,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan, Advisers Weighing Response To Gulf Mining Incident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan and his top advisers
discussed a U.S. response to the mine explosion in the Persian Gulf
that almost sank an American frigate, according to an
administration source who refused to say whether military
retaliation was considered.
   The source, speaking on condition of anonymity, also would not
say if any decisions were made.
   Maj. David Super, a Pentagon spokesman, said late Friday he had
no information on any plans for military action in the gulf area in
response to the incident, which injured 10 sailors aboard the USS
Samuel B. Roberts.
   The Pentagon said it believed the mines were made by Iran, but
U.S. officials say they do not know who placed the mines in the
gulf.
   The White House discussion occurred at a regular meeting Friday
of the National Security Council and was among many topics
discussed at the session, which was dominated by planning for
Reagan's May 29-June 2 summit in Moscow with Soviet leader Mikhail
S. Gorbachev, the source said.
   Bob Hall, a White House spokesman, declined comment, saying,
``We never discuss these kinds of meetings at the White House.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, asked during a briefing
earlier Friday whether the administration planned to retaliate for
the mining, said, ``We never discuss future military actions.''
   Asked if the administration had determined who was responsible
for the mining, he said, ``No. We have not.''
   The Pentagon, meanwhile, said two mines found later in the area
near where the explosion occurred were identical to the ones
recovered last autumn from an Iranian ship, but were new mines that
had been put in the gulf recently.
   ``These were shiny, bright mines,'' Super said. ``The mines are
identical to the ones recovered aboard the Iranian ship, the Ajr,
that we intercepted several months ago that had the mines aboard
it.''
   The earlier mines were made by Iran, he said, adding, ``We
believe that these were of Iranian manufacture as well.''
   The Washington Post reported in today's editions that the group
that met at the White House discussed a wide range of possible
military responses to the Roberts incident. But the newspaper,
citing sources it did not identify, said Reagan settled for
assessing military options rather than acting on any of them.
   The newspaper said officials said one reason a military strike
had not been ordered was the lack of hard evidence that Iran laid
the mines.
   Iran and Iraq have been at war in the area for 7{ years. The
Roberts was in the gulf as part of the U.S. operation escorting
American-flagged Kuwaiti tankers through the waterway to protect
them from Iranian attacks.
   The options discussed at the meeting, according to the Post,
ranged from a simple show of force by sending the battleship USS
New Jersey to the region, to launching a retaliatory strike against
a long list of possible targets.
   According to the Pentagon, the two mines spotted from the air by
a reconnaissance helicopter were photographed and later destroyed
by a Navy team.
   Spokesman Lt. Col. Keith Schneider said the mines were moored by
cables to the bottom of the Gulf and the Navy will search for more
mines at daylight Saturday.
   The Roberts on Friday was being towed to Dubai for repairs. All
10 sailors injured in the explosion remained hospitalized, and two
of them were in critical condition.
</TEXT>
