<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Ex-CopConvicted     04-16 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ex-Cop Convicted,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Cop Convicted of Nine Counts of Murder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury Friday rejected an insanity defense and
convicted an ex-policeman of murdering nine people he said were
drug dealers who deserved to die.
   The jury reached the verdict against Manny Pardo after 6{ hours
of deliberation. It will return Wednesday to decide whether the
31-year-old worshipper of Adolf Hitler should receive the death
penalty.
   The shooting deaths occurred in Miami over a period of several
months in 1986. Pardo's victims were shot several times, generally
at close range, some in their homes and some in vehicles. Three
victims were women, six were men.
   Defense attorney Ronald Guralnick had argued that Pardo was
insane, but Pardo himself denied it, testifying that the victims
were ``not human beings'' but parasites and leeches, and that
somebody had to kill them.
   ``There's good and bad in everybody,'' Guralnick said after the
verdict. ``He saved kids' lives.''
   The prosecution contended that Pardo was a drug dealer who
killed rival dealers but that not all his victims were involved in
drugs. One was a weapons expert, and two others had a dispute with
him about money, the prosecution said.
   In an interview with WPLG-TV after his conviction, Pardo said he
wished he had killed more people. ``The system doesn't work,'' he
said. ``I was making it work my way. I was judge, jury and
executioner.''
   Pardo worked as a Florida Highway Patrol trooper and Sweetwater
patrolman from 1978 to 1985, when was fired for violating
disciplinary rules.
   His employment status at the time of the slayings was unclear.
One witness testified he was working as a security guard and
private investigator.
   A co-defendant, Rolando Garcia, will be tried separately. Pardo
testified he killed all nine victims himself.
   ``We're very glad with the verdict,'' said Regino Muso, brother
of one of Pardo's victims. ``We can't wait until Wednesday. I hope
he gets the chair.''
   Pardo, who testified he has read 500 books on Nazism, said he's
ready for the death penalty. ``I want to die. My life's over now,''
he said.
   ``I'm going to fight for his life, whether he wants me to or
not,'' Guralnick said.
</TEXT>
