<DOCNO> AP880416-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-88 0646EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AlbanyNewspaper     04-16 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Albany Newspaper,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Albany Newspaper Ends 145 Years of Publication</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Knickerbocker News published its final
edition in its 145-year history, topping it with a banner headline
that read ``We Say Farewell.''
   Capital Newspapers, which published the afternoon newspaper and
the morning Times-Union, blamed the death Friday of The
Knickerbocker News on declining circulation.
   Paid circulation for the last edition was 28,000, down from a
peak of almost 70,000 in 1973.
   The departure of The Knickerbocker News leaves New York state's
capital with only one newspaper.
   The Knick, as it was known locally, began publication in 1843 as
The Albany Knickerbocker. From 1879 to 1928, when the Gannett Co.
purchased it, the paper was known as The Knickerbocker Press. It
became The Knickerbocker News in 1937. The Hearst Corp., which owns
Capital Newspapers, purchased the newspaper in 1960.
   The nearly 40 staff members who worked only for the News will
join the Times-Union, which will become an all-day newspaper
Monday, officials said. The two newspapers shared personnel in
several departments.
   Four people were laid off as a result of The Knickerbocker News'
demise and 39 took voluntary retirement, said Publisher Joseph T.
Lyons.
   ``It is a strategic marketing decision,'' Lyons said. ``It is
somewhat sad to lose a newspaper and a flag. On the other hand,
looking ahead, we're going to be able to devote our talents to a
bigger, better newspaper to serve our readers better. It's sort of
a natural evolution.''
   Current and retired staff members gathered in the newsroom
Friday, and reminisced about their years with the paper, said
afternoon News Editor Warren Carlson.
   Carlson, a staff member for 31 years, said he was too busy with
his new duties to talk much about the old days.
   ``I'm looking more ahead than back,'' said Carlson, who now is
on the Times-Union's editorial page staff. ``It's too bad, but we
know these things happen. Some of the younger people, they take it
in stride. I can't get emotional now because it's kind of hectic
right now.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
