<1ST_LINE>u p AM-LaRoucheSupporter 1stLd-Writethru a0645 04-16 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-LaRouche Supporter, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0645,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LaRouche Supporter Stripped of Virtually All Power</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with party chairman stripped of virtually
all power. ADDS byline. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>BY RUTH RENDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The executive committee of Harris County's
Democratic Party on Friday stripped the newly elected chairman, a
supporter of political extremist Lyndon LaRouche, of virtually all
power.
   The committee, consisting of the 664 precinct chairmen, approved
by a quick voice vote final adoption of new party bylaws initially
passed March 11 in the aftershock of Claude Jones' stunning victory
over incumbent Larry Veselka.
   The bylaws were drafted within three days of Jones' election.
   Jones won the March 8 primary with 54,394 votes, or 51 percent,
to Vesekla's 51,318 votes, or 49 percent. Veselka, an attorney,
blamed his loss on not being able to campaign because of a trial he
was handling outside Houston.
   The new bylaws give powers to the party secretary that were
previously held by the chairman, including record-keeping and
managing party finances. The secretary will be elected May 2.
   About a half-dozen supporters of Jones carried picket signs
reading, ``Larry, don't be a sore loser'' and ``Will Harris County
executives reject majority rule?'' during the meeting.
   ``I kind of expected that it would be passed,'' Jones said. ``It
passed without a quorum, so you know what that tells you.''
   On Thursday, state District Judge Melinda Harmon denied without
comment a request from Jones to block the changes in bylaws. Jones
had argued that the rule changes will interfere with his statutory
duties.
   ``There have been numerous wild and paranoid statements, making
it very clear they will do everything they can to contain me,''
Jones said Thursday.
   Jones, 40, said Friday he did not know if the issue would be
taken back to court.
   Jones, who was defeated by Veselka in 1986, said his sole
occupation is working for LaRouche. He said he staffs solicitation
booths the LaRouche organization sponsors at airports and other
public places.
   Jones said he will back the Democratic presidential nominee
although he supports LaRouche, who has accused Queen Elizabeth of
drug trafficking and espouses a quarantine of AIDS patients.
</TEXT>
