<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua 5thLd-Writethru a0433 04-16 0794</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua, 5th Ld - Writethru, a0433,0815</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contras, Sandinistas Begin First High-Level Peace Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS graf after 2nd pvs, `The two ...' to UPDATE with
brief meeting, agreement to resume talks Saturday; picks up 3rd
pvs, `Adolfo Calero ... Minor editing to TRIM</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the Nicaraguan rebels met
arrived Friday night and began their first high-level peace talks
with the leftist government in an effort to end a war that is more
than six years old.
   The two sides began the long-awaited talks about two hours after
the Contras' arrival. None of the negotiators spoke to reporters as
they went into the meeting at the Camino Real Hotel, near the
airport about four miles north of the capital.
   The negotiators met for less than an hour and agreed to resume
discussions Saturday morning.
   Adolfo Calero, head of the rebels' umbrella group, the
Nicaraguan Resistance, led the delegation of more than 40 leaders,
which arrived on a commercial flight from San Jose, Costa Rica.
   The state-run Voice of Nicaragua, which carried details of the
rebels' arrival, said the delegation included Pedro Joaquin
Chamorro, Alfredo Cesar, Azucena Ferrey, her brother Roberto, and
Aristides Sanchez.
   It said relatives of the rebels gathered at Sandino
International Airport to see their family members, some of whom
have not been in Managua since 1979.
   Violetta Chamorro, co-owner of the opposition newspaper La
Prensa, waited with the others to see her son, Pedro Joaquin.
   The Contras also were met at the airport by Marta Sacasa,
spokeswoman for the rebels, and David Stadthagen and Jose Davila,
members of the Contra who had arrived on an earlier flight.
   The flight carrying Calero and the other leaders was delayed by
more than four hours.
   Earlier Friday, leftist youths pelted the La Prensa building
with rocks. About 300 teen-agers demonstrated outside the building.
They said they were members of a group called Sandinista Youth and
were protesting the paper's support of the Contras.
   Witnesses who insisted on anonymity said a young man was
slightly injured by a pail thrown from the roof of the building.
   La Prensa is about two miles from Managua's Sandino
International Airport and near the hotel where the Contra
delegation was to stay.
   The Interior Ministry immediately banned all demonstrations and
alcohol sales around the airport and hotel and closed the main road
to the airport.
   The high-level talks could set the stage for an end to the war
that has claimed more than 26,000 lives since it began in November
1981, according to the government.
   Agreement on the technical issues of a cease-fire was reached
during talks that ended Friday in the southern border post of
Sapoa, 90 miles from Managua, and the two sides agreed to further
technical talks at the high-level meetings.
   Details of the Sapoa talks were not made public immediately, but
in a joint communique Friday the Contra and Sandinista delegates
said ``considerable progress'' had been made on reconciling earlier
differences.
   A tenuous, 60-day cease-fire has been in force since April 1, as
part of an accord the two sides reached in earlier Sapoa talks
March 23. Under that agreement, the U.S.-backed Contras would
gather in cease-fire zones until a permanent truce was negotiated.
   But the two sides were unable to agree on important technical
issues such as verification, how the rebels would be resupplied or
whether they should be allowed to keep their weapons.
   As part of the deal, the leftist Sandinistas released 100 of the
3,200 political prisoners and rebels they hold and pledged to
release the rest gradually as the Contras gather in the cease-fire
zones.
   But the entire process has been marked by bickering, with each
side accusing the other of violating the accord.
   Contra leaders have also accused the Sandinistas of releasing
only 10 of the prisoners they wanted freed, but the Sandinistas
claimed the agreement did not specify names.
   Each side threatened to cancel the talks several times. But by
Friday they finally were able to compromise on most points.
   Friday's talks in Managua mark the first time since the war
began that the Sandinistas have allowed Contra leaders to openly
come to Managua.
   Apparently, the toughest unresolved issue concerns weapons. The
Sandinistas have insisted the rebels give up their weapons before
they can participate in the country's political activities.
   Some Contra leaders say they will never disarm and others say
they will do so only when the Nicaragua moves to democracy.
   Contra leaders claim they have about 10,000 rebels under arms.
The Sandinistas claim they have an armed force of 300,000 men and
women, including an 80,000-man army.
   The cease-fire is called for under a Central American peace plan
written by Costa Rica's President Oscar Arias.
</TEXT>
