<HEAD>Blood Pressure Guidelines Urge Lowest Effective Doses Of
Medication</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Updated federal guidelines on treating high
blood pressure place new emphasis on prescribing the lowest
effective doses of medication.
   The guidelines, issued Friday by a federal advisory panel, are
based on an eight-month review of the latest research and they
update recommendations last issued four years ago. They are
intended primarily for physicians.
   Abram V. Chobanian, incoming dean of the Boston University
School of Medicine, said two new classes of drugs _ so-called
calcium antagonists and enzyme inhibitors _ have been approved for
treating high blood pressure since the last report.
   But Chobanian emphasized that the updated guidelines call for
``lower initial doses for most drugs than we did in 1984.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Judge Places Restrictions On Classified Iran-Contra Documents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge in the Iran-Contra trial says he
will give defendants, lawyers and witnesses access to classified
documents only on a ``need-to-know'' basis.
   U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell on Friday issued a
nine-page order governing the handling of some 300,000 classified
documents expected to be turned over to the defense by prosecutor
Lawrence Walsh.
   Access will be granted on a ``need-to-know'' basis and the
defendants, their lawyers and witnesses must sign an agreement not
to make unauthorized disclosures of the information contained in
the documents, Gesell said.
   Marine Lt. Col. Oliver L. North and former national security
adviser John M. Poindexter are accused of conspiring with arms
dealers Albert Hakim and retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Richard V.
Secord to divert profits illegally from the U.S.-Iran arms sales to
the Nicaraguan Contra rebels.
</TEXT>
