<HEAD>California Food Books To Receive Illegally Imported Fish</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California food banks are to be the recipient
of some 78,000 pounds of frozen salmon seized last year after being
imported from Japan and then relabeled as a product of the United
States.
   The National Marine Fisheries Service said Friday that after
inspecting the illegally imported salmon and clearing it for human
consumption, the agency decided to donate it for use in shelters,
day-care centers, soup kitchens and senior centers.
   About 26,000 pounds of salmon will go to the Los Angeles
Regional Food Bank and 52,000 pounds will be divided by the San
Francisco and Santa Clara County food banks. The salmon was seized
at cold storage plants in Oakland, Riverside and Watsonville.
