<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AsianDrugs 1stLd-Writethru a0416 04-16 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Asian Drugs, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0416,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arrests Show Asian Gangs Filling Void Left By Mafia, Officials Say</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, bgng: ``Cracking the ...'' to show arrests
occurred Friday.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal officials say the roundup of 20 people
in Hong Kong and the United States in the breakup of a Chinese
heroin importation ring reflects the growing influence of Asian
criminal gangs.
   Drug-importing Asian criminal gangs ``are moving in to fill the
void'' left by the successful prosecution of Sicilian Mafia members
in the United States, FBI Director William Sessions said in a
statement Friday.
   Cracking the Chinese heroin ring with a series of arrests Friday
ended a two-year undercover probe called Operation Bamboo Dragon
that was launched after federal agents were told a restaurant owner
in the Chinatown section of Washington was buying stolen firearms
and distributing cocaine.
   Eleven people were arrested in Hong Kong and nine in the United
States as investigators seized 137 pounds of heroin worthover $100
million.
   Five of those arrested in New York were charged with conspiring
to supply 1,000 M-16 military rifles to undercover federal agents
and to provide false documents so that the rifles could be shipped
to Libya, said the U.S. Customs Service and the Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms.
   ``This gang was capable of putting enormous firepower into the
hands of terrorists and drug smugglers,'' Customs commissioner
William von Raab said in a statement. Federal officials said at a
news conference that the ring had supplied 600 handguns, mostly to
Chinese gangs.
   The FBI and ATF inserted undercover operatives into the
operation, including a Chinese-speaking agent who portrayed himself
as a drug dealer.
   The Cantonese-speaking federal agent, Frederick Yau, met with
gang members in Washington and Hong Kong to negotiate the purchase
of heroin from Asia.
   The heroin came from Burma and China and was transported to San
Francisco and New York City's Chinatown. It also was distributed to
Newark, N.J., Alexandria, Va., and Washington.
   U.S. members of the ring were selling hundreds of stolen or
illegally obtained pistols, machine guns and rifles on the streets
of New York City, usually to Chinese gangs.
   Many of the firearms were obtained with fraudulent
identification documents from gun shops in Fort Worth, Dallas and
Houston, Texas, the officials said.
   The Chinese gangs were buying AR-15 semi-automatic rifles _ the
civilian version of the Army's M-16 rifle _ and converting them
into fully automatic M-16s.
   Customs and ATF undercover agents bought 10 weapons from the
five people charged in New York City and ordered 1,000 more M-16s
that were to be delivered to Libya. Such shipments would have
violated the Arms Export Control Act, which sets up federal
licensing procedures for the sale of weapons to foreign countries.
   The Drug Enforcement Administration was a major participant in
the probe, law enforcement officials said at a news conference in
Washington announcing the arrests.
</TEXT>
