<HEAD>Gephardt Sees Issues Still Alive, Ponders Support</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Richard Gephardt, returning to a
state which gave his Democratic presidential campaign a short-lived
boost, insisted his issues still are potent but said he may back
another candidate ``in the near future.''
   The Missouri congressman mingled with legislators at the
Statehouse and backers at a reception Friday as he thanked Iowa
Democratic activists who handed him a victory in the Feb. 8
precinct caucuses.
   The campaign went downhill after that and Gephardt dropped from
the race. Still, Gephardt insisted his get-tough talk on trade
touches a chord with Americans.
   ``Even though we didn't get the results we wanted later in the
contest, especially on Super Tuesday, the issues we stood for ...
are still out there,'' Gephardt said. ``I believe they are issues
the American people care about.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PULASKI, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of Tennessee's largest black
political organization is calling on Sen. Albert Gore Jr. to
release his delegates unless Gore gets 20 percent of the vote in
New York's presidential primary.
   James Brown, who has headed the Tennessee Voters' Council since
1985, said Friday that Jesse Jackson would get most of Gore's
416.55 publicly committed delegates if Gore released them.
   Gore campaign spokesman Arly Schardt said Gore was a ``very
viable and serious contender for the Democratic nomination'' and
had no intention of releasing his delegates.
   Brown said the TVC, long active in Tennessee Democratic
politics, sent a telegram to Gore asking him ``to make a commitment
to release his delegates without any lingering conditions if he
fails to get 20 percent of the New York popular vote on Tuesday.''
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis has 845.15 delegates, while
Jackson has 730.1 of the 2,082 delegates required to nominate the
party's candidate at the Democratic National Convention in July.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Celeste Says PAC No Sign of National Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Richard Celeste says he organized a
federal political action committee to get young people more
involved in politics, not to launch a national political race in
the near future.
   ``This is an effort to get people to participate more
effectively in politics,'' Celeste said Friday after returning from
an overseas trade mission.
   The Columbus Dispatch reported a committee called Participation
2000 had raised more than $60,000 in the last three months. The
committee, Celeste said, was not formed to back other Democrats in
elections this fall.
   ``I think this is going to focus particularly on involving young
people in the political process,'' he said.
   Jerry M. Hultin, the committee's treasurer, said the committee
will help minority, women, and progressive Democratic candidates.
   ``It's not centered on Dick as a candidate. It's centered on
public policy and political issues,'' said Alex Shumate, a trustee
of the committee.
