<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-88 0231EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Panama Bjt   04-16 0800</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama, Bjt,0823</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Days Later, U.S Sergeant Describes Alleged Intrusion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAULINE JELINEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A veteran U.S. Marine sergeant's
account of his company's alleged firefight with mysterious
intruders at a fuel depot near Panama City has left unanswered a
number of major questions.
   Foremost among them: Who were the ``highly professional''
intruders he said moved in military formations, wore dark uniforms,
carried sophisticated night-vision equipment and were ``trying to
provoke'' the Marines?
   First Sgt. Alexander J. Nevglovski declined to speculate Friday
on whether the intruders he said he and his men engaged in a
two-hour firefight Tuesday night were Panamanian soldiers.
   But, asked to assess the motives and actions of intruders he
said appeared Monday and Tuesday night at the Arraijan Tank Farm
near Howard Air Force Base, the 24-year Marine veteran replied:
   ``They were training. They were using us for training aides.
They were harassing us. They were very provoking. They were
basically using us as training aides, to see how they can get
around and how they can't get around, to see how they can get
detected and how they can't get detected.''
   Col. Ron Sconyers, chief spokesman for the U.S. Southern
Command, said a full investigation into the two incidents was still
under way and results would not be available for at least another
day or two.
   He said Nevglovski spoke to reporters in light of skeptical
reports in U.S. newspapers and ridicule from the Panamanian
government.
   Panama's military has described the Marines as inexperienced
troops who were ``shooting at swaying palm trees.''
   A Pentagon spokesman told reporters in Washington Tuesday that
intruders at the depot Monday night appeared to belong to Panama's
Defense Forces, which are commanded by the country's de facto
leader, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   A Marine corporal was killed in that incident, when he and 11
other members of his patrol tried to surround what Nevglovski
described as a group of eight intruders.
   U.S. officials said the corporal was accidentally shot by fellow
Marines.
   The Reagan administration has been trying for months to oust
Noriega, who was indicted on drug trafficking charges in Florida
two months ago. But a series of economic sanctions that have
crippled Panama's economy have failed to budge the general.
   Also Friday, Panama sent a formal protest to the United Nations
alleging U.S. troops violated its sovereignty by closing a highway
just outside the capital for three hours Tuesday night after the
alleged firefight began.
   Nevglovski told of two separate firefights Tuesday night, one
involving him and about 90 other Marines, the other involving eight
Marines and a sailor surrounded on a hill about a half mile away.
   He said he and other Marines were called to reinforce a patrol
that first sighted about 12 intruders at a fuel storage depot
shortly before sundown Tuesday. The sergeant said he later
personally counted about 40 of the unidentified men, all wearing
black uniforms.
   ``They were highly professional,'' said the sergeant, who
arrived in Panama from Camp Lejeune, N.C., last week as part of a
1,300-man U.S. military build-up. ``They were good at what they
did.''
   While Nevglovski said he had the intruders almost constantly in
view with a night-vision device, ``I didn't see a weapon on them. I
can't say why. We could see them clearly.''
   The sergeant said at least 12 of the intruders were standing in
plain view atop one of the 36 underground fuel storage tanks in the
807-acre reserve, which is only partially fenced.
   Nevglovski said he not only did not see the intruders carrying
any weapons, he could not guess what they used to open fire.
   ``We received the first three rounds and our (return) fire
lasted about 15 minutes,'' the sergeant said. ``What I could
identify was three or four (muzzle) flashes coming from a certain
area.
   ``At that time I immediately went to my machine gunner and
tapped him on the shoulder and told him to return fire,''
Nevglovski said. ``He returned fire, approximately 10 or 15
rounds.''
   Nevglovski said the intruders were headed toward his position
``in three different directions as they came down, as if to make an
encirclement. All along they had been harassing us, trying to
provoke us to open fire. But we held our ground and once we were
fired upon, we returned fire.''
   Nevglovski also said the Marines did not chase the intruders
into surrounding jungle because a month or so earlier ``two Air
Force MPs (military policemen) chased an intruder into the jungle
and one was hacked to death with a machete and the other was cut up
pretty bad.''
   No such incident has been announced by the Southern Command, and
military spokesman later said the sergeant had repeated a rumor
that had no basis in fact.
</TEXT>
