<1ST_LINE>u a PM-SamTheSham Bjt   04-16 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sam The Sham, Bjt,0531</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Rocker Turns To The Lord</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sam Samudio, who gained fame during the
1960s as leader of Sam the Sham and the Pharohs, says he fled rock
'n' roll to work anonymously in offshore oil fields because fast
living had drained him.
   Today, the 51-year-old composer and performer of the 1965 hit
``Wooly Bully'' preaches on the streets of Memphis.
   ``God is not in the throwaway business. He's in the renewal
business,'' Samudio said this week. ``We have a little trailer we
pull behind a pickup and we just pick a corner.''
   Samudio spends Sundays at a shelter for transients, visits
convicts in prison and preaches with a loosely organized group
called Gideon's Few, comprised largely of former drug users,
lawbreakers and ruffians.
   The group hits the rougher parts of town. On a recent outing,
the target was a residence believed to be a house of ill-fame.
   ``We went and set up on the other corner from them and just
began to share the Gospel,'' Samudio said.
   He said a life of alcohol, drugs and fast living had left him
emotionally and physically drained, and that he sat at a lonesome
Texas crossroads and prayed for a direction.
   ``I said which way do I go, Lord. Which way do I go?'' Samudio
recalled. ``It wasn't a booming voice, though God can speak in any
way he wants, but he impressed on me to go south, to head for the
water.''
   In 1979, he found work as a deckhand on an oilfield supply boat
and eventually worked his way up to crewboat captain.
   Samudio avoided telling co-workers about his rock past. He was
startled when a co-worker once stumbled up and said, ``Well, Sam
The Sham.''
   ``I said, `Why'd you call me that?' He was drunk and he said,
`Why man, didn't you ever hear of Sam The Sham? He was a rock 'n'
roll star. He died in a plane crash.'''
   Today, Samudio lives in a comfortable, working class
neighborhood with his fourth wife, Ann, and 8-year-old daughter,
Brisa. Two grown sons from a previous marriage live in other states.
   His living comes mostly from royalties for songs he has written
or recorded, as a solo artist or with ``The Pharaohs.'' Samudio
said his last major commercial job was writing two songs for ``The
Border,'' a 1982 movie starring Jack Nicholson.
   Samudio is working on a gospel album with a local group called
``The Ambassadors for Christ,'' but says the project is moving at
its own pace since it isn't aimed at making money.
   He said he recently turned down a $40,000 offer to sing ``Wooly
Bully'' for a TV wine commercial.
   Samudio explained that his ministry would suffer if he appeared
to be looking for material riches.
   ``If I go to a prison, it only takes about 30 seconds for the
people in a prison to clock you,'' he said. ``If I'm not for real,
I won't be able to fool them, and I certainly can't fool God.''
</TEXT>
