<2ND_LINE>PM-Turnpike Explosives,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FBI Agents Head to Italy To Investigate Possible Links to Bombing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-USO Bombing, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McMAHON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   FBI agents will travel to Italy to
investigate possible links between the bombing of a USO Club in
Naples and a Japanese man arrested with three powerful bombs in New
Jersey, a law enforcement source said.
   Yu Kikumura, 35, is believed by the Japanese Foreign Ministry to
have ties to the leftist Red Army, a terrorist group linked to the
bombing which killed a U.S. servicewoman and four Italians.
   A federal magistrate here on Friday ordered Kikumura held
without bail. Kikumura was arrested by state troopers Tuesday after
being found with three sophisticated homemade bombs in his car.
   In Washington, a law enforcement source speaking on condition of
anonymity said an FBI bomb squad is on its way to Italy to
investigate whether the explosives used in the Naples bombing
Thursday match those found in New Jersey.
   FBI spokesman Ray McElhaney refused to confirm the report, but
said ``we have offered forensic and other cooperative services to
the Italian law enforcement authorities'' in connection with the
Naples bombing. He declined to elaborate.
   A terrorist task force composed of state police, FBI and U.S.
Secret Service agents is investigating Kikumura's background and is
trying to determine where he was headed when he was arrested,
authorities said.
   U.S. Attorney Samuel A. Alito Jr. on Friday refused to comment
on indications that Kikumura is linked to the Red Army.
   Kikumura was arrested on the New Jersey Turnpike after a state
trooper stopped him for a routine motor vehicles violation and
found the bombs in his car.
   A state judge on Thursday released Kikumura into the custody of
federal authorities, who charged him with using a fraudulent visa
to enter the country and possession of unregistered firearms, the
explosives.
   FBI Agent Robert J. Heckman, an explosives expert leading the
investigation, described the bombs found in Kikumura's car as
``anti-personnel'' devices. Two thirds of the 18-inch containers
were packed with gunpowder and the rest with steel pellets, a
mixture that, when detonated, could blow up an average home, he
said.
</TEXT>
