<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Visitor'sNightmare     04-16 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Visitor's Nightmare,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Irish Girl Returns Home after `Miraculous' Recovery from Coma</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wearing a cast and a smile, a young Irish woman
bade farewell to the country that adopted her after a St. Patrick's
Day traffic accident that put her in a coma for 10 days.
   ``I feel great, as though I haven't changed a bit,'' Margaret
Hanley, 22, said in an interview Friday shortly before leaving for
Ireland.
   Miss Hanley said she would take time while convalescing to
answer the nearly 600 letters she received from well-wishers who
heard of her plight, some as far away as New Mexico.
   After tearful goodbyes and laden with gifts, Miss Hanley left
Weiss Memorial Hospital with her parents a month later than she had
planned but much sooner than doctors and well-wishers had dared
hope.
   ``It was a miraculous recovery,'' said Dr. Richard Bigg, a
surgeon who headed the team that treated Ms. Hanley. ``Everyone is
absolutely amazed.''
   The black-haired aspiring actress came to Chicago in February to
see her boyfriend, Daniel Stokes, who is jailed on murder and armed
robbery charges in the death of his landlord.
   But she was hit by a car March 17, a day before she planned to
return to Dublin, and suffered a fractured leg and hip.
   Stokes, who has pleaded innocent, says the couple met in Dublin,
where Miss Hanley was working as an actress for his father's
theater company.
   ``I remember getting hit,'' Ms. Hanley said late Thursday. ``But
to tell you the truth, since I woke up, I don't remember a thing
about it, except I think I told the people (in the ambulance), `I
can't stay overnight _ I have to go home tomorrow.'''
   Before reaching the hospital, she slipped into a coma. Doctors
said later that the broken leg created a blockage in blood vessels
carrying oxygen to her brain.
   Her parents rushed to Chicago from Dublin and were at her
bedside 26 of her 29 days in the hospital.
   They kept a round-the-clock hospital vigil while she was
comatose, playing tapes of Irish folk music and tape-recorded
messages from her 13 brothers and sisters.
   Shortly before Easter, Ms. Hanley awoke.
   Reports of the cash-strapped family's plight brought an
outpouring of support from the local Irish community and readers
around the country.
   ``I couldn't believe it,'' Ms. Hanley said. ``I thought I was
just another tourist, but these people have been so nice.''
   A nurse accompanied Ms. Hanley on the return trip to Ireland at
the hospital's expense, and will help her develop an exercise
regimen to strengthen her broken leg.
   ``Everybody's been wonderful, but we miss our kids,'' said her
mother, Ann Hanley, reached at O'Hare International Airport as she,
her husband, Stephen, and their daughter prepared to leave for New
York and a connecting flight to Ireland.
   ``And to tell you the truth,'' Mrs. Hanley said. ``We could do
without all the excitement.''
</TEXT>
