<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-Politics     04-16 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Politics,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troops Raid Another Suspected Honasan Hideout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops raided the suspected hideout
of the fugitive leader of last August's coup attempt after
capturing 10 followers and foiling a plot to seize the presidential
palace, military officials said today. Former Lt. Col. Gregorio
Honasan was not in the hideout, an automobile repair shop in
suburban Quezon City. But authorities seized a motorcycle and
military uniforms believed used by Honasan, the officials said.
   The raids came late Friday as the military was on nationwide
alert against any coup attempt while President Corazon Aquino was
visiting China.
   Military officials, meanwhile, questioned the 10 Honasan
followers arrested in a nearby home. A broadcast executive who owns
the house where they were captured denied any links to the
renegades.
   Officials claimed Friday's raids in Quezon City foiled a plan by
Honasan and his followers to attack the presidential palace.
   Col. Emiliano Templo, commander of the raiding party, said the
plotters planned to approach the palace by rubber boats down a
tributary of the Pasig River which flows behind the palace in the
heart of Manila.
   But the military was tipped off about the plot, ``so we acted
quickly,'' Templo said. ``We pre-empted the plan.''
   Honasan led the Aug. 28 coup in which 53 people were killed and
more than 300 others wounded, including Mrs. Aquino's only son,
Benigno Aquino III.
   In Beijing today, Mrs. Aquino told reporters she was ``very
happy'' to learn of the arrests. She arrived in Hong Kong soon
after on a one-day visit.
   Honasan was arrested in December but escaped April 2 from a navy
prison ship with the help of 14 guards from an elite navy group
trained in demolition and commando attacks. Eight of those arrested
Friday were his guards. The two others were civilians.
   Lt. Anselmo Cabingan, a military spokesman, declined to give
details of the raid on the shop, but the government's television
station quoted officials as saying they believed Honasan had used a
small room there as his sleeping quarters since his escape.
   The station said that, in addition to the motorcycle, the
raiders seized black military uniforms and a gadget used in
reloading bullets.
   The shop is near the house where Honasan's followers were
arrested in suburban Quezon City.
   Officials said the group offered no resistance although they
were found in possession of 16 M-14 rifles, four M-16s, one light
machine gun, five Israeli-made Uzi machine guns, and a grenade
launcher.
   The house were they were captured belonged to Ildefonso
``Butch'' Canoy, a vice president of the Radio Mindanao Network,
one of the country's largest private broadcasting companies.
   Canoy was vacationing in New York and could not be contacted for
comment. But his network's news manager said Canoy denied any links
to Honasan's group and was surprised to hear of the raid on his
house.
   ``I talked to him by telephone and he was just as surprised as
we were,'' Mike Enriquez told The Associated Press. ``We fell off
our chairs when our guys (reporters at the scene) asked whose house
it was and were told it was Butch Canoy's.''
   He said he asked Canoy if he had given anybody permission to use
his house or if he knew that dissident soldiers were using it, and
he said ``No.''
   Canoy is related to opposition politician Reuben Canoy, who has
been advocating self-rule for the southern island Mindanao.
</TEXT>
