<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Eastern     04-16 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Eastern,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Inspectors Temporarily Ground 15 Planes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD W. SWINTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal inspectors grounded at least 15 Eastern
Airlines planes for safety violations, said Machinists union
officials who vowed to derail a company plan to delay announcements
on additional repair problems.
   In addition to the 15, the airline pulled five planes from
service at Washington National Airport on Friday to repair problems
found during federal inspections, said Jim Hare, Eastern station
manager at National.
   The problems with the five planes included such things as oil
leaks and worn seat belts, but none presented a safety threat,
Eastern officials said.
   However, Eastern management ordered the planes pulled because of
the intense scrutiny of Eastern by the Department of
Transportation, Hare said.
   The latest temporary groundings ordered by the Federal Aviation
Administration were in Kansas City, Mo.; Boston, St. Louis,
Tallahassee and Atlanta, union spokesmen said.
   About 400 passengers were stranded when three flights to Boston
were canceled. Two of the grounded planes had been scheduled to be
used as backups for other flights.
   Eastern and Federal Aviation Administration officials refused to
continue listing the number of planes temporarily grounded.
   ``They didn't want to see a running box score,'' FAA spokesman
John Leyden said of his department's policy change after two days.
``We'll summarize it at the end of the inspection.''
   But members of the Machinists union continued to keep the tally,
counting eight more safety violations Friday that temporarily put
planes out of service.
   ``They're calling in from around the country,'' said a union
spokesman who spoke on condition that he not be identified.
   Eastern Machinists union District President Charles E. Bryan
issued a bulletin to Eastern's 12,000 machinists urging them to
report threats some employees have said they received from
management after speaking voluntarily with FAA inspectors.
   Bryan said Eastern's sister airline, Continental, has even worse
safety problems. There are an estimated 1,000 ``minimum equipment
list'' safety violations at Continental, he said.
   Eastern and Continental are owned by Texas Air Corp., which
Bryan has repeatedly accused of skimping on maintenance.
   ``Mr. Bryan continues to spout the kind of rhetoric that he has
maintained for the many years, even prior to Texas Air's
acquisition of of Eastern,'' said Texas Air spokesman Bruce Hicks
in Houston. ``It would appear that Mr. Bryan knows as little about
the operations of Continental as he does about Eastern.''
</TEXT>
