<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-88 0743EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FootKiss     04-16 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Foot Kiss,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parent Outraged Over Hearing of Teacher's Ultimatum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIMAS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gym teacher demanded her students
either run a lap around a school track or kiss her foot, according
to an angry mother who wants an apology and the instructor fired.
   Sherry Schluter said her son was one of only three students in
the class who choose to jog during the physical education class
April 8.
   ``The only time my son should have to kiss someone's foot is
when his life is being threatened,'' Mrs. Schluter said during a
Bonita Unified School District board meeting in this city about 25
miles east of Los Angeles.
   A complaint filed by Mrs. Schluter contends Kathy Stewart, an
instructor at Lone Hill Intermediate School in San Dimas, gave her
seventh-grade class the ultimatum: run or kiss.
   ``I'd like to see her apologize to the students and parents and
be terminated,'' Mrs. Schluter added at the Wednesday night meeting.
   Neither Ms. Stewart nor Adolphus D. Carter, principal of the
sixth through eighth grade Lone Hill school, returned phone calls
Friday seeking comment. Carter's secretary said they would have no
comment.
   District officials are investigating, said interim
Superintendent Mitchell Gilbert.
   Ms. Schluter told the board that other parents told her Ms.
Stewart ordered students in a gym class last year to kiss her hand
if they sought permission to use the restroom.
   ``Some of the kids took it as a joke. Some were humiliated, and
some were afraid it would affect their grades,'' Mrs. Schluter said.
   ``Last year it was her hand. This year it was her foot. Who
knows what it will be next?'' said Mrs. Schluter's husband, David.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
