<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-88 0751EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     04-16 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mark Twain is associated with Mississippi
River steamboats, but that hasn't stopped Amtrak from using him to
promote the passenger rail service's newest train car.
   Roger Durrett, 37, will impersonate Twain today and Sunday at
the Amtrak terminal in New Orleans as part of Amtrak's new
equipment exhibition.
   Durrett, who began studying Twain at age 17, was chosen to help
promote Amtrak and its new equipment because the author loved to
travel.
   Two-level diners, sleepers, coaches, lounges and other amenities
are new additions to Amtrak's Superliner.
   The Viewliner, a diner on display, is now being tested by Amtrak.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW ALBANY, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rose is a rose for some purposes, but
not when it comes to those used on the blanket awarded to the
winner of the Kentucky Derby.
   Kroger Inc., which makes the famed blanket of roses draped over
the Derby winner each May, has commissioned a hybridizer here to
develop the perfect bud.
   ``The garland of roses for the winner of the Kentucky Derby is
the most prestigious floral arrangement in the world,'' said Ben
Harper, Kroger's Kentucky advertising manager. ``We feel it is
important for the Kentucky Derby to have its own rose.''
   Hybridizer Von C. Weddle, 76, said finding the perfect Derby
rose may take three to five years.
   ``I hope I live so long,'' Weddle said. ``It would be a great
honor if I could get it done.''
   The rose must redefine brilliant red, Harper said. It has to be
large because it takes 550 roses to cover the blanket, which is 14
feet long and 21 inches wide. And it must be hardy because after
the roses are sewn into the blanket's satin backing, it sits for
five to six hours at Churchill Downs before it is presented to the
winner, he said.
   The rose must also be able to grow in a hothouse because a plant
that grows outdoors would not bloom in time for the Derby in the
event of a long winter.
   In his 37-year career as a rose breeder, Weddle has created 25
different varieties, including one named for Elizabeth Taylor.
</TEXT>
