<HEAD>Wintery Cold Sweeps Through the Northeast</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT, Lake George and Saratoga sted Lake
Georgia and Sarasota</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A low-pressure system funneling through New England today
produced a chilling combination of rain and snow, dumping snow from
the Great Lakes to Vermont.
   A winter storm watch was posted for Vermont, the Adirondacks,
Champlain Valley, Lake George and the Saratoga region of New York,
where up to 6 inches of snow were expected today. In northern Ohio,
up to an 1{ inches of snow fell on Cleveland Friday night.
   Freeze advisories were in effect for southwestern Ohio, northern
Kentucky and most of central and part of northwestern Indiana this
morning. Frost advisories also were in effect for southern Indiana
and northern Kentucky.
   Meanwhile, a low-pressure system in the Southwest produced
showers and thundershowers in Arizona and New Mexico early today.
Thunderstorms on Friday caused a power outage at Wickenburg, Ariz.
Full power was restored this morning, police said.
   Scattered showers early today fell along the northern Pacific
coast, while isolated showers and thunderstorms lingered in
northern Idaho. Central Arkansas and eastern North Carolina also
had scattered showers. Fog reduced visibility to near zero at some
spots in the Tennessee Valley.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from the
southern Rockies into western and central areas fo Texas; rain or
snow across the upper Ohio Valley into western New York and across
coastal parts of New England; snow from eastern New York into
interior sections of New England.
   Highs will be in the 60s or 70s across much of the nation; 30s
across central New England; 40s from the eastern Great Lakes into
the upper Ohio Valley and southern and coastal New England; 50s
from the central Great Lakes through the lower Ohio Valley into the
mid Atlantic states; low 80s along the western Gulf Coast and the
southern half of the Florida Peninsula.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 26
degrees at Bradford, Pa., to 72 degrees at Brownsville, Texas.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 48 fair; Boston 40 windy; Buffalo 32 partly
cloudy; Charleston, S.C. 57 partly cloudy; Cincinnati 41 cloudy;
Cleveland 32 partly cloudy; Detroit 34 cloudy; Miami 64 fair; New
York 40 cloudy; Philadelphia 40 fair; Pittsburgh 31 snow; Portland,
Maine 33 rain; Washington 41 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 36 fair; Chicago 37 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
64 partly cloudy; Denver 49 fair; Des Moines 37 fair; Indianapolis
39 cloudy; Kansas City 39 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 36 fair;
Nashville 36 fair; New Orleans 61 fair; St. Louis 42 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 58 windy; Anchorage 38 rain; Las Vegas 50
showers; Los Angeles 55 fair; Phoenix 55 cloudy; Salt Lake City 50
fair; San Diego 58 partly cloudy; San Francisco 53 windy; Seattle
58 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 36 partly cloudy; Toronto 28 fair.
</TEXT>
