<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Indonesia-Condoms     04-16 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Indonesia-Condoms,0185</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>144 Million Condoms Ordered From Indonesia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indonesia has signed a contract to
provide 144 million condoms to Western European countries to
prevent the spread of AIDS, an official of the National Family
Planning Coordinating Board said today.
   Sutejo Mulyodiharjo, deputy head of operational activities of
the board, said the condoms would not be used within the framework
of a family planning program. They will be used to prevent AIDS
from spreading.
   He said the order came from the European Economic Community.
   Sutejo did not say how Indonesia would produce the condoms.
   Its only condom factory has a capacity of slightly less than 144
million condoms a year. Sutejo said the factory now produces around
29 million condoms a year to meet Indonesia's domestic needs.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by viruses that
cripple the victim's immune system, rendering it vulnerable to
infections and cancer.
   It is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or
syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products,
and from pregnant women to their offspring.
</TEXT>
