<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Beating     04-16 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Beating,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinese Reporter Beaten by Security Guards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chinese television reporter was beaten by
security guards while covering a flower show, a newspaper said
today in a rare report on the activities of Chinese police.
   The Worker's Daily said Zhang Jianhua, a reporter for a
television station in Henan province was in a park just before its
annual peony show when four security guards surrounded him.
   The report said an argument ensued, but it did not say why the
guards stopped the reporter.
   Zhang showed the guards his press credentials, but one of the
guards said, ``It doesn't matter who you are.''
   One guard whipped him with a belt while another hit him over the
head with his baton. Zhang immediately collapsed, but the four
guards continued beating him.
   As they were dragging him by the collar to the park police
station, a police officer demanded that Zhang be tied up, but
several other reporters intervened.
   The paper said Zhang suffered a concussion. It did not say
whether the guards were arrested.
   News organizations in Luoyang called for respect for reporters'
rights and guarantee for reporters' safety, the report said.
   Chinese papers rarely report incidents that raise questions
about the activities of its police. The report today was unusual
because it did just that.
</TEXT>
