<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Pakistan-Clash     04-16 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pakistan-Clash,0206</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven Dead, 17 Wounded In Clash Between Tribesmen And Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A clash between local tribesmen and
paramilitary police in northwest Pakistan has left seven people
dead and 17 others injured, reports said today.
   The official news agency APP and the newspaper Frontier Post in
Peshawar said the fighting between Kukikhel tribesmen and
Pakistan's Frontier Constabulary occurred Friday near the Khyber
pass into Afghanistan.
   APP said the fighting broke out when troopers tried to dislodge
about 3,000 tribesmen who had occupied and set up barricades on
territory controlled by the military.
   The Frontier Post said the Kukikhel action was a protest over
the contabulary's attempt to set up a post in the tribal area,
which usually is self-ruled and off limits to Pakistani police.
   Neither report said whether all the dead were civilians, but the
newspaper said at least three of those seriously wounded were
constables.
   It said the paramilitary force used artillery and mortar fire in
its attempt to oust the tribesmen, who responded with automatic
weapons fire.
   Family feuds and other clashes are frequent in Pakistan's
volatile tribal areas. Nearly all men carry guns, the most popular
being Soviet Kalshnikov assault rifles.
</TEXT>
