<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Afghanistan-Guerrillas     04-16 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan-Guerrillas,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghan Guerrillas And Refugees Denounce Geneva Accord</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   By KATHY GANNON=
   PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) _ About 75,000 Afghan guerrillas and
refugees jammed into a sun-baked stadium today to denounce the
Geneva accord that paves the way for a Soviet troop withdrawal from
Afghanistan.
   One by one, the seven leaders of the Islamic Unity of Afghan
Mujahedeen vowed to keep on fighting until the last Soviet soldier
is gone and they have toppled Kabul's communist government.
   Resistance leaders have said they would reject any peace
agreement reached without their participation.
   The United States, the Soviet Union, Pakistan and Afghanistan
signed an agreement on Thursday that calls for Soviet troops to
begin leaving Afghanistan on May 15.
   In Islamabad, Pakistan's acting foreign minister returned from
Geneva today and predicted that Afghanistan's communist government
will fall quickly after the Soviet withdrawal.
   ``I do not have any doubt about it. (The Kabul government) has
been rejected by the people of Afghanistan,'' Zain Noorani was
quoted as saying by the official news agency APP.
   Noorani said Afghan anti-communist guerrillas control more than
80 percent of the country.
   Afghanistan's Marxist leader, Najib, has acknowledged that
Soviet-Afghan forces are weak in the Afghanistan countryside.
   In Peshawar, Ahmed Shah, a guerrilla designated by the alliance
to head an all-rebel interim government, stood in the 95-degree
heat and told the refugees his administration would soon move
inside Afghanistan. He gave no deadline.
   ``We'll stay with you in Afghanistan, in the caves and snow, not
in Pakistan,'' he said. An interpreter translated his remarks into
English.
   Three rows of turbaned, gun-toting Afghans stood in front of the
stage.
   A guard at the rear of the stage fainted. Outside the grounds, a
camel lay dead.
   Gulbaddin Hekmatyar, a hardline guerrilla leader and current
chairman of the alliance, told the crowd the Geneva agreement
provided for the return of about 5 million Afghan refugees from
Pakistan and Iran.
   The black-bearded Hekmatyar asked for a show of hands of those
who would wait until the last Soviet was gone to return. Virtually
all hands went up.
   The leader of one of the more moderate guerrilla parties
threatened to boycott the rally if Hekmatyar tried to get a vote of
confidence for the proposed all-rebel government.
   Sibghatullah Mojaddedi recently resigned from the alliance, then
later rejoined it, in protest over the plan which he said was the
work of the hardline Moslem majority.
   Mojaddedi's Afghan National Liberation Front also is the only
alliance party to welcome the Geneva accord as flawed but useful.
   The hardliners say the accord is a sellout because the United
States failed to secure a cutoff of Moscow's military aid to the
Kabul government. Under the agreement, both the United States and
the Soviet Union can aid their respective allies in the struggle.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
