<DOCNO> AP880416-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-88 1025EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Al-WazirProfile     04-16 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Al-Wazir Profile ,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Assassination Of PLO Leader Silences Moderate Voice</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-PLO Assassination, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOUBAKER GHARIANI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Today's assassination of the No. 2 man in
the PLO's largest branch silenced a moderate voice and deprived the
group of an heir apparent to chief Yasser Arafat.
   Khalil al-Wazir, killed by eight commandos who sprayed him with
machine gun fire early today at his suburban Tunis home, was deputy
military commander of the Palestinian Liberation Organization's
armed forces behind Arafat. Al-Wazir served as No. 2 man in the
mainstream Fatah, the largest branch of the PLO.
   PLO leaders blamed his assassination on the Israeli secret
service, but an Israeli government spokesmen said he knew nothing
of the killing.
   Al-Wazir, 52, was widely regarded as among the most moderate of
PLO leaders. A soft-spoken man, he was obeyed even by dissident
officers, who split from Fatah after feuding with Arafat.
   As Arafat's closest aide, he headed military operations inside
Israeli-occupied territories and masterminded the 4-month-old
uprising in the West Bank and Gaza Strip. He was known to have
urged Palestinians in the territories not to use arms in their
fight against the Israeli occupation.
   Abu Sharif, Arafat's chief PLO spokesman, described Al-Wazir's
death as ``a great loss for the PLO.''
   Al-Wazir was the first of the three founders of Fatah to be
killed. He, Arafat and another PLO chief, Salah Khalaf, had
survived many attempts on their lives since Fatah was launched in
1964.
   Born in Ramle, now in Israel, Khalil Ibrahim al-Wazir was the
son of a bakery owner. He left the area after the 1948 Middle East
war, moving with his family to Gaza.
   He became involved early in the struggle against Israel. In
1963, he joined up with Arafat and together they founded the PLO's
mainstream Fatah guerrilla faction. He became Arafat's right-hand
man in 1967.
   Al-Wazir, also known as Abu Jihad, later became head of military
operations against Israel from bases in Jordan, Syria and Lebanon.
   He helped build the PLO's organization in Lebanon in the 1970s,
when it became a virtual state within a state. In April 1975 when
Lebanon's civil war broke out, he commanded the Palestinian and
Lebanese Moslem forces against Israeli-backed Christians.
   When the Israeli army invaded Lebanon in 1982 to crush the PLO,
he was evacuated on the same ship with Arafat under the protection
of a U.S. Marine force.
   He then went with Arafat and other Palestinian leaders to Tunis,
where the PLO established its new headquarters.
   Al-Wazir was credited with re-building Palestinian guerrilla
strength in Lebanon.
   His wife Imjihad, daughter Hannan, 14, and son Nidal, 2, were in
the house in suburban Tunis early today when the commandos burst
in. But the relatives were not hurt, PLO officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880416-0058 </DOCNO>
