<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Obit-Nakamura     04-16 0136</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Nakamura,0140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Famed Kabuki Actor Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kanzaburo Nakamura, a leading kabuki actor and
recipient of cultural awards from the government, died of a heart
attack today, kabuki officials said. He was 78.
   Nakamura, whose real name was Seiji Namino, was active in
promoting kabuki overseas and led a troupe of actors to New York in
1960 during the theater's U.S. debut. He also had performed in
Europe.
   Nakamura debuted on the stage in 1916. In 1980, he received an
Order of Culture award from the Japanese government for his
contribution to the art form and was designated a ``holder of
important intangible cultural properties.''
   Kabuki, a highly stylized form of drama, originated in 1603 in
Kyoto and is performed solely by men.
   Nakamura is survived by his wife, Hisae, and three children.
</TEXT>
