<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Vietnam-US     04-16 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam-US,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Surgeons Agree On Three-Year Cooperation Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two American plastic surgeons who
recently visited Vietnam agreed to a three-year program of
cooperation with Vietnamese doctors, the official Vietnam News
Agency reported.
   The report said that during their visit, John D. Constable, of
Boston University, and Michael H. Moises, of the University of New
Orleans, performed a number of reconstructive face operations with
Vietnamese surgeons.
   The report, dated Friday and seen in Bangkok today, said the
three-year program involved research on and treatment of cleft lip
and cleft palate.
   They agreed to train personnel and to exchange results of
research, it said.
   The surgeons visited Vietnam from March 22 to April 1 as part of
an agreement between Hanoi's Maxillo-Facial Institute and the
private U.S. Committee for Scientific and Technical Cooperation
with Vietnam.
   Since last August, the United States government also has
dispatched medical teams to Vietnam on four occasions to explore
the needs of disabled war veterans and others. Vietnam in return
pledged to speed up efforts to account for Americans missing in the
Vietnam war.
</TEXT>
