<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-88 1050EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-Labor Bjt   04-16 0735</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Labor, Bjt,0756</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Challenge Or Last Hurrah: Tony Benn Runs For Labor Leadership</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tony Benn, the aristocrat-turned-dean of the
radical left, is running for the leadership of the Labor Party in a
contest that could determine whether the socialists still can
topple Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
   Labor leader Neil Kinnock appears certain to defeat Benn, but he
needs a big win to demonstrate he has led the party away from the
left-wing radicalism that has helped it lose three successive
elections.
   When Benn, 63, announced last month that he will contest the
leadership at the party's autumn conference, Kinnock called it
``selfish and futile.''
   Kinnock saw the challenge as a blow to his drive to woo back
blue-collar and middle-class voters who have deserted to Mrs.
Thatcher's Conservative Party. But there are signs now that Kinnock
is relishing the contest as an opportunity to hand the left a
decisive, public defeat.
   ``I didn't choose this (contest),'' Kinnock, 46, said in a
television interview. ``But I shall fight it and win it in a way
that will bring strength and credibility to the Labor Party.''
   The opening salvos attracted the kind of publicity Labor
moderates dread: Benn back on prime time television with his calls
for class struggle, newspapers mulling over his demands for state
control of the economy, renewed trade union militancy, the closure
of U.S. military bases and the removal of Britain from NATO.
   In a party that lost power to Mrs. Thatcher nearly a decade ago,
Benn, a former energy secretary, is one of a diminishing band of
opposition members of Parliament who have held high government
office.
   Born Anthony Wedgwood Benn, he inherited the title Viscount
Stansgate but renounced it in 1963.
   A pipe-puffing intellectual with a mischievous wit and brilliant
oratorical style, Benn once was seen as a prime
minister-in-waiting. In 1981 he came within half a percentage point
of defeating Denis Healey for the Labor deputy leadership.
   Benn now appears likely to get around 20 percent of the vote by
an electoral college made up of union leaders, members of
Parliament and branch leaders.
   It is a mark of how far Kinnock, a Welsh miner's son and former
leftist, has shifted the party since taking over in 1983.
   Benn, who sees himself as the bulwark against Mrs. Thatcher's
stated aim of burying socialism, maintains that Labor loses because
it is trying to ape her capitalist doctrine instead of siding
squarely with left-wing causes. It is an argument that infuriates
Labor moderates.
   ``There's got to be a much stronger commitment to people in
struggle _ much, much stronger,'' says Benn.
   He accuses Kinnock of distancing the party from strikes by
miners, teachers, printers and health workers. ``You can't ask
people to support you on polling day if you don't support them when
they're on picket lines.''
   Benn is running with another veteran left-winger, Eric Heffer,
who is one of two candidates trying to unseat deputy leader Roy
Hattersley, a moderate.
   Labor's showing in June 1987, when Mrs. Thatcher won a third
five-year term, improved only marginally from the previous election
in 1983. Labor won 31 percent of the vote compared with the
Conservatives' 42 percent, while centrists and minority regional
parties took the rest.
   Benn made his challenge for the leadership when it appeared
Kinnock was shifting further to the right.
   A preliminary report on a wholesale review of Labor policies
ordered by Kinnock is due in the summer.
   Party left-wingers suspect Labor is about to ditch, or at least
fudge, its pledge to dismantle Britain's nuclear arsenal and shut
down U.S. nuclear bases, and will leave intact some major Thatcher
changes, such as selling off state-owned industries.
   Many analysts see Benn's move as offering a new opportunity for
the party. Splits among the centrist factions have re-established
Labor as the only credible challenger to the Tories, but it remains
five to 10 points behind the Conservatives in poll ratings.
   Labor also hopes to benefit from Mrs. Thatcher's controversial
third-term program of shaking up the welfare system and imposing
unpopular new property taxes.
   ``Labor now has some chance of reuniting the center-left into an
electable coalition,'' commented the respected weekly The
Economist. ``The challenge for Labor's leadership from the failed
old man of the left, Mr. Tony Benn, ought to provide Mr. Neil
Kinnock with a golden opportunity.''
</TEXT>
