<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TrainDeath     04-16 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Train Death,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boy Crossing Tracks On A Dare Killed By Train</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDEN PRAIRIE, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 9-year-old boy trying to beat a
freight train across railroad tracks was tossed about 100 feet and
killed by the train's engine, witnesses said.
   Joshua D. Bischoff and three other boys were playing a ``game of
chicken'' Friday afternoon, daring one another to cross the track
on bicycles as the train drew closer, witnesses said.
   ``You could tell they knew better not to do it,'' said Chris
Harrington, an Eden Prairie High School senior who saw the
accident. ``The first two boys to cross were dangerously close to
being hit. They just made it.''
   The engineer told police the train sounded a warning horn as it
rolled along the track at between 30 and 40 mph, according to Lt.
Les Bridger of the Eden Prairie Police Department.
   ``Then they locked the brakes as they realized what was
happening ahead of them,'' Bridger said. ``But you don't stop a
train on a dime. It took another several hundred feet for the train
to stop.''
   Bischoff, who was trying to cross the track on his bicycle, was
thrown about 100 feet down the track and then run over by the
engine, Harrington said. His small dirt-type bicycle landed in
pieces near him.
   The boy, who was a student at Prairie View Elementary School,
was returning with his brother and a friend from a book fair held
at the school, said his father, Doug Bischoff.
   ``I don't think it was a game of chicken they were playing,''
his father said. ``My oldest boy was there and he would not do that
and their friend would not do that, either.
   ``All I can think is that he decided to try to get across the
tracks and then didn't make it. The best I can say is he was just
going to beat the train across the tracks.''
   The accident is under investigation by the Eden Prairie Police
Department.
</TEXT>
