<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Four-FingeredZollie     04-16 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Four-Fingered Zollie,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hobbyist Saws Off Thumb, Wife Puts Saw on Block</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOVELAND, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Wife of four-fingered man has scrap
wood and old table saw FREE. You haul.''
   Zollie Evans' wife, Frances, put that ad in the Loveland
Reporter-Herald classifieds on Thursday.
   Evans, 69, accidentally cut off part of his right thumb with the
saw last spring, and he hasn't used the saw since.
   ``You know what they say about where a young man's fancy turns
in the spring. An old man's fancy turns to saws and wood. I
thought, `Oh my God, I have to get rid of it,''' Mrs. Evans said.
   The saw is homemade, and Evans attached it to a wheeled cart to
make it portable.
   ``It's ideal for a good carpenter,'' said Evans, a retired Air
Force serviceman.
   Evans used the saw to cut timbers for a storage shed, a family
room and covererd porch. Last year he was cutting wood for a window
frame when he stooped to pluck something from the ground, looked up
and discovered the top part of his thumb missing.
   Evans said he plans to ``relax and cut the grass'' when not busy
with his new hobby _ hooking rugs.
   ``Somebody can take that and do pretty well,'' Evans said,
looking wistfully at the saw. ``Until he cuts his finger off, too.''
</TEXT>
