<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Priest-Guns     04-16 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Priest-Guns,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Saddened By Funerals, Priest Asks Parishioners To Turn In Their
Guns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A priest dismayed by two funerals for gunshot
victims has asked parishioners to turn in their weapons and pledge
that they won't carry guns.
   ``Why do people need a gun on their hips? This isn't Tombstone.
Why do they need a gun under the seat of the car when they go to
King Soopers?'' asked the Rev. Marshall Gourley.
   Gourley began focusing on guns in January after the church had
two funerals for gunshot victims. One was a young man carrying a
gun who was shot by police. The other was a suicide victim.
   Gourley, pastor of Our Lady of Guadalupe Roman Catholic Church,
wants church members and ``everyone else of goodwill'' in Denver to
turn in their pistols, rifles and shotguns.
   He also is asking parishioners to sign pledge cards that they
won't carry guns or have them in their vehicles or in their homes,
unless they are used for hunting.
   ``And they'd better be hunting wild animals, not their
neighbors,'' he said.
   As of last week, he said, more than 400 pledge cars and eight
guns have been turned in to the parish. He said the weapons will be
handed over to the police department.
   ``That's eight guns less out there,'' Gourley said.
   Gourley suggested that those who want to keep their guns should
attend every rosary and every funeral for gunshot victims the
church holds between now and next Easter.
   ``If they still think guns are a good idea, maybe they can
convince me,'' he said.
</TEXT>
