<1ST_LINE>u i AM-CentralAmerica Bjt   04-16 0722</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Central America, Bjt,0742</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Policy Struggling in Central America</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. policy has been buffeted
in recent weeks throughout Central America, prompting suggestions
that Washington's goals in the critical region ignore local
aspirations and feelings.
   President Jose Napoleon Duarte's government in El Salvador,
given full U.S. support since it took office in 1984, suffered a
humiliating defeat last month in legislative and municipal
elections.
   Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriego, although described as a ``tinhorn''
in Washington, has taken the Reagan administration's best punches
and still runs Panama.
   In Honduras, long considered the strongest U.S. ally in the
region, the American consulate was sacked and burned by a mob
angered by what was seen as high-handedness from Washington.
   The Reagan administration's goal of bringing down the leftist
Sandinista government in Nicaragua has all but crumbled because
Congress ended military aid to the Contra rebels and the two sides
now are trying to negotiate a peace agreement.
   A South American ambassador to El Salvador told The Associated
Press privately he believes Washington's recent problems are at
least partially due to security concerns that isolate U.S.
diplomats from their surroundings.
   ``They live in bunkers and when they emerge they're surrounded
by bodyguards,'' he said, with the result that ``they cannot get a
feel for people's concerns and feelings.'' The diplomat represents
a nation friendly to Washington and has served in five Latin
American countries.
   Michael O'Brien, spokesman for the U.S. Embassy in Honduras,
said last week that U.S. diplomats were ``somewhat surprised'' by
the ferocity of the April 7 attack on the consulate.
   The building was burned by a mob infuriated by the arrest and
expulsion two days earlier of a Honduran facing narcotics and
murder charges in the United States.
   Honduran forces worked closely with U.S. authorities in the
operation against Juan Ramon Matta, which violated a constitutional
provision that prohibits extradition of Honduran citizens. Matta
now is in a federal prison at Marion, Ill.
   Many Hondurans view the episode as evidence that U.S. interests
in Honduras carry more weight than the nation's own institutions.
   Resentment of the United States has been growing for years in
Honduras. O'Brien and Honduran authorities say the rioters
represented a small radical minority, but for a year before the
attack the scrawled slogan ``Yankee Get Out!'' had proliferated on
walls in Tegucigalpa, the capital.
   A sore point with many Hondurans is what they consider a loss of
sovereignty caused by the Reagan administration's use of their
nation as a surrogate in its Nicaragua policy.
   ``This country has allowed its territory to be converted into a
sanctuary for irregular forces attacking a neighboring country with
which we're not at war,'' Anibal Puerto, vice president of the
Honduran Human Rights Commission, said in an interview.
   ``This raises the question of the allegiance of the Honduran
armed forces. Everything leads one to believe they are loyal to the
government of the United States rather than to their own people.''
   In El Salvador, political leader Alfredo Cristiani accused
Washington of trying to impose solutions that do not suit local
circumstances.
   Cristiani, president of the rightist Republican National
Alliance that beat Duarte's Christian Democrats in the March 20
elections, referred in an interview to U.S.-designed agrarian
reform that has gone nowhere.
   ``It is not right that U.S. professors with land reform
experience in other contexts come here and destroy an entire
agrarian system for a political end,'' he said. ``That is the great
mistake, trying to experiment without really knowing much about El
Salvador. This creates resentment.''
   U.S. policymakers clearly miscalculated about Panama. Since
Washington cast its lot with Eric Arturo Delvalle, the figurehead
civilian president Noriega pushed aside Feb. 26, administration
officials have been predicting the general would abandon power in a
matter of days. That was seven weeks ago.
   Harsh U.S. economic sanctions imposed in the effort to force
Noriega out have crippled the economy, hurting ordinary people the
most.
   American military reinforcements sent to improve security for
the Panama Canal accidentally shot one of their own men to death
last week, a result of increasing edginess caused by the extended
crisis.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Douglas Grant Mine, formerly news editor for The
Associated Press in Buenos Aires, Argentina, now reports on Central
America.
</TEXT>
