<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--AllegedCheating     04-16 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Alleged Cheating,0185</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Student Sues To Prevent Release Of Information</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LATROBE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior at St. Vincent College accused of
fabricating data for a research program is suing to prevent
officials there from telling medical schools about the incident,
according to published reports.
   The 21-year-old biology major, identified only as ``J.C.'' in
the suit, denies he made up the information. He originally received
an A on the project, but the grade was dropped to an F after
another professor challenged the work, The Pittsburgh Press
reported Friday.
   The college wants to revoke a recommendation its
pre-professional committee sent to medical school on the student's
behalf, including one school that has accepted the student.
   Revoking the recommendation might cause the student ``to forever
lose his opportunity to attend medical school,'' the student and
his parents claim in a lawsuit filed last month.
   Court papers indicate the student challenged the failing grade
during two hearings at St. Vincent, but the college would not
change it.
   St. Vincent spokesman Don Orlando declined to comment Friday. A
court hearing is scheduled Tuesday.
</TEXT>
