<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Gulf-Mines 1stLd-Writethru a0504 04-16 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-Mines, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0504,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Divers Detonate Two Mines In Gulf</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with mined ship reaching port.
PICKS up 10th graf, `Navy officials ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABOARD THE USS WAINWRIGHT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Navy divers detonated two mines
in the central Persian Gulf today while U.S. mine sweepers and
helicopters searched for more explosives.
   Meanwhile, an American warship disabled by a mine Thursday
reached port. Ten sailors were hurt in that blast, the first mining
of a U.S. warship in the gulf.
   The U.S. Navy has found and destroyed 45 mines in the gulf since
June, all the same type Iran has placed. Iran and Iraq are fighting
a 7{-year-old war and have attacked shipping in the gulf.
   In Bahrain, shipping executives said today that a navigational
hazard area had been declared within 10 miles of Thursday's
explosion.
   Western diplomats and the executives, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Iran recently laid the mines in the area.
   ``The shipping channel is frequented by the U.S. Navy and the
implication is that the Iranians have laid the mines for the
Americans,'' said one of the executives.
   A Navy spokesman, Lt. Cmdr. Mark Van Dyke of the Joint Task
Force Middle East, indicated Friday that ``strong evidence''
indicated the mines ``came from the same source'' as the ones the
Navy found in September.
   Van Dyke was referring to an Iranian boat, Iran Ajr, which was
caught laying mines in the central gulf Sept. 21. It was attacked
and disabled by U.S. helicopters and nine other mines were found on
the deck of the craft.
   U.S. officers said that Marine helicopters spotted the two mines
Friday in the waters where the 3,700-ton guided missile frigate,
Samuel B. Roberts, struck the underwater explosive, injuring 10 of
the warship's 225 men.
   Van Dyke said the mooring cables appeared new and the mines
themselves had no growth or barnacles. He said that showed that
they had been in the water ``a reasonably short amount of time.''
   The 445-foot Samuel B. Roberts, its stern low in the water and
its steel skin rippled and bent by the force of the blast, reached
Dubai, the capital of the United Arab Emirates near the mouth of
the Gulf, under tow today.
   Navy officials said four of the injured were relayed by
helicopter to a hospital in Bahrain. Three were suffering from
serious burns and the fourth from smoke inhalation.
   Six others returned to the Roberts.
   Van Dyke said the ship was ``currently considered stable.''
   Asked about possible U.S. retaliation for the mining, Van Dyke
said, ``It would not be appropriate to comment on that.''
   The Newport, R.I.-based ship, on assignment in the gulf, hit the
mine about 55 miles east northeast of the Qatar Peninsula.
   The waters where the Roberts was hit make up a a major shipping
lane used by commercial vessels, including Kuwaiti tankers. The
tankers were reflagged by the United States in July 1987 for
protection from Iranian attack.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
