<DOCNO> AP880416-0069 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-88 1105EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MaulingTrial     04-16 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mauling Trial,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lion Owner Convicted in Lion Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owner of a pet lion that attacked
an 8-year-old girl at a Houston flea market has been convicted of
injury to a child.
   Gary Durkovitz, 35, of Houston, owner of a 350-pound lion, faces
up to 10 years in prison and a $5,000 fine when the sentence is
handed down Monday. He was found guilty Friday after jurors
deliberated about five hours.
   Durkovitz's attorney, Robert Scardino, said he would appeal.
   ``There just weren't facts there to prove a crime had been
committed,'' Scardino said.
   Durkovitz was charged after his lion mauled Roxanne Hernandez at
the Texas Flea Market in Houston on Oct. 10, 1987. The lion was
part of an exhibit and was being led out of the building when the
attack occurred.
   A flea market security guard shot the lion as the animal bit the
little girl's head, exposing part of her brain.
   During the five-day trial, Durkovitz said he did not know the
lion was dangerous and had taken all possible precautions to
prevent an attack. But the animal's previous owner testified that
he had warned Durkovitz that he was selling the animal because it
had bitten his children.
   Harris County Assistant District Attorney Alice Brown said
during closing arguments Friday that Durkovitz knew the lion was
dangerous.
   ``I tell you now. This beastmaster was playing Russian roulette
with the lives of our children, with the lives of our public,'' Ms.
Brown said.
   Roxanne's mother, Sonia Hernandez, testified that her daughter
faces more operations and that her academic performance has
declined.
</TEXT>
