<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-88 1113EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Kosinski     04-16 0953</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Kosinski,0979</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>After 31 Years, Kosinski Returns in Triumph to Homeland</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jerzy Kosinski, once one of official
Poland's most reviled authors, had the sweet revenge of being feted
and showered with praise during a triumphal return to the country
he fled 31 years ago.
   The creator of ``The Painted Bird'' and ``Being There''
delivered a vibrant message of intellectual independence to crowds
who packed the auditoriums wherever he appeared last week.
   Speaking in flawless Polish, the U.S. writer of Polish-Jewish
descent stressed the relationship between Poles and Jews over the
centuries, condemned prejudice against Poles and Jews, blasted the
official critics who pilloried his reputation here the late 1960s
and bemoaned economic conditions in Poland.
   Cutting a lithe, elegant figure, the 55-year-old Kosinski was by
turns tragic and comic. His outrageous statements, rich wordplay
and puns quickly won over his audiences.
   Judging by the 180-degree turnabout by the authorities, he
seemed to be having the same effect on them.
   Before his scheduled departure Sunday, he had promises that
Poland would publish his nine novels and won agreement to build an
Institution of Polish-Jewish Heritage in Kazimierz, the ancient
Jewish quarter of Krakow.
   But Kosinski, speaking with American and British reporters
Friday, said he has a healthy skepticism of official promises.
   ``We are living in a country in which all plans, five-year
plans, seven-year plans, 10-year plans, have all been very
definite,'' he joked. He said he will believe his books are to be
officially brought out in Polish only ``when I see them published
in more than five copies, and not mimeographed.''
   Kosinski, who left his native city of Lodz for the United State
in 1957, came back April 6. His visit coincided with observances of
the 45th anniversary of the doomed Warsaw Jewish Ghetto Uprising
that preceded the Nazi eradication of all but a few traces of
Jewish life in Poland's capital.
   But he stressed that he had not come to Poland solely to mourn
the dead. He objected to the ``deification'' of the Jewish
Holocaust.
   Considering history ``only from the point of view of a four-year
drama, in relation to 1,000 years of (Polish-Jewish cultural)
development, is for me, a man who genuinely loves life,
unacceptable,'' he said.
   He went to Auschwitz to show it to his wife, but he devoted more
time to visiting sites of former Jewish life in Poland: Kazimierz
in Krakow, the old Jewish quarter of Lublin in eastern Poland and
his former home of Lodz, a textile center.
   There he met his brother by adoption for the first time in 30
years. While in Poland, he also renewed close friendships from his
student days.
   Only two relatives of Kosinski survived the Nazi occupation of
World War II. He said he survived thanks to Poles whose names he
does not know. He was 24 when he left the country, a promising
photographer and a sociologist who wanted to become a novelist.
   Asked about views that Poland is a land of anti-Semitism, he
said: ``This is disgusting.''
   ``I know enough about my history to say this. If they, if the
architects of disaster, the Germans and the Nazis, are to be called
anti-Semites, then those (Poles) who spat at me occasionally or
even pogromized me, historically speaking, clearly should be called
by another name.
   ``To have the same name for those who burned my relatives in
Auschwitz _ that's not a Polish name _ to have the same term for
them ... is simply unfair, as unfair as anything I can think of.''
   But Kosinski's voice rose to greatest emotion when he discussed
his own literary exile from his native land, where no books by him
have been published official and only fragments published in the
underground press. He had been attacked as a traitor to Poland for
the brutal images in ``The Painted Bird,'' which reviewers assumed
referred to Poland.
   ``It is an injustice that a man named Jerzy Kosinski, who goes
to the United States and becomes a writer there, and is not a
politician and is clearly apolitical, that this man is not allowed
to return to his own country.''
   Polish journalists frequently asked Kosinski about his decision
to write in English, which he said now puts him in the odd position
of being translated into his native tongue. He said it was largely
a pragmatic choice motivated by his desire to be read in his
adopted country.
   But he said writing in English is an emotional filter for him.
   ``The English language was necessary to create an emotional
distance between myself and the other Jerzy Kosinski, who maybe
could write the book in Polish. But could he? Maybe he would
shudder that he had lived through that war in Polish, and not want
to write. About himself.''
   He said he saw are promising signs of increasing literary
freedom in Poland.
   But he noted the continued ban of the Polish section of the
international PEN writers club since Poland's 1981 martial-law
crackdown and said he has reason to doubt the authorities'
sincerity. Kosinski served two terms as the president of the
American PEN.
   ``It's been 30 years of these authorities and I still have no
trust of them,'' he said.
   ``I know almost nothing (about those in power now) but what the
authorities used to write about me was fiction, and I do know
something about that because I am an expert on writing fiction.''
   Still, said Kosinski, he has been ``very much at home'' during
his visit, ``very much in love with the country thanks to my Polish
nature ... and at the same time very much like a foreigner.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
