<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-88 1130EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-PanamaOptions Bjt   04-16 0840</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Panama Options, Bjt,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Many Now Urge Negotiated Settlement in Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA </BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. failure to oust Panamanian strongman
Manuel Antonio Noriega is increasing calls from members of
Congress, Central American leaders and outside experts for a
negotiated solution to the Panama crisis.
   Administration officials also are listing negotiations as one of
several options but they remain hopeful that Panama's severe cash
shortage and continued payless paydays for thousands of government
workers still will induce Noriega to depart.
   Costa Rican President Oscar Arias said during a visit to
Washington last week that the economic sanctions the United States
has imposed have punished the Panamanian people more than they have
military chief Noriega.
   Arias is the author of a plan to bring peace to Nicaragua and
other Central American countries and has been involved in an effort
to resolve the crisis in Panama.
   He recommended a negotiated settlement and said that the United
States should cooperate with other Central American countries in
finding a solution. Unilateral action only leaves the Reagan
administration isolated, said Arias.
   Former President Richard M. Nixon said he, too, believes broader
action by Latin American nations offers the best hope for a
solution.
   Following a briefing Thursday by State Department and Pentagon
officials, Senate Foreign Relations Committee members generally
agreed the administration must do more to seek a diplomatic
solution.
   This view was shared by committee chairman Claiborne Pell,
D-R.I. and Sens. Nancy Kassebaum, R-Kan. and John Kerry, D-Mass.
   Senate Majority Leader Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., sent a letter to
President Reagan asking that U.S. policy give greater emphasis to
the common hemispheric interest in combatting drugs. Noriega has
been indicted in the United States on drug charges, and has been
accused of turning his country into a haven for drug traffickers.
   Sol Linowitz, a former ambassador to the Organization of
American States who helped negotiate the Panama Canal treaties,
said, ``We've got to stop acting as if we can do it alone.''
   Linowitz urged that the United States get behind a diplomatic
effort begun last month by Arias, Spanish Prime Minister Felipe
Gonzalez and former presidents Daniel Oduber of Costa Rica, Carlos
Andres Perez of Venezuela and Alfonso Lopez Michelson of Colombia.
   He expressed hope that a solution could be worked out with the
help of Panamanian Archbishop Marcos A. McGrath, who offered last
month to act as a mediator but backed off from the role after he
was unable to get the government and the opposition together.
   Noriega has clung to power despite strikes, demonstrations,
defections, a coup attempt by disaffected military officers, and,
most importantly, a severe economic slowdown to which the United
States has been a major contributor.
   U.S. officials believe that the Panamanian government's
inability to meet its payroll for more than a month is the single
most potent force working against his continued rule.
   Additional U.S. sanctions are being contemplated but Linowitz
believes the administration has gone too far already.
   ``There is no guarantee that more pressure will drive Noriega
from power,'' he said. The consensus in Latin America is that the
United States should reverse the sanctions it has imposed on
grounds that these measures are ``coercive'' and therefore
inappropriate.
   A former U.S. ambassador to Panama, Ambler Moss, said the
administration has pursued its policies in a ``typically
hegemonistic'' way. He agreed with Linowitz that Latin American
countries would be useful in the search for a negotiated solution.
   A U.S. official, insisting on anonymity, said that among the
options still not ruled out is sounding out Noriega on his proposal
to leave his post as commander of the Defense Forces before
elections scheduled for next year provided opposition groups agree
to a ``national dialogue'' with the government.
   The official gave the impression this option is being held in
reserve for the time being. A more likely course of action over the
short term is a U.S. attempt to devise a strategy that will enable
opposition groups in Panama to carry out their struggle more
effectively, he said.
   Some State Department officials, exasperated by Noriega's
resilience, are urging military action to remove him but the
Pentagon is generally hostile to the idea.
   Arias warned against such action during his visit.
   Nixon said he believes that option is unwise because it would
generate an anti-American reaction throughout Latin America.
   Former White House aide Patrick Buchanan wrote last week that
sending the Marines into Panama is the wrong way to fight drug
smuggling.
   If the U.S. refuses to deal seriously with the drug problem at
home, Buchanan asked, ``why should American Marines risk their
lives, to take lives, in the jungles of Panama?''
   But Michael G. Wilson, an analyst at the Heritage Foundation, a
conservative research group, believes military force would be
warranted under certain conditions.
   ``We should let Noriega realize that if he makes any wrong move
toward U.S. citizens, U.S. bases or the canal, or even against the
Panamanian opposition, we would be willing to consider a surgical
strike against him,'' he said.
</TEXT>
