<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--CrossBurning     04-16 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Cross Burning,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cross Burned At Home Of Racially-Mixed Couple</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RISING SUN, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cross was burned early Saturday near
the home of a white woman living with a black man in what a fire
official said was the third ``racially motivated'' incident
directed against the couple.
   Although the Ku Klux Klan has held rallies in this part of
northeastern Maryland, officials do not know if the Klan was
involved, said Bob Thomas, state fire marshal's spokesman.
   In two previous incidents, relatives of the woman were
suspected, according to a state police officer who declined to be
identified. However, there is not necessarily a connection between
Saturday's cross burning and previous harassment, the officer said.
   Police were looking for two white men in their early 20s, Thomas
said.
   The woman discovered the 8 foot by 6 foot cross before dawn,
Thomas said. The timbers were wrapped with cloth, doused with a
flammable liquid, and then set afire next to the driveway, Thomas
said.
   Thomas said last month someone shot at the couple's car and
there was another assault, but had no further details.
</TEXT>
