<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-88 1134EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush Bjt   04-16 0803</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, Bjt,810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Likely GOP Nominee Bush Hoping to Share Political Limelight With
Democrats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While the three Democratic contenders are
battling to the wire for votes in Tuesday's New York primary,
Republican George Bush has the luxury of sitting back and watching
his delegates pile up.
   Bush can receive as many as 96 delegates in Tuesday's contest
(of which he already has 48 committed), raising his total to a
potential 970 and moving him ever closer to the 1,139 needed for
the GOP nomination.
   However, Bush strategists says that while the vice president is
running virtually unopposed, he plans to spend considerable time
campaigning in the months ahead in delegate-rich states.
   Rep. Guy Molinari, R-N.Y., Bush's New York campaign chairman,
said that Bush will likely return to the state two or three more
times between now and the August convention.
   Bush spent three days campaigning leisurely in New York last
week, including stops in Syracuse, Buffalo, Rochester and New York
City.
   Molinari said the withdrawal from the race of Bush's only
remaining major opponent, Sen. Bob Dole, ``changed the itinerary
somewhat. The vice president cut back days.''
   But he said that Bush's visit was helpful in shoring up GOP
support and in giving the vice president some visibility in the
state to help offset the constant coverage that has gone to
Democrats Michael Dukakis, Sen. Albert Gore Jr., and Jesse Jackson.
   Bush planned to campaign in Ohio on Monday and Pennsylavnia on
Tuesday, and then spend several days back in Washington. He will
spend considerable time next month on the West Coast, much of it in
California, aides said.
   The candidacy of former television evangelist Pat Robertson,
however, continues to stand between Bush and a total lock on the
GOP nomination _ and may also be helping to keep President Reagan
on the sidelines for the time being.
   Reagan had vowed to remain neutral as long as there was a
contest among Republicans.
   However, even though Robertson has not formally withdrawn from
the race, his recent campaign efforts have been minimal.
   Speaking to the American Society of Newspaper Editors on Friday,
Robertson said ``it is obvious from the delegate count that has
come out that George Bush is going to be the nominee of the
Republican Party absent any unexpected eventuality.''
   Still, Robertson, who has 17 delegates, has not pulled out of
the race and said he still hopes to ``energize the people who
support me'' to take an active role in the convention.
   There has been no direct contact between Bush and Robertson,
even though the two were back-to-back speakers before the audience
of newspaper executives.
   ``I think he's plowed under,'' Bush said, speaking with
reporters on Air Force II last week as he returned from his swing
through New York.
   Asked if some prominent Republican, perhaps Dole, might serve as
a mediator between the two camps, Bush said: ``We don't need any
mediation. We need our facts clear.''
   Bush spokesman Peter Teeley said there was no intention on
Bush's part to try to persuade Robertson to throw in the towel in
the name of party unity.
   ``It would not be proper,'' Teeley said.
   However, the aide said, ``his campaign for the most part is
dormant. He's doing very little traveling. It's almost as if his
campaign is non-existent.''
   As for Reagan's participation, Teeley suggested it may be the
delegate count more than Robertson's persistence that is sidelining
the president. Teeley said that might change ``once we have the
delegates to go over the top.''
   According to The Associated Press delegate count, that will come
no later than May 3, probably even sooner.
   Meanwhile, Bush has clearly changed his campaign tactics. He's
focusing much more on the Democrats, and his campaign speeches have
become more assertive in their criticism.
   Claiming he can't distinguish much difference between Dukakis,
Gore and Jackson on most issues, Bush has accused all three of
seeking to take the United States back to ``the days of ships that
couldn't sail and planes that couldn't fly,'' of double-digit
inflation and interest rates.
   ``Do you want Americans to go back to those terrible days of
malaise and darkness?'' he asks audiences.
   On foreign policy, Bush accuses the Democrats of advocating
international policies that are ``dangerous, naive'' and filled
with ``wishful thinking.''
   Wherever Bush speaks, he is dogged by questions about his role
in the Iran-Contra affair and the legal difficulties surrounding
Attorney General Edwin Meese III.
   On Iran-Contra, Bush sticks by his assertion that he knew
nothing about the arms-for-hostages operation until it had been
terminated. And, he adds, if he were a Democrat, he'd raise it as a
campaign issue too.
   ``The Democrats will be after it,'' is his stock answer,
``they've got little else to run on.''
</TEXT>
