<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Chernobyl     04-16 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chernobyl,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Elderly Residents Sneak Back to High-Radiation Areas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 100 mostly elderly people evacuated from
their homes near Chernobyl have sneaked back to areas where
radiation levels are still above normal two years after the nuclear
disaster, Tass said Saturday.
   The official news agency said many never fully adjusted to
relocation after the April 26, 1986, nuclear reactor explosion. The
accident caused the death of at least 31 people and radiation
sickness in more than 200 others.
   About 135,000 people were evacuated from an 18-mile zone around
the plant. Two of 180 settlements evacuated have been declared safe
for rehabitation, but most evacuees are still housed in settlements
outside the danger zone.
   Tass quoted Alexei Demchenyuk, deputy head of the interior
department of the Kiev region, as saying people were returning to
their houses and farms by going around checkpoints. Tass did not
say to which settlements the people were returning.
   ``We do not have either a moral or legal right today to force
them to leave the zone,'' Demchenyuk told Tass. ``Militiamen not
only discharge their immediate functions to maintain public order,
but also help elderly people to cut firewood, repair houses and
deliver food.''
   Tass said there had been several cases of theft in abandoned
homes and public buildings over the two years.
   Demchenyuk said some people had tried to smuggle 17th and 18th
century icons out of the contaminated region.
   ``The radiation level of these cultural treasures exceeds
somewhat the permitted radiation standard. Therefore, the
scientists and restorers summoned to Chernobyl now work on how to
decontaminate and preserve them,'' Demchenyuk said.
   Chernobyl is about 80 miles north of the Ukrainian capital of
Kiev.
   Tass said 21,000 houses and 1,500 apartments were built for the
evacuees in other parts of the Ukraine and that $1.5 billion in
compensation was given to the evacuee.
   Tass did not say how many militia patrols are assigned to the
area, but that they are responsible for ``keeping watch'' over the
radiation zone. Decontamination measures have reduced the radiation
level, Tass said, but it still is higher than normal.
   The report did not specify how high the radition level was.
</TEXT>
