<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-88 1139EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MajorityLeaders-Style     04-16 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Majority Leaders-Style,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Democrats Can Expect Style Change in Leader When Byrd
Leaves</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Byrd Successor Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE GOULD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Majority Leader Robert Byrd's decision
to step down at the end of the year assures at the least a change
in style at the top of the Democratic Party.
   And it gave one retiring veteran of the Senate a moment to pause
and reflect on the changing style of leadership in what senators
like to call the world's oldest deliberative body.
   ``In the 30 years I have been here,'' said Sen. William
Proxmire, D-Wis., ``we have had the all-encompassing, dominating
leadership of Lyndon Johnson; the every-senator-is-a-leader,
consensus leadership of Mike Mansfield, the gentle,
behind-the-scenes masterful compromising leadership of Howard
Baker, the forceful and yet always considerate leadership of Bob
Dole, and the diligent, persistent, truly dedicated leadership of
Robert Byrd.''
   Mike Mansfield, who served 16 years as majority leader before
retiring in 1977, is now U.S. ambassador to Japan. Baker, a
Republican, is now White House chief of staff, while Dole, the
current Senate Republican leader, recently gave up his bid for the
GOP presidential nomination.
   Senate Democrats under Byrd of West Virginia, now meet weekly to
consider their agenda. But, Proxmire recalled, under Johnson, who
ran the Senate like a dictator from 1953 until 1961, ``we would
have a party caucus literally only once every two years, at the
beginning of the new Congress.
   ``Lyndon would deliver what we called Lyndon's `State of the
Union Message' and that was that. There was no need for a caucus
because Lyndon would decide everything, and I mean everything, the
Senate would act on.
   ``The Senate was a one-man show,'' said Proxmire, who is leaving
the Senate.
   The Wisconsin senator said that Byrd, who served as party
leader, and majority leader when Democrats controlled the Senate,
from 1977 through this year, was no dictator. But, Proxmire added,
Byrd has his convictions, too.
   ``Just yesterday, I called Senator Byrd to ask him to vote with
me on a matter of great importance to this senator. He flatly
refused. I entreated him. He replied, `No way!'''
   ``He said, `This is my position and that's that.' He would not
yield his convictions. I respect and admire him for that.''
   With Byrd looking on from his desk, Proxmire wound up by noting
``a little-observed side of our retiring majority leader.''
   He noted that the chaplain opens each day's Senate session with
a prayer.
   ``But often this body is treated to two prayers. We have the
chaplain's prayer, and then we have another prayer by the majority
leader, in effect. The majority leader often offers a truly
astonishing, spur-of-the-moment analysis of the chaplain's prayer.
   ``Senator Byrd will often be inspired to launch into a flight of
poetry, or a passage from some long-forgotten American or English
author. His recall is amazing. He can quote at length from the
Bible, from an infinite variety of speeches made by past political
leaders. He is able to recall word-for-word something he must have
read 10 or 20 years ago.
   ``Here is a unique leader, one who is, I think, too little
appreciated and one who has given this Senate and all senators a
very great deal.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
