<DOCNO> AP880416-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-88 1217EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GulfRdp     04-16 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp,0564</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran, Iraq Trade Missile Attacks, Mined U.S. Frigate Reaches Port</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Asociated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq fired six long-range missiles into
Tehran and two other Iranian cities Saturday and Iran said it fired
two back. It was the heaviest missile barrage in the ``war of the
cities'' in 10 days.
   The U.S. Navy missile frigate Samuel B. Roberts limped into
Dubai in the southern Persian Gulf after it was holed by a mine
Thursday. Ten of the warship's 225-man crew were wounded in the
blast.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in
Nicosia, said the Iraqi missiles that hit Tehran crashed into
residential neighborhoods in the Iranian capital. It reported many
casualties, but gave no specific figures.
   It said missiles exploded in the central city of Isfahan,
Persia's 16th century capital, and the holy city of Qom, 100 miles
south of Tehran.
   IRNA said Iranian Revolutionary Guards fired two missiles at
``military centers'' in Baghdad, the Iraqi capital, several hours
later. The official Iraqi News Agency said one missile hit the city
and killed an unspecified number of civilians in a residential
neighborhood.
   The two sides in the 7{-year-old Persian Gulf war have fired
more than 300 missiles into each other's cities since Feb. 29.
   More than 120 missiles have hit the Iranian capital in that
period. Until the latest phase of the ``war of the cities,'' which
Iran and Iraq have waged intermittently since 1984, Tehran had
never been hit by missiles.
   The Iraqis also said their fighter-bombers raided the western
Iranian cities of Dezful and Hamadan. IRNA said four civilians were
killed.
   The Iranians reported 24 civilians were killed in Iraqi air
raids on nine Iranian cities Friday.
   IRNA said Iranian warplanes bombed ``military and economic
targets'' in four Iraqi towns, including Baqubeh, 30 miles
northeast of Baghdad, and the northern town of Dukan.
   It said other Iranian jets bombed Kut, 80 miles southeast of
Baghdad, and Zako and Erbil in the north.
   Shipping executives in Bahrain said a 10-mile stretch of the
central gulf has been declared a navigational hazard area because
of supected mines.
   The executives and Western diplomats, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said they believe the Iranians laid the mine there that
holed the U.S. frigate.
   The mine was one of several spotted in the area and has
rekindled fears that the Iranians were again mining shipping lanes
in the strategic waterway after laying off for several months
following clashes with U.S. forces.
   Associated Press reporter Richard Pyle, aboard the USS
Wainwright in the gulf, reported that Navy divers Saturday
detonated two mines in the central gulf, near where the Roberts was
hit. Mine sweepers and helicopters searched for others.
   The Roberts was the first U.S. Navy ship damaged in the gulf
since an Iraqi warplane attacked the frigate Stark with missiles
May 17, 1987, killing 37 crewmen. The Iraqis said the pilot mistook
the Stark for an Iranian warship.
   The U.S. Navy, supported by warships from several western
European countries, increased its presence in the gulf last July to
protect reflagged Kuwaiti tankers from Iranian attack.
   The Kuwait vessels were reregistered in the United States so
they could fly the U.S. flag. Iran accuses Kuwait of aiding Iraq's
war effort.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
