<DOCNO> AP880416-0084 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-88 1253EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hijack-Nightmare     04-16 0807</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hijack-Nightmare,0837</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Freed Hostages Tell of Hijack</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hijack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saadi Qattaineh was dozing in his seat, high above
the Indian Ocean, when a clamor woke him.
   ``There were two men shouting `Hands up!''' he said. ``One
grabbed the steward and the other started checking him for guns.''
   One of the longest air hijackings had begun. It lasted nine days
for Qattaineh and was in its 12th day Saturday for about 35
hostages still held on the Boeing 747 that left Bangkok as Kuwaiti
Airlines Flight 422 and made its way in stages to Algiers.
   Qattaineh and other freed hostages described the hijack, which
began before dawn April 5, in interviews with The Associated Press.
   They said the gunmen quickly donned makeshift hoods cut from
airline pillowcases and began herding their hostages to a central
section of the jumbo jet.
   ``As soon as they hijacked the aircraft they told us, `We have
certain demands of the Kuwaiti government. ... Just remain calm,'''
Qattaineh said. The hijackers demand the release of 17 pro-Iranian
extremists convicted of bombing the U.S. and French Embassies in
Kuwait in December 1983.
   The plane veered north to Iran and landed at the airport in
Mashhad.
   Because the gunmen ordered the window blinds kept closed, the
passengers did not know where they were, Qattaineh said. The first
inkling came when they were served bread and cheese for breakfast
and ``the napkins said Iran Air.''
   Qattaineh, a 61-year-old retired fireman with a Jordanian
passport, said the hijackers placed the passengers two to a row,
separated by several seats.
   At least two gunmen watched the hostages at all times,
forbidding them to talk and ordering them to shift seats every few
hours, he said.
   Passengers were taken individually for questioning to a forward
cabin beyond a curtain. Some said pillowcase hoods were slipped
over their heads.
   ``We were asked about our religion and how many children we had,
and our work,'' said Saleh Ibrahim Malik, a Kuwaiti.
   Ramadan Ali, an Egyptian-American engineer, said hijackers asked
whether he was a Sunni Moslem or Shiite.
   The hijackers are believewd to be Shiites. All Kuwaitis released
in the first 11 days of the hijacking are Shiites, the predominant
faction in Iran and south Lebanon.
   Ali said the gunmen took the briefcase in which he had hidden
his American passport and stowed it with other luggage in a baggage
compartment.
   Hijackers confiscated passports _ Ali gave them his Egyptian
documents _ and while inspecting wallets overlooking Ali's American
driving license.
   In Iran, Moslem passengers stood several times to pray in the
traditional Islamic manner, but Ali said it made the hijackers
nervous and ``They said, `Hey guys, if you want to pray, pray in
your seats.'''
   On the ground in Iran, the gunmen produced plastic handcuffs
after two days and put them on the hostages, the freed passengers
said.
   Some former hostages said the handcuffs were left on until their
release, but others said they were removed occasionally.
   After three days in Iran the plane flew to Cyprus, where it was
permitted to land at Larnaca because it was low on fuel. It
remained there five days.
   Passengers said they were unaware of the gunmen's threats to
blow up the plane unless their demands were met.
   Most agreed that small machine guns appeared after the plane
left Iran, along with more hand grenades and ropes that were tied
to the doors. Some said they saw explosives attached to the ropes.
   Several passengers also said one or two new gunmen appeared
during the stop in Iran and Ali said they seemed to take charge of
the ``six or seven'' young men who had seized the plane.
   Identification was difficult because the hijackers ``kept
changing their voices and the way they were dressed,'' Qattaineh
said.
   In Cyprus, the hijackers beat and shot two young Kuwaitis to
death, throwing the bodies from the plane.
   None said they knew of the slayings, which occurred out of their
view, but several former hostages said there were ominous signs.
   Mohammed Kamel Sayyid Rehan of Cairo said the gunmen told them:
``We either all die together or live together.''
   ``Before they let us go, two hijackers appeared wearing napkins
round their necks on which they had written `Martyrdom is our
Love','' he said.
   Passengers said they were forced to wear handcuffs even to the
restroom.
   ``I was hit on the face once when I locked the door to the
toilet,'' Rehan said, but he and the others said blows were
infrequent.
   With their hands bound, forced to remain in their seats, there
was little to do but read the only book most had at hand, Islam's
holy Koran.
   ``I feel as if I've been born again,'' said Sharif Mamdouh
Badrawi. ``I read the entire Koran on the plane.''
</TEXT>
