<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-88 1305EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     04-16 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines ,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Philippine Troops Raid Hideout of Fugitive Rebel Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops raided a hideout of the
fugitive leader of August's attempted coup and scoured other
neighborhoods for rebels, the military said Saturday.
   The nation's armed forces remained on full alert to block any
coup attempt while President Corazon Aquino was on a four-day trip
to China and Hong Kong. She was to return Sunday.
   The raiders did not find former Lt. Col. Gregorio ``Gringo''
Honasan in the hideout, an automobile repair shop in suburban
Quezon City. But they seized his motorcycle and military uniforms,
the officials said.
   The raid came late Friday after troops captured 10 of his
followers in a nearby house.
   Chief military spokesman Col. Oscar Florendo said they included
eight of 14 navy guards who helped him escape his prison ship April
2. He had been held there since his December arrest for the failed
coup on Aug. 28 that left 53 dead and 300 hurt.
   The military said the 10 arrests foiled a plot to attack the
presidential palace.
   A report to Defense Secretary Fidel V. Ramos said government
forces were still looking for rebels. It gave no details, and Ramos
told reporters only that the operations were being carried out in
undisclosed neighborhoods.
   Before flying to Hong Kong Saturday, Mrs. Aquino told reporters
in Beijing she was ``very happy'' about the capture of the 10
Honasan followers.
   The military believed Honasan used a small room in the auto shop
as his sleeping quarters, the government's television station
reported Saturday. It said the raiders also found a device used to
reload 45-caliber bullets, a dictionary, a bible and canned food
inside the room.
   Col. Emilio Templo, commander of the 300-member squad making the
arrests, said the plotters planned to approach the palace by rubber
boats down a tributary of the PasigRiver, which flows behind the
building in the heart of the capital.
   But the military was tipped off about the plot, ``so we acted
quickly,'' Templo said. ``We preempted the plan.''
   Honasan was a key figure in the civilian-backed military revolt
that ousted former President Ferdinand Marcos and swept Mrs. Aquino
to power on Feb. 25, 1986.
   But Honasan became disenchanted with Mrs. Aquino and led the
August coup attempt, the most serious of six bids to unseat Mrs.
Aquino since she became president.
   A military statement said officials were questioning the
arrested navy soldiers and some had admitted receiving bribes from
Honasan to help him escape. One told investigators that married men
in the group were given $100 and bachelors received $65 each, the
statement said.
   Officials said the group offered no resistance although they
were found in possession of 16 M-14 rifles, four M-16s, one light
machine gun, five Israeli-made Uzi machine guns and a grenade.
   They told authorities they didn't know where Honasan was hiding,
according to the military statement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
