<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PrisonScholarship Bjt   04-16 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prison Scholarship, Bjt,0599</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>College Scholarship Set Up In Name Of Convicted Murderer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOYT HARWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Samuel Howard lived a hard life, but the
money he saved while he was in prison on his third of three murder
convictions has been set aside to provide a brighter future for
other inmates.
   The University of Alabama at Tuscaloosa has established what is
believed to be the nation's first college scholarship for
prisoners, the $10,000 Samuel Howard Endowed Scholarship Fund.
   Of the $10,000, about $6,000 came from Social Security checks
that Howard, who died in 1986, had deposited in a bank in Dothan.
The joint bank account was set up by Howard and Jim Loftin, a
former employer who had befriended him, before Howard went to
prison for the third killing.
   Loftin and his wife, Marian, provided the rest of the money for
the fund.
   ``We wanted to put the money in something that would help other
people,'' she said in an interview last week. ``We felt that as
hard a time as he had in his life, there were people who helped him
in prison. It meant a lot to him. We wanted to do something in his
memory.''
   Howard ``didn't care about the money,'' Loftin said. ``He would
have loved to have a scholarship in his name.''
   Howard worked for the Loftins for five years, doing yard work
and helping in the warehouse at Loftin's moving and storage
business.
   State prison system records show Howard was convicted of two
counts of first-degree murder and one of assault with intent to
murder and was sentenced to two life terms plus 20 years in prison
in January 1952. He was paroled in 1961.
   Then, in 1975, he was sentenced to 40 years on a second-degree
murder conviction, said a prison spokeswoman. The records
immediately at hand gave few details of the crimes, she said.
   Howard died in the state prison's facility for aged and infirm
prisoners on July 20, 1986. Following his death, the Loftins
started exploring the idea of a scholarship in his memory.
   ``We couldn't find any university that had done that, and it was
difficult to work out the details because there was nothing like it
to go on. It was an idea that just happened,'' said Mrs. Loftin,
who is director of the university's regional office at Dothan.
   A university committee will administer the scholarship and
select recipients from among the prisoners who apply, starting next
January. ``It is not set up according to age, sex, race or
anything,'' Mrs. Loftin said. ``Anyone can apply.'' The state
prison system has more than 12,000 inmates.
   The university's College of Continuing Studies will help inmates
who want to take independent courses.
   ``Reports on illiteracy say people who have some kind of
educational development while in prison are less likely to be put
back in incarceration,'' Mrs. Loftin said.
   Despite his murder convictions, Howard ``was a very friendly
person,'' she said. ``He was uneducated but was very interested in
people. Our kids liked him and he liked them. It was a friendship.''
   The Loftin family occasionally visited Howard in prison and
often sent him items that he needed. ``He didn't have anybody that
we knew of, so we just kept in communication with him,'' said Mrs.
Loftin.
   ``We kept hoping that one day he would get a pardon,'' Mrs.
Loftin said. ``He told us, `If you need any money, you just take
it.' But we never did.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
