<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Gore     04-16 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gore,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore Says He Needs Strong Finish In New York To Remain Viable</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic candidate Albert Gore Jr., who
is trailing badly in voter preference polling for Tuesday's New
York primary, reiterated Saturday he had to pick up more support in
order to remain a viable candidate.
   ``At a minimum we have to have a strong finish to demonstrate
continued momentum,'' Gore said as he toured a market in the heart
of Buffalo's Polish community. ``But I'm not going to put specific
numbers on it.''
   In a poll released Friday by a Buffalo-based public research
firm, Goldhaber Associates, Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis
holds a comfortable lead among the Democrats with 43 percent, Jesse
Jackson was second with 28 percent and Gore had 8 percent.
   Twenty percent of the 367 Democrats surveyed by telephone on
Thursday and Friday said they were unsure whom they would vote for
in the primary. The poll had a margin of error of 5 percent.
   On Friday, Gore dismissed the figures, saying, ``The polls have
been consistently wrong about me.''
   He said there was time for him to improve his standing and that
several recent endorsements from state and local officials were
encouraging. New York City Mayor Ed Koch endorsed Gore on Thursday
and state Assembly Majority Leader James Tallon endorsed him
Friday. Gore picked up the endorsements of a city councilman and
state senator on Saturday.
   Many voters have not yet decided on the candidates and those who
have expressed a preference might still change their mind, he said.
As a result, support for the front-runners may not be as strong as
people think, he said.
   On another issue, Gore disagreed with party leaders, such as
Democratic National Committee Chairman Paul Kirk and New York Gov.
Mario Cuomo, who think the nomination should go to the candidate
with a plurality of votes.
   ``The rules provide that the candidate who has the majority of
the delegates becomes the nominee,'' Gore said. ``One or two people
can't change the rules of the Democratic Party. It has to be done
according to due process and that hasn't taken place.''
</TEXT>
