<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 6thLd-Writethru a0537 04-16 0803</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 6th Ld - Writethru, a0537,0825</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Riots Erupt, 13 Killed, After PLO Leader's Assassination</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with 13 dead. PICKS up 5th graf,
`The victims ...' EDITS to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOCELYN NOVECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GAZA CITY, Occupied Gaza Strip (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers today
killed 13 Palestinians, Arab and hospital reports said, in the
bloodiest day in four months of violence as riots erupted to
protest the assassination of a PLO leader.
   Up to 90 other Palestinians were wounded in the riots, according
to hospitals, U.N. officials and Arab journalists. Curfews were
slapped on 10 refugee camps.
   At least six Arabs killed in Gaza by army gunfire were from
refugee camps. A Palestinian from the village of Abasan, near Gaza
City, also died in a clash with soldiers.
   Reports said three of the dead were from the Jenin refugee camp
in the West Bank. It was not immediately clear where the others
deaths occurred.
   The victims ranged in age from 17 to 45.
   The army command, which is normally slow to confirm casualties,
said four Palestinians were killed, all in the Gaza Strip. It said
it did not have figures on the number of wounded.
   Violence broke out early in the morning in Gaza, where Khalil
al-Wazir, the assassinated PLO leader, lived at one time and had
relatives.
   Al-Wazir, also known as Abu Jihad, was the No. 2 official in
Yasser Arafat's Fatah group. He was killed today by a commando unit
of seven men and one woman in a suburban home near Tunis, Tunisia.
   Black flags of mourning flew across the West Bank and throughout
towns in the Gaza Strip.
   At a memorial service for al-Wazir held by family members, a
confrontation developed between Israeli soldiers who fired tear gas
and Palestinian youths, who raised the outlawed PLO flag and threw
stones.
   Women carrying black flags gathered on the roof, shouting
``Allahu Akbar,'' God is Great.
   Several shots were heard, and the group dispersed with no
injuries immediately evident.
   Reporters saw makeshift roadblocks and burning tires on nearly
every street in Gaza City. Palestinian youths, their faces masked
by kaffiyeh headdresses or shirts, stopped motorists and questioned
them.
   The fatalities, if confirmed, would equal the highest single-day
death toll since the uprising began Dec. 8.
   U.N. spokesman Bill Lee said 149 Palestinians had been killed in
riots not including today's clashes. Of those, 124 have died from
army gunfire. One Israeli soldier has been killed.
   Ariel Merari, a leading terrorism expert at Tel Aviv
University's Jaffee Center For Strategic Studies, predicted
al-Wazir's assassination would have a divisive effect on the
Palestinians.
   ``It is a blow to the morale of the Palestinians in the occupied
territories, but it could also arouse feelings of revenge,'' said
Merari.
   He said there was a strong possibility the assassination early
today was an outgrowth of a power struggle between al-Wazir and
Arafat over the appointment of commanders in southern Lebanon,
where the PLO was rebuilding its guerrilla force.
   But Merari also noted that al-Wazir had headed the PLO appartaus
that carried out thousands of military operations against Israel
since it seized the West Bank and Gaza in the 1967 Middle East war.
   Bassam Shakaa, the deposed mayor of Nablus in the West Bank,
blamed Israel for al-Wazir's assassination.
   ``No one else can benefit from his killing, only Israel and the
Zionists,'' said Shakaa, a hardline Palestinian leader whose legs
were blown off in a booby-trap car bomb attack by the Jewish
Underground.
   Ahmed al-Wazir, cousin and brother-in-law of the slain PLO
leader, held a memorial service in Gaza City that was attended by
thousands of Palestinians.
   ``All I can say is that Abu Jihad had been carrying his coffin
in his own hands for the past 30 years,'' al-Wazir said.
   Al-Wazir was born in the city of Ramle, now in Israel, and moved
to the Gaza Strip in 1948.
   Elias Freij, the mayor of the West Bank town of Bethlehem,
condemned the killing of Abu Jihad but said it was ``not easy to
point a finger at anyone'' until more was known.
   But he predicted the killing would have ``grave consequences.''
   Rashad Al Shawaa, the deposed mayor of Gaza City, said most
Palestinians were blaming Israel for the attack: ``I don't think
his death is going to stop the PLO from continuing its struggle.
Perhaps his death will create more support.''
   On Friday, hundreds of Jewish settlers defiantly marched in West
Bank hills and named a highway junction for a 15-year-old Israeli
girl who was killed along with two Palestinians in a clash in an
Arab village.
   Israeli soldiers surrounded mosques in the West Bank cities of
Hebron and Qalqilya and clamped a curfew on Khan Yunis in the Gaza
Strip to prevent violent protests after Moslem prayers.
</TEXT>
