<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HonestyPays     04-16 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Honesty Pays,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Finds $1,000 in Envelope; Saves Georgia Woman's Vacation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At first, Alice Lisquez thought the
$100 bill she pulled from an envelope was play money, and in a way
it was.
   A Georgia woman had sent in an order to Michigan Bulb Co. and
mistakenly enclosed 10 hundred-dollar bills that she had been
saving for her vacation.
   ``It never occurred to me to take it,'' Lisquez said.
   Lisquez, 47, found the big bucks about three weeks ago, tucked
into a $21.84 order for creeping phlox and peonies sent to the
company from Mary Duval of Dahlonega, Ga.
   Lisquez told her supervisor, Sue Barnstable, about her
discovery. Barnstable tracked down Duval and sent her a $1,000
check to her to replace the cash.
   On Thursday, Lisquez received a $100 bill and a silk scarf from
Duval as a reward. ``Lord, it's the least I could do,'' Duval said
Saturday.
   Duval, 63, a nurse, said the return of the money has saved a
month-long trip to England she has planned for later this year.
It'll be her first trip there.
   ``Dear Alice,'' Duval wrote in a letter enclosed with the scarf.
``I called your office to obtain your name and to thank you. I,
like you, am a working girl and I had saved most of (the money)
haphazardly and converted it to the $100 bills, as a twenty gets
easily spent.
   ``It was for a badly needed vacation, and thanks to you my plans
do not have to be changed.''
   A second note to Barnstable praised Lisquez for her honesty.
   ``I still have difficulty accepting the fact that there is basic
honesty practiced,'' Duval wrote. ``I would never have known what
happened to the money.''
   Office Manager Lyle Hansen said he has seen a few mistaken
mailings over the company's 43-year history, but never more than a
phone bill or house payment that got switched around in the
shuffle, and never before in cash.
</TEXT>
