<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis     04-16 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Questioned About Absence of Campaign in New York's Harlem</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis made one of his first
visits to Harlem on Saturday and was challenged by a critic who
said his presidential campaign was ignoring the area's black voters.
   During a breakfast with 40 black bankers, business and community
leaders, critic Robert La Prince said he saw no evidence that
Dukakis' campaign had waged any effort in Harlem and added it was a
mistake for him to write off the predominantly black neighborhood
despite rival Jesse Jackson's unquestioned strength.
   Dukakis responded, ``The Jackson campaign isn't that active in
Astoria,'' a reference to the Greek neighborhood of Queens where
the Massachusetts governor drew more than 2,000 people in an
emotional outpouring of support two days earlier.
   ``I understand Jesse's going to get the lion's share of the
votes in this community, and that's understandable,'' Dukakis said,
adding that he has enjoyed black support too.
   La Prince pressed him on the absence of even placards and
handbills. ``We'll get some signs out,'' Dukakis replied.
   La Prince, who described himself as president of the National
Council for Culture and Art, said later: ``It's evident the
campaign is ignoring the Harlem community ... I think it's
unfortunate.''
   Dukakis told reporters he couldn't recall if he had campaigned
in Harlem before, saying the visit was ``one of the first.''
   As Dukakis was confronted with the criticism, his campaign began
airing a radio commercial targeted at black audiences. The ad says
Dukakis has appointed blacks to top jobs while the ``Reagan-Bush
administration turned its back on Black Americans.'' It also
accuses Vice President George Bush, the inevitable GOP nominee, of
``cheerleading efforts to turn back the clock on equal
opportunity.''
   Dukakis flew upstate after spending the morning in New York
City, where he also walked with a small crowd along a street in an
Italian neighborhood in Queens.
   ``We're going to begin to work with communities _ that's what
America is all about,'' Dukakis said. ``I'm a community guy.''
   A young woman shouted a question to him about ``fiscal
discipline'' and followed up by asking if he would raise taxes.
   ``I hope not,'' Dukakis said and then repeated his call for
tougher enforcement of income taxes.
   He was throwing out the ceremonial first ball at a minor league
baseball game in Buffalo, where a light snow fell in a blustery
cold, and later joining Jackson and Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr.
for a League of Women Voters debate in Rochester.
   Dukakis' aides contended polls showed the New York race
tightening as Tuesday's primary drew closer. Dukakis sidestepped
questions about whether his candidacy could sustain a loss in New
York to Jackson, and contended he was not moved to over-confidence
by polls that showed him ahead.
   ``Assuming one is going to win because one is ahead in the polls
is very, very bad policy,'' the Massachusetts governor said.
</TEXT>
