<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-88 1424EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Fetuses-Research     04-16 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fetuses-Research,0651</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brain Cells From Aborted Fetus Used In Surgical Procedure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brain cells from an aborted fetus were implanted
into two Britons suffering from Parkinson's disease in a surgical
procedure banned in the United States, doctors said Saturday.
   The operations were the first of their kind in Britain, said
neurologist Edward Hitchcock, of the Midland Center for
Neurosurgery and Neurology.
   Hitchcock operated on a severely disabled 60-year-old woman
March 3 and on a 41-year-old man April 7.
   Both patients have been discharged from the hospital near
Birmingham in west-central England and have discontinued the
medication they were taking for the crippling disease, Hitchcock
said in a statement.
   The hospital would not release the patients' names nor that of
the woman whose aborted fetus was used in the procedure.
   Press Association, the domestic British news agency, and
Independent Television News said the woman was unaware that cells
from her aborted fetus had been transplanted. The hospital had no
immediate comment on the report.
   Parkinson's disease causes gradual loss of muscle control and is
potentially fatal. The implanted fetal tissue is believed to
stimulate production of dopamine, a brain chemical lacking in
people who suffer from Parkinson's.
   Hitchcock said the operations, performed under local anesthetic,
involve transplanting the fetus' cells into the patient's brain
through a surgical procedure that involves making a small hole in
the skull.
   The first documented use of the experimental procedure was
revealed in January, when surgeons in Mexico City said they
injected tissue from a miscarried fetus into the brains of two
Parkinson's sufferers last September.
   Researchers in Sweden also have reported using a similar
technique.
   ``The results obtained so far have been more than satisfactory,
giving a new revolution to world medical science, particularly in
the field of neurosurgery,'' the Mexican Social Security Institute
said in a statement in January.
   In Washington on Friday, government scientists were denied
permission to attempt the procedure because of legal, medical and
ethical questions.
   But the Department of Health and Human Services instructed the
National Institutes of Health to appoint an outside advisory
committee to examine the implications of using tissue from
intentionally aborted fetuses.
   The prohibition does not ban continuing research on tissue from
fetuses from miscarriages or stillbirths, but that type generally
is not feasible to use in the kind of transplant research the NIH
contemplated.
   Hitchcock, a professor of neurology at the University of
Birmingham, said the ethics of the procedure were reviewed by the
hospital's ethical committee. The government and the Medical
Research Council, which sets professional standards, were kept
informed, he said.
   ``We have been preparing for this kind of operation for several
years,'' he said. ``All the ethical issues have been carefully
considered over a very long period.''
   Hitchcock said the fetus involved was aborted ``well within the
time limits'' set by current British law and within a proposed law
before Parliament.
   Women in Britain now can have abortions until the 28th week of
pregnancy, although the proposed law would set a limit of 18 weeks.
   Dr. Michael Harrison, chairman of the Sandwell Health Authority,
which administers the hospital, said that if the ethical committee
had any doubts ``about anything, they turn it down.''
   ``Any research that is done, that has the benefits we hope to
have, is to be welcomed,'' Harrison said.
   ``Parkinson's disease is absolutely dreadful. It is a disease
that affects the brain and the patient's ability to think and to
move. It makes them shuffle along. It is dreadful and ultimately
fatal.''
   Hospital administrator Glyn James said fetal tissue is often
used for research in Britain.
   ``This is nothing like a brain transplant, or even a
quarter-brain transplant,'' he said. ``It only involves very, very
small pieces of cells.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
