<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DenisonPresident     04-16 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Denison President,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Denison President Says Resignation Coincidental To Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRANVILLE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of Denison University said
his resignation does not have anything to do with student protests
over a racial incident and called the timing ``a curious and
fateful irony.''
   Andrew G. De Rocco submitted his resignation Friday after four
years as president of the 2,200-student school. Charles A.
Brickman, chairman of Denison's board of trustees, said the board
accepted with regret.
   On Tuesday, De Rocco suspended two white students for the rest
of the current academic year. The University Judicial Board had
found them guilty of racially harassing a black student.
   The judicial board had ordered the students suspended for the
fall semester, but blacks said the punishment was lenient and last
week held rallies and called for class boycotts. The protest was
called off after De Rocco ordered the two white students off campus.
   ``My agonies about the next stage of my career began some months
ago. It's a curious and fateful irony that the other events were
coincidental,'' with the resignation, De Rocco said Friday night.
``It's accidental but not causal.''
   Denison spokesman Stewart B. Dyke said De Rocco was not
pressured by the trustees. ``The board voted a resolution fully
supporting the actions Andrew De Rocco took,'' Dyke said.
   De Rocco, 58, became president of the central Ohio liberal arts
college in 1984. He came to Denison from Trinity College in
Hartford, Conn., and had been a research physicist.
   ``As the time draws near for implementing Denison's long-range
plan, it has become clear to me that the commitment needed to
realize it would be more than I could reasonably give and still
contemplate future career options for myself,'' De Rocco said in a
news release issued Friday.
   Brickman said that Trustee William T. McConnell, president of
the Park National Corp. in Newark, would head a committee to search
for a successor.
</TEXT>
