<2ND_LINE>AM-Cinder Block Injury,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>College Tennis Player's Face Smashed When Cement Block Falls Off
Truck</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cinder block fell off a truck and
crashed through a car windshield, hitting a young woman driver in
the face and leaving her in serious condition Saturday after
surgery to rebuild facial bones, officials said.
   Reconstructive surgeons at Halifax Medical Center toiled for
nine hours on Mary Stoll, 20, after the Thursday accident about 10
miles east of DeLand.
   ``Apparently she can hear us but she doesn't respond,'' said her
father, Tom Stoll, who kept a vigil over his daughter's bed in the
intensive care unit.
   Miss Stoll was alone when cinder blocks came loose on a
westbound flatbed truck driven by Furman Mitchum, 37, of Edgewater.
After the block crashed through her windshield, her car veered off
the road and hit a small palm tree.
   No charges had been filed but police said Mitchum, who works for
Tarmac Florida Inc., could be charged with driving with an unsafe
load.
   ``It's not legal for your load to be shifting or dropping or
blowing, in the case of sand,'' said Florida Highway Patrol trooper
Gary Schluter.
   ``As far as I know it was secured properly,'' Tarmac manager
Ronald Sweeney said of the truck.
   Miss Stoll, a junior from Bradenton, ranked No. 1 in singles and
last year was voted the most valuable player of her Stetson
University women's tennis team.
</TEXT>
