<DOCNO> AP880416-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-88 1521EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Jordan-Blast     04-16 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jordan-Blast,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Killed When Civil Defense Truck Hits Building, Bomb Explodes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded Saturday in a parking lot,
and a fire truck rushing to the scene crashed into a building and
killed five people, officials reported.
   Jordanian officials blamed Israel for the bombing. A spokesman
for the Israeli Foreign Ministry said such accusations were
``nonesense.''
   The explosion was the second in a week.
   An spokesman for the Interior Ministry said the blast started a
fire in a parking lot in the basement of the city's six-story
municipality building in downtown Amman but caused no casualties.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the bomb
had been placed under a car and contained 1.1 pounds of explosives.
   The official Jordan News Agency quoted a government spokesman as
saying the bombing ``took place after Jordan explained its position
in supporting the Arab rights in Palestine.''
   ``This act was carried out by a group ... recruited as agents
and traitors by our enemy (Israel),'' the spokesman said, without
elaboration.
   A security colonel at the scene said the car, which was empty,
caught fire.
   As the fire truck was rushing to the scene it sped out of
control on a steep hill and smashed into a building. Five people
were killed and four others were seriously injured.
   The driver and another civil defense worker were among the dead.
   A civil defense spokesman said the driver drove the truck into
the building because ``he was trying to avoid killing people'' on
crowded sidewalks.
   ``He was leaning out the window screaming `get out of the way,'
as he headed toward the building,'' a witness said.
</TEXT>
