<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People     04-16 0940</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0973</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Douglas Fairbanks Jr. may have been a
romantic leading man on and off screen in his heyday, but don't
expect a lot of kiss-and-tell stories in ``The Salad Days,'' the
first installment of a two-volume autobiography.
   ``I don't like washing dirty linen or telling tales,''
Fairbanks, 78, said in a recent interview. ``I don't like done to
me and I don't like it done to other people. Nobody likes it. I
didn't write this to make a lot of money. If it does become a best
seller that's fine. If it doesn't, the kids will enjoy reading
about another generation.''
   Fairbanks, whose films included ``The Dawn Patrol,'' ``Prisoner
of Zenda'' and ``Gunga Din,'' was married briefly to Joan Crawford
and had romances with such leading ladies as Gertrude Lawrence and
Marlene Dietrich.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LEEDS, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rock star Michael Jackson has pledged more
than $130,000 to help provide immunizations for children in
developing countries, a British charity announced Saturday.
   Give for Life, a charity based in Leeds, said Jackson has
promised to make the donation from proceeds of a concert he is to
give in this northern England city on Aug. 29.
   The charity is trying to raise $1.9 million to immunize 40,000
children against diseases such as measles, diptheria, polio and
tuberculosis.
   A Jackson spokesman, Jonathan Morrish, said: ``This is something
that Michael wanted to do because he is visiting Leeds. He does
this sort of thing quite often in America when there is an
association between a particular charity and a city where he is
playing.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former automaker John Z. De Lorean has filed a
$610 million federal lawsuit against several lawyers and
accountants, claiming they conspired to destroy his business
operations and personal reputation.
   In the suit filed Friday in U.S. District Court in San Diego, De
Lorean said the lawyers and accountants maliciously prosecuted him
in violation of federal racketeering laws, the Detroit Free Press
reported Saturday.
   He added that the group's actions caused him emotional distress
and damaged his business.
   De Lorean settled his car company's bankruptcy case in August,
when he agreed to pay $9.36 million to creditors.
   Those named in the suit include Sheldon Toll and Robert Weiss,
lawyers for the Detroit firm of Honigman Miller Schwartz & Cohn;
Yale Levin, an accounting executive who has worked for Price
Waterhouse & Co. in Detroit; and a group of British accountants,
the newspaper said.
   ``All the things people said about me were fabricated,'' De
Lorean said. ``These people cost me a lot of money to defend myself
and I think it's only right they be held accountable.''
   Weiss called the suit ``utterly preposterous,'' the Free Press
said Saturday. It said most of those named in the suit couldn't be
reached for comment.
   The De Lorean Motor Co. went bankrupt after De Lorean was
arrested on cocaine trafficking charges in 1981.
   He was acquitted of the cocaine charges in Los Angeles federal
court and later was cleared of racketeering charge in Detroit
federal court. In the latter case, he was accused of defrauding
investors of $8.5 million.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DEEP GAP, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doc Watson, the blind entertainer who is
an icon of traditional mountain music, says he's still not sure
when he will retire.
   Since a tractor overturned and killed his son at his own farm
near Lenoir 2{ years ago, Watson, 65, has wrestled with thoughts of
quitting. He announced his retirement early this year, but
rescinded the decision last month.
   ``I've always told everybody I'd like to quit the road when I'm
still able to carry in a stick of firewood or do a chore around
here,'' Watson said.
   ``I was going to quit the end of June, then next March. Let's
just leave it hang right now.''
   The Grammy Award-winner and more than 20 other performers will
appear at a festival in Wilkesboro on April 30 and May 1 to raise
money for the ``Eddy Merle Watson Garden of the Senses,'' a garden
for the blind named for Watson's late son, at Wilkes Community
College.
   Other performers include Chet Atkins, Grandpa Jones, Earl
Scruggs, Mac Wiseman, Tony Rice, John Hartford, the New-grass
Revival, George Hamilton IV, David Holt, the Moody Brothers and
Mike Cross.
   The garden will consist of raised planters containing fragrant
plants that appeal to the sense of touch. All plants will be
identified in Braille. There will be a small stone memorial to the
younger Watson.
   Watson believes his son, who died at age 36, deserves a
memorial. For himself, Watson wants only ``a small bunch of
old-fashioned marigolds.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trumpeter Al Hirt, who's been plagued by trouble
with his playing arm, was released from the hospital Saturday
morning ready to to resume performing immediately, a hospital
spokeswoman said.
   Hirt returned to Methodist Hospital on April 6 to be treated for
inflammation of tendons in his right hand and arm, spokeswoman
Brenda Blake said.
   The inflammation was related to an infection he had in the same
hand and arm for which he underwent treatment last month at
Methodist.
   Dr. Michael DeBakey, Hirt's physician and friend, is optimistic
about the musician's recovery.
   ``We have recommended that he continue taking antibiotics and
rest his hand and arm between performances for the next two to
three weeks,'' DeBakey said. ``The long-term prognosis for his hand
is excellent and he can return to his performing engagements
immediately.''
   His manager, Gwen Campbell, said Hirt was to resume his normal
schedule Saturday night, appearing in Sioux Falls, S.D., with the
Sioux Falls Symphony.
</TEXT>
