<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador-MayorSlain     04-16 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Mayor Slain,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unidentified Gunmen Kidnap, Kill Salvadoran Mayor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen believed to be leftist
guerrillas kidnapped and killed the rightist mayor of a small
northeastern town, a provincial governor said Saturday.
   Morazan province governor Francisco Valenzuela said in a
telephone interview that the mayor of San Isidro, Pedro Ventura,
was kidnapped on Thursday and his bullet-riddled body was found on
nearby road on Friday, but gave no further details.
   Valenzuela said he and police investigators believe the gunmen
belonged to the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, a
coalition of five guerrilla groups that has been fighting for power
since October 1979.
   The guerrillas have several strongholds in Morazan province,
especially a few miles north of San Isidro. The town is 107 miles
northeast of San Salvador.
   Ventura, 55, was a member of the Republican Nationalist
Alliance, a rightist group, which won control of the National
Legislature in elections March 20.
   Its founder, retired army Maj. Roberto d'Aubuisson, has been
linked by press reports to rightist death squads, which have hunted
down and killed suspected leftist guerrillas for many years.
D'Aubuisson has repeatedly denied the accusations.
   In a related development, police sources said a group of
guerrillas attacked a coffee plantation northwest of the capital on
Friday night and set fire to several warehouses and other buildings.
   The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
rebels attacked the Colombia coffee plantation outside
Quezaltepeque, 15 miles northwest of the capital. They said no one
was hurt.
</TEXT>
