<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DemocratsText     04-16 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democrats Text,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Trade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a transcript of the Democratic radio
address, delivered Saturday by Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill.,
chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee:
   This is Congressman Dan Rostenkowski of Illinois. I'd like to
talk to you about the trade legislation that is nearing completion
in Congress.
   For too many years, the United States has been without a
coherent trade policy. This has been true in both Democratic and
Republican administrations. Trade has simply been ignored and the
effect of this inattention has been devastating. In the space of a
few years, we have gone from being the world's largest creditor
nation to the world's largest debtor. The result has been the loss
of American jobs and a growing dependence on foreign investment.
   In the coming weeks, we will have an opportunity to begin the
reversal of this alarming trend. The House and Senate are about to
approve and send to the president the most comprehensive trade bill
ever considered in the Congress. This legislation is the result of
a three-year, bipartisan effort to develop a strong, cohesive trade
policy _ one that is designed to open markets, centralize our trade
decision-making process and assist U.S. workers.
   The legislative process has been both time-consuming and
controversial. We had to resist strong protectionist sentiments
that demanded we erect our own trade barriers. We also had to
overcome a ``business as usual'' indifference on the part of the
current administration.
   Our legislative goal was a trade bill that was so strong our
trading partners could not ignore it and so fair that the president
would have to sign it. I think we've succeeded.
   The message this bill sends to our trading partners is strong
and clear: We expect their markets to be open to U.S. goods. We
streamline the process of resolving trade disputes. We give our
trade negotiator the tools to attack trade agreement violations and
we require him to use those tools. But our message is not one of
belligerence, it simply says we want fair trade. I have met with
foreign trade ministers in Europe and Asia. They not only expect
this message, they accept it.
   Like any bill of this size and scope, the legislation is not
perfect. At various stages, it has been criticized. The president,
in particular, has been a vocal critic of several provisions. I had
hoped for greater cooperation from the president in the development
of the bill, but he elected instead to simply list his objections.
Although this made it difficult to reach compromises, the final
product addresses many of the president's concerns.
   Many doubted we could agree on a strong trade bill that avoided
protectionist measures. In fact, many in the administration were
hoping for a bill that was so protectionist the president could
easily veto it. Well, they are going to be disappointed.
   In recent days, I've heard complaints that we've gone too far
and complaints that we have not gone far enough. My 30 years as a
legislator tells me that when a bill is attacked by both sides,
it's probably pretty good legislation.
   The Congress has done a responsible job in strengthening our
trade laws and avoiding protectionist measures. Now it's up to the
president. It took us three years to get this far. We can't afford
to let our trade policy drift any longer. The president can put us
on the right course by signing this landmark legislation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
