<DOCNO> AP880416-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-88 1602EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BridgeProtest 2ndLd-Writethru a0587 04-16 0857</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bridge Protest, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0587,0874</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Politician Chains Himself to Outer Banks Bridge</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8-9th grafs pvs, ``Lawrence, who xxx, with 2 grafs,
Lawrence taking chain off several times, wife and son on scene;
SUBS 16th graf, ``Orman Mann xxx, with 4 grafs, no comment from
gov's spokesman, more comment from bystanders</NOTE>
<DATELINE>OREGON INLET, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state senate candidate toting 50
paperback novels chained himself to the only bridge that leads to
Cape Hatteras and pledged Saturday to stay there until action is
taken to save the bridge from erosion.
   Dan Lawrence, who owns a mobile-home park in the Outer Banks
community of Frisco on Hatteras Island, attached his leg to a fence
along the catwalk of the Herbert C. Bonner bridge over Oregon Inlet
on Friday morning.
   ``I'm going to stay here until they carry me away. This is
something the governor is going to have to think about because he's
the man who needs to act on this. We need positive action,'' the
42-year-old Republican said Saturday.
   Lawrence, who took along raingear, the paperbacks, a transistor
radio and a cooler full of non-alcoholic beverages, said he has
also started a hunger strike.
   The 3{-mile structure, the only route from the mainland to the
island's vacation and fishing communities, was threatened by heavy
erosion from a storm Wednesday that also damaged 30 homes along the
Outer Banks.
   Gov. Jim Martin flew in Thursday and called for jetties to
stabilize Oregon Inlet's shifting sands. A project authorized by
Congress 17 years ago has never been built, mostly due to
opposition from environmentalists and the U.S. Department of the
Interior. They say jetties won't work in the long run and would be
environmentally hazardous.
   Lawrence, who keeps the key to the padlock in his boot, took the
chain off several times Saturday to get his circulation going. His
wife, Karen, and son, Matthew, were with him Saturday afternoon.
They brought food but Lawrence, who said he has only had water,
chicken broth and apple juice, refused it.
   ``I felt like the loneliest man in the world (Friday night),''
Lawrence told Outer Banks radio station WOBR. ``I've never been
through an experience like that _ just bone-chilling.''
   An officer at the Coast Guard's Oregon Inlet station said
Lawrence had weathered a thunderstorm and several showers
overnight. The National Weather Service said the temperature at
Oregon Inlet was 47 degrees Friday night, with temperatures
Saturday night expected to drop to 40 to 45 degrees.
   ``I might go to the end of the bridge and sleep in my truck ...
to keep away from the wind. I'm still keeping up my hunger
strike,'' said Lawrence. ``I don't know what's going to happen ...
I'm about ready to drop now.''
   State transportation officials said about 275 feet of shoreline
near the southern end of the bridge was washed away during last
week's storm. If the rapid erosion continues, the base of the
bridge would be vulnerable to waves and undercutting.
   W.D. Campbell, an engineer with the state Division of Highways,
said better weather had reduced the threat. But he said the
long-range threat remained and that state agencies were continuing
to draw up plans to protect the bridge.
   ``The bridge is going to be washed away with the next nor'easter
that comes through here,'' said Lawrence at a Friday news
conference. ``The result is going to be catastrophe for Hatteras
Island. People will die.''
   ``I believe a person can live about 30 days (without food), and
I'm prepared to stay here until I die,'' said Lawrence, wearing a
red cap and sitting in a chair at the end of a catwalk about a
quarter-mile from the Hatteras Island side of the bridge.
   ``My mother lives here. A lot of people's mothers, fathers and
grandparents live here,'' he said.
   Karen Hayes Rotterman, a spokeswoman for Gov. Jim Martin, said
Martin would have no comment.
   Orman Mann, chairman of the Dare County Oregon Inlet and
Waterways Commission, which has been fighting for the jetties, said
he thought Lawrence's act ``shows the frustration of the local
people.''
   Pat Mullaney, of Charlottesville, Va., who was fishing on the
bridge and knows the area, was more skeptical, saying ``I wish they
would do something, but I'm not sure this will get it done.''
   Lawrence said 30 to 40 people have talked to him since Friday.
``A couple of people have gone by and yelled out I'm a kook.'' But
he said ``everyone has a right to an opinon.''
   Linda Morris, a state assistant attorney general, said Lawrence
can remain chained to the bridge as long as he doesn't cause a
nuisance.
   The Outer Banks are a line of islands off the North Carolina
shore made of sand that is pushed and shaped by storms and tides.
Many buildings have been threatened and washed away in years past.
   Hatteras Island, which has about 4,800 year-round residents, is
about 50 miles long and never more than a few miles wide; there has
also been controversy over how and whether to move the historic
Cape Hatteras lighthouse, which has also been threatened by the
ever-encroaching sea.
</TEXT>
