<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHAPEL HILL, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police couldn't put the collar on any
of the naked men who played a game of basketball next to a private
dormitory complex near the University of North Carolina at Chapel
Hill.
   The X-rated game Thursday night would have been covered up had
it not been for a Granville Towers resident who called police. The
athletes peeled off running as police arrived, and a group of women
booed the cops for chasing the men away.
   A police report, filed Friday by Public Safety Officer Woody
Sands Minton, said:
   ``A group of about 10 nude males were playing basketball at
Granville. They had attracted the attention of 100 or so coeds with
varying focuses of attention. The suspects ran upon the approach of
the police car. The coeds booed. No suspects were caught.''
   The incident occurred about 10 p.m. Thursday at the basketball
court located near Granville Towers, three high-rise dormitories
just west of campus.
   Police didn't say when they thought the case would be wrapped up.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FORT COLLINS, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 10-month-old llama named Kosha has
become the first llama ever to get an artificial leg, and she seems
to be zipping around happily on the high-tech device, Colorado
State University veterinarians say.
   ``It's remarkable how easily she has adjusted,'' said Frank
Garry of CSU's Veterinary Teaching Hospital. ``She goes scooting
off when she has her artificial leg on. She enjoys having four legs
again.''
   Kosha lost much of her right front leg last December when she
got tangled in fence wire. She was part of a herd of 30 llamas
owned by Rudyard and Katharine Nelson, and their son, Jim, at a
farm near Kimball, Neb.
   In many cases when a large animal's limb is severely injured,
the animal has to be put to death because fitting artificial limbs
is so difficult. But veterinarians were able to replace the lower
part of Kosha's leg with materials developed for the space shuttle.
   Kosha was fitted with the device Wednesday. Officials say she
moved somewhat awkwardly at first, but soon was getting around with
few problems.
   The leg was designed to withstand almost all-day use without
causing sores and discomfort. It is expected to be weather
resistant and will allow natural movement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880416-0111 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-88 1624EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     04-16 0582</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0604</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghan Rebels Denounce Accord, Bombs Kill 5</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Najib, one name, is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan rebel leaders told 75,000
supporters Saturday they will fight on despite an accord to
withdraw Soviet troops from Afghanistan. Two nearby bomb explosions
killed five people.
   But Afghan President Najib, speaking in Kabul, warned the rebels
that they will face the ``iron will'' of his people after the
Soviet troops leave. His government controls about 75,000 troops.
   In Islamabad, Pakistan's acting foreign minister returned from
Geneva Saturday and predicted that Afghanistan's communist
government will fall quickly after the Soviet withdrawal.
   On Thursday in Geneva, the United States, Soviet Union, Pakistan
and Afghanistan signed an agreement to begin withdrawing an
estimated 115,000 Soviet troops from Afghanistan on May 15.
   Pakistan represented the guerrillas at the talks, but the
insurgents have vowed to oppose any agreement without their
participation. The Soviets have been helping the Marxist government
fight the Moslem insurgents since 1979.
   The guerrillas, known as Mujahedeen, are believed to number
about 200,000. They are based in Pakistan and receive support from
that country, as well as the United States, China, Iran, and other
nations.
   The two explosions near Peshawar Saturday also wounded at least
11 people. No one claimed responsibility, but Pakistani authorities
have blamed a wave of bombings in the past two years on the Afghan
secret police.
   In the village of Rajjar, about 40 miles north of Peshawar, four
people, including two women and a child, were killed and 10 wounded
when a 4-pound bomb went off in a waiting room of a bus station.
   One person was killed in another bomb explosion in Landi Kotal,
on Pakistan's border with Afghanistan.
   The guerrilla leaders told the insurgents and refugees in a
stadium in this border city that they will fight until they topple
the Afghan government.
   Ahmed Shah, a guerrilla designated by the rebel alliance to head
an all-rebel interim government, stood in the 95-degree heat and
told the crowd his administration would soon move into Afghanistan.
He gave no deadline.
   ``We'll stay with you in Afghanistan, in the caves and snow, not
in Pakistan,'' he said.
   Despite the withdrawal agreement, the United States and Pakistan
have vowed to continue supplying arms to the rebels until the
Soviet Union ceases its aid to the Kabul government. The Kremlin
says it will continue supporting the Kabul government.
   Pakistan's acting Foreign Minister Zain Noorani said he expected
the Afghan government to fall soon after the Soviets withdraw.
   ``I do not have any doubt about it. (The Kabul government) has
been rejected by the people of Afghanistan,'' he was quoted as
saying by the official Pakistani news agency APP.
   Noorani said Afghan guerrillas control more than 80 percent of
their country.
   The official Soviet news agency Tass quoted Najib as saying he
no longer needs Soviet support because the Geneva accord guarantees
his country's sovereignty. Pakistan and Afghanistan pledge not to
interfere in one another's affairs in the agreement.
   Najib said his government would need the help of Afghan refugees
to stave off the rebels. He called on the refugees, who number
about five million and live in Pakistan and Iran, to return home
and offered to help them set up armed units.
   Under the Geneva accord, the Soviet Union will pull half its
troops out of Afghanistan in three months and the rest after six
additional months.
   Many U.S. analysts believe Najib's government will collapse
during or after the Soviet withdrawal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
