<1ST_LINE>u i AM-PLOSlaying-Reax     04-16 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PLO Slaying-Reax,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arab Nations, PLO Factions Outraged By Leader's Slaying</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-PLO-Slaying, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Palestine Liberation Organization's
nine factions all condemned the assassination Saturday of the
movement's deputy commander and vowed revenge, displaying unity
after years of fragmentation.
   Khalil al-Wazir and three of his bodyguards were killed by seven
armed men and a woman who burst into al-Wazir's home in suburban
Tunis, Tunisia.
   Among the Arab nations expressing outrage over the slayings were
Jordan, Iraq, Tunisia, Kuwait and Egypt _ all countries in which
al-Wazir, 52, had lived after the 1948 Arab-Israeli war and Israeli
independence.
   Saudi Arabia, Bahrain and the United Arab Emirates also
denounced the assassination.
   Syria, which had declared al-Wazir unwelcome following the
government's 1983 feud with PLO chief Yasser Arafat, said it would
receive al-Wazir's body if it was flown for burial in Damascus,
where his parents live.
   Hundreds of grieving Palestinians gathered outside the Damascus
residence of his 80-year-old father, Ibrahim al-Wazir, to offer
sympathy.
   The various PLO factions issued similarly worded statements
vowing revenge.
   ``We will avenge the blood of our martyr,'' said statements by
Saiqa, the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine _ General
Command, and the Popular Struggle, the three Damascus-based groups
at odds with PLO chief Yasser Arafat's mainstream leadership.
Arafat is the head of Fatah, the largest group in the PLO, and
al-Wazir was Fatah's military commander.
   The Fatah-Uprising, a dissident faction that broke away from the
PLO in 1983, said in its statement: ``The crime aims at liquidating
the uprising and boosting the morale of the Zionist army,'' a
reference to the Palestinian rioting that has left more than 160
Arabs dead in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip since Dec.8.
   The Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine, Democratic
Front for the Liberation of Palestine, the Arab Liberation Front
and the Palestine Liberation Front all praised Al-Wazir as ``a
national hero'' and vowed to strike at Israel.
   Fatah, which was founded by Arafat and al-Wazir, was the most
grieved and a spokesman for the group called the slain leader a
``national hero ... who has fallen victim of the Israeli bloodbath''
   ``A promise to the martyr: His mission will continue and his
blood will be avenged,'' Fatah said.
   The PLO blamed Israel's Mossad intelligence service for the
killing. There was no official reaction from the Israeli government.
   In Cairo, Butros Ghali, Egyptian minister of state for foreign
affairs, said: ``Egypt strongly condemns the assassination of Mr.
Khalil al-Wazir.
   Tunisian President Zine Al-abidine Ben Ali set up a special
committee to supervise a search for the killers.
   The emir of Kuwait, Sheik Jaber Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah, allocated a
pension for Al-Wazir's widow and five children. The amount was not
given.
</TEXT>
