<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson-Indians     04-16 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Indians,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Urges Native Americans To Vote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NIAGARA FALLS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Native Americans, who generally do
not vote as a matter of principle, must get involved in the
nation's political process in order to improve life on the
reservation, Democratic presidential hopeful Jesse Jackson said
Saturday.
   ``We want to reach out to them and urge them to vote,'' Jackson
said at a rally at an Indian museum. ``So many Native Americans
have simply been broken-hearted. They've been hurt so long they
feel a sense of betrayal. We have to get them involved.''
   Jackson urged Indians to join his Rainbow Coalition of
minorities and workers. He said racism and poverty experienced by
Indians was no different from that of blacks and other minorities.
   While some Native American communities have become involved in
American politics, New York is a stronghold for sovereign Indian
governments, such as the Six Nations of the Iroquois Confederacy.
Most of the tribes in the confederacy believe that voting would
abrogate the treaties establishing their reservations as distinct
nations.
   Tribal governments are on guard against any incursion by
non-Indians and have often rejected economic development they could
not control. Partly as a result, the reservations have unusually
high unemployment rates.
   ``We all want the same things _ dignity, respect, and equal
opportunity,'' Jackson told about 800 people who gathered at the
Native American Center for the Living Arts on the banks of the
Niagara River near the Falls. Most of the crowd was black.
   Wanda Shoe, a director of the Native American center, said that
while most Indians are not even registered to vote, many identify
with Jackson as a candidate.
   ``He's the only one who has demonstrated any interest in us,''
Shoe said, adding that the candidate was causing many Indians to
re-evaluate themselves. She said she's not registered to vote, nor
are members of her family and most friends.
   ``We see what he is doing for black people,'' she said. ``It's
hard not to get excited by it.''
   Jackson spoke for almost an hour, calling for a war on drugs, an
increase in the minimum wage, better educational opportunites and
more money spent rebuilding roads and bridges.
   His supporters often interrupted him with chants of ``Win,
Jesse, Win''
   Following the speech, the directors of the center gave Jackson a
necklace and a printed shirt that read ``Remember Us, Native
Americans.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
