<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-16 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow Across Northern New England, Rain In West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A slow-moving storm system Saturday dumped up to 11 inches of
snow heavy enough to pull down power lines in New England, while
rain was scattered across the West.
   Scattered light snow blew across parts of New York state and
northern and western Pennsylvania.
   In Maine, 11 inches of snow fell at Upton, on the New Hampshire
border, with more possible by Sunday morning. Southern sections of
the western Maine mountains received as much as 8 inches. In New
Hampshire, Dixville got 6 inches.
   The heavy, wet snow in Maine snapped tree branches and broke
power lines, leaving some 13,000 customers without electricity,
utilities officials said.
   ``A storm this time of the year is the worst nightmare for us
because it is always heavy and we can always count on these types
of problems,'' said Frank Chiaravalloti of Central Maine Power Co.
   Maine state police said they received reports of more than 100
traffic accidents, but no serious injuries were reported.
   The snow frustrated golfers and minor league baseball fans in
Maine, but it didn't stop the 22nd annual Kenduskeag Stream canoe
race. Several hundred people donned wet suits and lowered canoes,
kayaks and tire tubes into the stream at Bangor to race or lollygag
amid the snow.
   Showers and thunderstorms extended from Arizona across New
Mexico into northwestern Texas, while rain and a few thunderstorms
extended across south-central Texas.
   In the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT, 1.01 inches of rain fell at
Tucumcari, N.M.
   Elsewhere in the West, showers were scattered over Nevada, Utah
and Arizona. Rain also fell along sections of the northern Pacific
Coast.
   Temperatures were only in the 30s and 40s from the upper Ohio
Valley across the northern and central Appalachians to the northern
half of the Atlantic Coast. Highs only in the 40s were common over
northern New Mexico and northern Arizona and in the mountains of
southern Utah and southern Colorado.
   Freeze warnings were posted overnight over the West Virginia's
Eastern Panhandle, western Maryland, northwestern Virginia,
southeastern Pennsylvania, and inland sections of southern New
Jersey. Frost warnings were issued for the rest of Maryland and
interior Virginia, as well as inland sections of the Carolinas.
   Record low temperatures were posted at Key West, Fla., with 59
degrees, and at Nashville, Tenn., with 28 degrees.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 30
degrees at Johnstown, Pa., and Limestone, Maine, to 83 in Florida
at Miami, Crestview and Fort Myers. The low for the day was 19
degrees at Marquette, Mich.
   For Sunday, showers and thunderstorms were forecast from
Colorado across Kansas, Oklahoma and northern and eastern Texas to
the lower half of the Mississippi Valley. Scattered showers were
forecast across the Rockies and the southwestern half of Texas.
Scattered rain was forecast along the northern half of the Pacific
Coast. More snow was forecast over northern Maine, with scattered
rain or snowshowers elsewhere across northern and central New
England and eastern New York state, and over Upper Michigan.
   Highs only in the 40s and 50s were predicted from the Dakotas to
Upper Michigan and northern Lower Michigan, and across New York
state and New England; in the 50s over Montana, southern Wyoming,
Colorado and the Arizona mountains; in the 80s over southern Texas
and the Florida Peninsula, and over parts of the central Gulf Coast
and the desert Southwest, and in the 60s or 70s over most of the
rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
