<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OfficerCharged     04-16 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Officer Charged,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former State Trooper Charged With Raping Two Girls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAPEER, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A recently retired state trooper who used
to give speeches about child abuse has been charged with sexually
assaulting two girls while on the force, authorities said.
   Robert L. Beadle, 52, of Traverse City was arraigned earlier
this month on charges of criminal sexual conduct, kidnapping and
felony use of a firearm.
   He is accused of abducting and raping at gunpoint an 11-year-old
Lapeer girl in 1986 and a 13-year-old Lapeer girl in 1987. In each
case, the girl told police the assailant forced her off her bicycle
and into his car.
   Beadle worked in Traverse City from 1970 to 1985 and then at the
state police central office in Lansing until he retired in December.
   In Traverse City, he did school liaison and investigation of sex
crimes, said district commander Capt. John Cosgrove. His duties
included traveling the state giving speeches about child abuse.
   His most recent job involved training officers around in
computerized record-keeping, police said.
   Beadle, who was arraigned April 6, is free on $1,000 bond and
faces a preliminary examination Friday in Lapeer, a town east of
Fling and roughly 200 miles from Traverse City. If convicted, he
could face life imprisonment.
   Authorities said police first suspected Beadle last fall while
investigating a traffic accident in Traverse City that Beadle had
with an unmarked police car.
   While searching Beadle's car, officers found Beadle had police
artists' sketches of the suspect in the sexual assaults and
wondered why Beadle would have them. They also noticed a
resemblance to Beadle.
   Beadle was later identified by each victim in a photograph
lineup and then again in a physical lineup, said Lapeer County
Prosecutor Nick O. Holowka.
   A weapon described by the victims in both cases matched the type
of gun issued almost exclusively to state police officers,
authorities said.
</TEXT>
