<HEAD>Reporter Plays Key Role In Ending Armed Standoff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURLINGTON, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cub reporter kept an armed man on the
telephone for three hours and helped persuade him to surrender
Saturday after the man barricaded himself in his home to draw
attention to the drug problem.
   Raymond A. Garcia, 36, fired several shots in his home during
the seven-hour siege. No one was injured.
   Garcia had armed himelf with an AK-47 combat rifle, police said.
Neighbors were evacuated and police and agents from the state
Division of Criminal Investigation urged him to surrender by
telephone.
   Diana Reed, 23, who has worked for radio station KBUR for three
months, said she got a call from Garcia late Friday. ``I initially
had a reporter reaction,'' Miss Reed said. But she emerged as a key
player in resolving the standoff.
   ``I felt like it was all on my shoulders. The police and the DCI
kept telling me to stay on the line,'' she said.
   Garcia said that his 16-year-old son had a drug problem but that
police refused his request that they arrest the teen-ager and send
him to a drug dependency center, Miss Reed said.
   Garcia said he did not want to go to jail and threatened to
leave the house firing into the air so police would have to shoot
him, Miss Reed said.
   She advised him to surrender so police could answer his
complaints. He finally agreed on the condition that he not be taken
to jail.
   Garcia was taken to a hospital for a psychiatric evaluation,
said police Lt. David Wunnenberg. The man was charged with a
misdemeanor count of discharging a firearm, said Capt. Robert Sloan.
   ``I'm going to look into what he said,'' Miss Reed said. ``I
guess it takes arrest or charges filed by police to get children
into a drug rehabilitation program.''
   Police said four to six shots were fired during the siege but
were not aimed at anyone outside the house.
</TEXT>
