<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SchoolTax     04-16 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-School Tax,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Christian School to Let IRS `Steal' Taxes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICEVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rocky Bayou Christian School says it
will let the Internal Revenue Service ``steal'' four years of
Social Security taxes it has refused to pay on grounds they violate
religious freedom.
   The non-denominational school of more than 300 students agreed
Friday to place nearly $90,600 in a bank account that the IRS can
then seize, said school director Bob Grete.
   ``Since we are not going to write a check for that amount,
they're going to steal it,'' Grete said. ``Neither side can
tolerate continuing this conflict.''
   IRS officials who met with Grete at the school Friday declined
comment.
   The school has refused to pay Social Security contributions for
its employees since 1984, claiming the levy amounts to a tax on God.
   The IRS withheld efforts to force collection until the U.S.
Supreme Court last month refused to hear an appeal in a similar
case involving the Bethel Baptist Church of Sellersville, Pa.
   ``We have an obligation to proclaim the authority of God. We're
being asked by human government to do what God would forbid,''
Grete said. ``We can't pay the tax. Sin is sin regardless of
whether the Supreme Court will give us a hearing or not.''
</TEXT>
