<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-88 1816EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PTLFuture     04-16 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PTL Future,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trustee: Moral Bankruptcy Led to Financial Bankruptcy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT MILL, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The trustee for the financially troubled
PTL ministry says he will try to save its religious activities,
even if it means selling its Heritage USA theme park.
   ``PTL is something much more important than a water park or a
hotel,'' David Clark said Friday. ``The heart of PTL must be the
ministry.''
   During a hearing Friday, U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Rufus Reynolds,
who extended the deadline for PTL to present a bankruptcy
reorganization plan by two weeks to May 16, said it ``looks like
the end of the road'' for the ministry.
   PTL officials told Reynolds at the hearing in Greensboro, N.C.,
that they couldn't raise the $5.7 million needed by the previous
deadline of May 2.
   Reynolds ordered Clark to present a plan that would enable the
ministry built by Jim and Tammy Bakker to sell whatever is
necessary while continuing to operate.
   ``It's definitely a liquidation,'' Reynolds said. ``It's just a
matter of how orderly a liquidation.''
   The Internal Revenue Service is seeking more than $55 million in
back taxes and opposes PTL's plan to qualify as a tax-exempt
organization.
   PTL plans to sell 1,700 undeveloped acres it owns on the South
Carolina-North Carolina border and a small attraction at Heritage
USA in Fort Mill called Farmland USA.
   Clark said other assets may have to be sold to preserve the
ministry's religious activities, including the daily ``PTL Club''
show and the satellite TV network.
   He told Reynolds the $10 million water park at Heritage USA will
not open this year for lack of money.
   Clark also told the judge that people who once financed the
ministry aren't contributing any more. ``We had a moral bankruptcy
in the ministry that led to a financial bankruptcy,'' he said.
   He said the ministry laid off about 125 employees Friday,
leaving the full-time payroll at about 685. When Clark arrived at
PTL on Nov. 1, the ministry had about 1,100 employees.
   Clark said representatives of ``a major U.S. financial
institution'' will meet next week with PTL officials to discuss a
possible long-term loan of $45 million.
   But Reynolds was skeptical. ``I don't know who would loan you
money,'' the judge said.
   The financial troubles renewed talk that Bakker, who stepped
down last year in a sex and hush-money scandal, may return.
   ``The second that Clark fails, Jim will be back,'' said Inez
Brown, vice president of the Bring Bakker Back Club, which has been
urging supporters to withhold contributions until Bakker returns.
</TEXT>
