<2ND_LINE>AM-Allende Visa, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0551,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Upholds Ruling Against Government for Visa Denial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 3rd graf pvs, `But the ...' to ADD
that Mrs. Allende has visited the U.S. under visa.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. government acted improperly when it
denied the widow of former Chilean president Salvador Allende a
visa in 1983 by saying the speeches she planned to give were a
potential threat to foreign policy, a federal appeals court has
ruled.
   The 1st U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld a lower court
ruling that denying a visa to Hortensia Allende violated the 1952
Immigration and Nationality Act.
   But the court also noted that after the lawsuit was filed, the
government approved a multiple entry visa for Mrs. Allende valid
through the end of 1987 and has said it presumably would approve a
visa application in 1988.
   Mrs. Allende has visited the United States several times under
the visa, said one of her attorneys, Allan Rosenberg.
   The court rejected the Reagan administration's argument that
Mrs. Allende's presence would cause ``general harm to foreign
policy.''
   ``The government may not exclude Allende on the bare assertion
that her presence in the United States at any given time may
prejudice foreign policy interests,'' the court said in a decision
Wednesday upholding a U.S. District Court ruling last year.
   Mrs. Allende had planned to address several groups in California
that had invited her to speak on women's and human rights issues.
Her husband, Salvador Allende, was slain during a 1973 coup that
overthrew him and his Marxist government.
   The case was brought by the National Emergency Civil Liberties
Committee, the Boston Area Council on Latin America, the Northern
California Ecumenical Council and four Massachusetts university
professors who had invited Mrs. Allende to speak.
   In a statement, attorneys for the civil liberties organization
said the ruling ``is of historic significance because of the clear
ruling that Mrs. Allende was denied a visa because of the content
of her intended speech and the court's rejection of the
government's right to do so.''
</TEXT>
