<HEAD>Police to Notify Parents of Child's Gang Membership</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police plan to pay dinnertime calls on
parents of suspected gang members or recruits in an effort to curb
the burgeoning gang population.
   ``We're going to kick off a program of notifying parents of
at-risk young people in a very supportive way, not going to their
houses to threaten them,'' Assistant Police Chief Robert Vernon
said Friday.
   ``We'll be dropping around at the dinner hour'' to tell them
their children were seen with gang members, he said.
   The program will use intelligence information on gang associates
that in the past was kept within the department, Vernon said.
   Between Jan. 1 and April 4, there were 89 gang-related deaths in
Los Angeles County. Last year, there were 387 gang-related deaths
in the area.
