<HEAD>Thirteen Tear Gas Protestors Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUNNELTON, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirteen demonstrators were arrested
Saturday after chaining themselves to the gate of a plant that
manufactures tear gas being used by Israeli soldiers against
protesting Arabs, police said.
   Police said 200 to 300 demonstrators, most of whom arrived by
bus from Washington, D.C., West Virginia and Ohio, marched 2{ miles
from a park to the Federal Laboratories Inc. plant to ask for an
end to the manufacture of the tear gas canisters.
   Thirteen chained themselves to the gate until State Police
arrived with bolt cutters. They were charged with criminal
trespass. Most posted bail.
   The national American-Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee has
charged that more than 30 people have died from exposure to tear
gas in the West Bank and Gaza Strip. Tear gas can be lethal if
inhaled in a small, enclosed space.
   The parent company of the western Pennsylvania plant said last
week that it has written top Israeli officials over how its
products are being used.
   ``We asked what they can do to rectify the situation. ... We
stated we are very, very concerned,'' Burl Alison, vice president
of TransTechnologies Corp. of Sherman Oaks, Calif.
