<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-88 1930EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-WarsawGhetto     04-16 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Warsaw Ghetto,0449</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Celebrants Dance Again At Warsaw's Last Synagogue
^By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last synagogue in Warsaw was filled
Saturday with hundreds of young Jews who prayed, danced and sang
the Israeli national anthem to mark the Jewish ghetto uprising
against Nazi occupation troops.
   An overflow crowd of 1,000 people packed the rebuilt Nozyk
Synagogue, where the weekly Saturday morning services usually are
attended by only several dozen Polish Jews, most of whom are
elderly.
   There are no rabbis still in Poland, but several from Israel,
the United States, Canada and England led the Sabbath services on
Saturday.
   Several thousand Jews from around the world have come to Poland
to mark the 45th anniversary of the Warsaw Ghetto Uprising, in
which poorly armed insurgents fought a heroic but doomed battle to
resist the final Nazi drive to liquidate the 70,000 Jews left in
the ghetto.
   Israeli Deputy Prime Minister Itzhak Navon, who is heading the
official Israeli delegation for the anniversary observances, gave
an emotional speech to the worshipers, speaking in Hebrew.
   ``I want the Hebrew language to be heard here, the language of
the resurrection of the Jewish people,'' said Navon, who later
translated his remarks into English.
   Navon, the highest-ranking Israeli official ever to visit this
communist country, said ``nothing is left'' of Warsaw's
once-vibrant Jewish community.
   Before the 1939 Nazi invasion, Warsaw was home to about 380,000
Jews, or 30 percent of the city's population. Most died of hunger,
disease or in the gas chambers of Nazi death camps.
   ``There are no remains of the ghetto and of the revolt,'' said
Navon. ``For all those who survive there is only one way _ back to
Zion.''
   Afterwards, several hundred young Jews from Israel and other
countries sang Hebrew songs and joined hands to dance inside and in
front of the synagogue, which was destroyed by the Nazis and
reopened in April 1983 during observances of the 40th anniversary
of the ghetto uprising.
   They also sang ``The Hope,'' the Israeli national anthem.
   ``I'm very excited,'' said 15-year-old Tsul Shafil of Tel Aviv.
``I think it is very important for us to come because the blood is
here and we must be here to say that Israel is living.''
   Stanley Shapiro of Venice, Calif., a member of a U.S.-based
committee set up to preserve sites of the Holocaust in Poland, said
watching the young Jews dancing at the synagogue was an emotional
experience.
   ``I think it's a reaffirmation of the vitality of the Jewish
people,'' he said. ``It shows that the Jewish people remember and
do not forget.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880416-0133 </DOCNO>
