<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SouthKorea     04-16 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Korea,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Violence Breaks Out During South Korea Campaigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supporters of rival candidates battled
at political rallies throughout South Korea during campaigning
Saturday for legislative elections.
   It was the first day of ``joint'' rallies attended by opposing
candidates in the April 26 balloting.
   Police said about 12 people were injured in fights between
supporters of governing party candidates and opposition parties in
Seoul and other cities.
   In central Seoul, a woman believed to be a governing party
worker was injured when she was hit by an object thrown during a
rally that included opposition speakers.
   Another planned joint rally in Seoul was canceled because of
clashes.
   In the southern city of Kwangju, a dozen students attacked a
police station with rocks and firebombs. No injuries were reported.
   Also in Kwangju, hundreds of governing and opposition supporters
fought during a joint rally, hurling rocks and bottles, and a few
people were injured, police said.
   Other cities were clashes were reported included Chunchun,
Pusan, Inchon and Chonju.
   At stake in the elections are 299 National Assembly seats, of
which 224 are to be filled by direct popular vote with the
remaining 75 seats allocated to parties according to their share of
the overall vote.
   President Roh Tae-woo's Democratic Justice Party is seeking a
majority in the one-house legislature. Divisions among opposition
parties are expected to give the governing party the advantage.
   Roh won the presidency in balloting on Dec. 16 with just 36.6
percent of the vote. Main opposition leaders Kim Young-sam and Kim
Dae-jung split most of the remaining vote.
   In a rare show of unity, four opposition parties announced a
joint petition drive Saturday to urge the government to investigate
former President Chun Doo-hwan and his wife on corruption charges.
   The nation's two main opposition groups, the Reunification
Democratic Party and the Party for Peace and Democracy, and two
minor opposition parties said they hope to collect 1 million
signatures.
   Chun's brother, Chun Kyung-hwan, is awaiting trial on charges of
embezzlement, influence peddling and extortion while he was head of
the semi-official Saemaul Undong, or New Community, development
movement.
   Last week, ex-President Chun resigned as chairman of the
Advisory Council of State Elders, which advises the president on
national affairs, and as honorary chairman of the Democratic
Justice Party. He said he resigned because he had failed to prevent
his brother from acting improperly.
</TEXT>
