<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Graham     04-16 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Graham,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Billy Graham Welcomed by Chinese Premier</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American evangelist Billy Graham, making his
first visit to China, met Saturday with Premier Li Peng in
Zhongnanhai, a walled compound in central Beijing where many of the
Communist Party's top leaders reside.
   ``We don't have the same god but that doesn't matter,'' Li said
in opening remarks. ``It doesn't prevent us from having a good talk
together.''
   Graham said his wife Ruth was born in China, the daughter of
missionaries, and lived in China until she was 17. He said they
wanted to be good ambassadors for both Chinese and Americans.
   Also attending the meeting was Ren Wuzhi, head of the Religious
Affairs Bureau, and Bishop K.H. Ding, president of the China
Christian Council.
   Graham, 69, who has spoken at evangelical meetings in more than
60 countries, is to deliver a sermon to mainland Chinese for the
first time Sunday, at a Protestant church in Beijing.
   China has 4,000 established churches under the state-sanctioned
three-self movement of ``self-government, self-support and
self-propagation.''
   Religious worship is no longer suppressed as it was during the
1966-76 Cultural Revolution, but proselytizing is banned and
Catholics have been imprisoned for refusing to break ties with the
Vatican.
   According to official estimates there are about 4 million
Protestants and more than 3 million Catholics in China. There may
be others who stay away from the state-approved churches.
   Graham, a Southern Baptist, has met with students at Beijing
University and members of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences.
   Saturday morning Graham, his wife and their son Franklin visited
the Temple of Heaven, where China's emperors used to pray for good
harvests.
   The official English-language China Daily, in a report Saturday
on Graham's visit, quoting him as saying, ``I am impressed with the
fact that several thousand churches have reopened ... after the
decade of the Cultural Revolution.''
   Graham told the newspaper that Beijing University students ``had
a tremendous religious awareness'' and they talked about
Confucianism, Taoism and Islam as well as Christianity.
   He was asked if had converted any of the students and the paper
reported Graham laughed and said, ``I didn't attempt that. I was
just answering their questions.''
</TEXT>
