<2ND_LINE>AM-Aquino-Deng-Smoking, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0528,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinese, Philippine Leaders Differ on Smoking</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 4th, ``Deng, laughing...'' to note
that Deng continued smoking after Mrs. Aquino's comments; picks up
5th pvs: Deng has...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's most famous smoker, senior leader Deng
Xiaoping, ran up against the Philippines' most famous anti-smoking
advocate, President Corazon Aquino, at the Great Hall of the People
on Saturday.
   ``Mind if I smoke?'' the 83-year-old Deng asked at the start of
their talks.
   ``I cannot say no to you because I am not the leader of this
country,'' Mrs. Aquino responded as Deng lit up. ``But in the
Philippines for Cabinet meetings, no smoking'' is allowed, she
added.
   Deng, laughing, recalled that at the recent National People's
Congress session he had started smoking and ``a deputy to the
congress handed over a piece of paper criticizing my smoking. I
violated the regulations of the NPC so I stopped.''
   Deng continued smoking after Mrs. Aquino made her commments.
   Deng has acknowledged in the past that smoking and spitting are
his two most serious vices. He is believed to chain-smoke Panda
cigarettes, a high-quality brand unavailable to most Chinese.
   Public health officials in China only recently have begun to
warn the nation's 300 million smokers, including two-thirds of
Chinese men over the age of 15, of the dangers of smoking. Some
efforts have been made to ban smoking in train stations and other
public places.
   Mrs. Aquino, who reportedly suffers from asthma, has imposed
strict prohibitions on smoking in her home as well as at her
Cabinet meetings.
</TEXT>
