<HEAD>Bush Sweeps Maine Delegates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGOR, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Part-time Maine resident George Bush won
all 22 of the state's national convention delegates, one of whom is
his daughter, as the Republicans wound up their state convention on
Saturday.
   Former television evangelist Pat Robertson, who had once hoped
to stage an upset in Maine's February caucuses, succeeded only in
winning two alternates to the Republican National Convention.
   The delegates elected Saturday include Bush's daughter, Dorothy
Bush-LeBlond, who lives in Cape Elizabeth; Gov. John R. McKernan
Jr., and his mother, Barbara, who lives in Bangor.
   Bush backers had acknowledged a possibility that some Robertson
allies might infiltrate the Maine delegation, but the Bush camp
said it would not work actively to stop the Robertson forces.
   ``There's a spirit here not to cut everything all-out,'' said
Linwood Palmer of Nobleboro, a member of Bush's executive committee
who was ultimately elected as a national delegate.
   ``We're just going to let it go,'' McKernan said mid-way through
the delegate elections. ``If it were going to be a race, we'd play
hardball.''
   More than 1,000 people gathered in the Bangor Auditorium for the
convention, where the outcome of the delegate elections was never
seriously in question. Most of the speech-making amounted to an
advance celebration of the nomination Bush is expected to win in
New Orleans in August.
   McKernan, who has been Bush's most prominent Maine booster,
hailed him as ``the most qualified person ever to seek the
presidency.''
   Sen. William Cohen, R-Maine, who previously professed neutrality
in the presidential race, said, ``No one, in my judgment, comes
better prepared to assume the reins of leadership in this country
than George Bush.''
   McKernan said he plans to call all the delegates to a meeting in
Augusta in the next seve|~kS z
