<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Soviet-Spokesman     04-16 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Spokesman,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Spokesman Pokes Fun at Speakes Controversy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail Gorbachev's chief spokesman poked fun
Saturday at former White House spokesman Larry Speakes' admission
that he concoted quotes for President Reagan.
   Asked about his job during a news conference at the University
of Colorado, Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady Gerasimov
said: ``One difference is I don't put my own words in someone
else's mouth.''
   Gerasimov, who later gave a lecture at the university, also
called the war in Afghanistan ``a bleeding wound, and we're very
happy to have this wound heal'' by withdrawing Soviet troops.
   On Thursday, the Soviet Union, the United States, Pakistan and
Afghanistan signed an agreement calling for Soviet troops to begin
leaving Afghanistan on May 15.
   Gerasimov said Soviet intentions ``to help the revolution'' in
Afghanistan may have failed because ``maybe this revolution does
not have enough local roots to be a real socialist revolution.
Maybe they were too early.''
   Speakes, in his upcoming book, ``Speaking Out,'' said he twice
attributed remarks to Reagan that the president never said.
   In one instance, Speakes said he quoted Reagan as telling
Gorbachev during their 1985 Geneva summit meeting, ``There is much
that divides us, but I believe the world breathes easier because we
are talking here together.''
