<DOCNO> AP880416-0142 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-88 2150EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-YamamotoReunion 1stLd-Writethru a0634 04-16 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yamamoto Reunion, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0634,0632</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Historians, Survivors Debate Assassination of Japanese Naval
Commander</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with dispute over who shot down Yamamoto
and ADD survivors' accounts; CORRECTS Yamamoto's first name to
Isoroku sted Jukito. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FREDERICKSBURG, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forty-five years after U.S. fighter
pilots killed the mastermind of the Japanese attack on Pearl
Harbor, American survivors of the mission dispute who actually shot
down Admiral Isoroku Yamamoto.
   Yamamoto was killed April 18, 1943, when American fighter planes
intercepted his bomber near the Solomon Islands. Capt. Thomas G.
Lanphier Jr. of Detroit, who died last year, was credited by the
military with the kill.
   But the eight survivors among the 16 Americans who carried out
the mission said at a reunion Saturday that they could not
corroborate the official account because they had not been
debriefed immediately after the attack.
   They said they also could not determine how many Japanese Zero
fighters accompanying Yamamoto's bomber were shot down.
   ```At this time it's a toss up on who shot down the Betty
(bomber) carrying Admiral Yamamoto. Which one was he in? We didn't
know at that point,'' said Ret. Lt. Col. Besby Frank Holmes of San
Francisco. ``The passage of years hasn't clarified the subject.
These accounts add great confusion to the subject.
   ``I wish there would have been a debriefing years ago,'' he
added.
   Holmes and the seven other survivors spoke at a symposium along
with one of the Japanese Zero pilots.
   The gathering was held here because Fredericksburg is the home
of Admiral Chester Nimitz. Nimitz and his superiors approved the
mission after the Americans broke Japan's code and learned that
Yamamoto was going to be in the Solomon Islands.
   Yamamoto planned the Japanese raid on Pearl Harbor on Dec. 7,
1941, that triggered the United States' entry into World War II.
   Capt. Roger Pineau, a retired naval intelligence officer, said
Yamamoto's death gave the American war effort a major boost.
   ``In addition to the strategic and tactical effects of the shoot
down of Yamamoto, it was a fantastic morale blow to the Japanese
people,'' Pineau said. ``There was mourning in Japan after the
announcement of his death like is seldom seen except for emperors.
He was highly thought of.''
   The Americans attacked two Japanese bombers, one carrying
Yamamoto and the other his chief of staff, Vice Admiral Matome
Ugaki. The bombers were escorted by six Zeros.
   Holmes said he shot down the bomber carrying Ugaki, and Ret.
Col. Rex Barber of Culver, Ore., claimed on Saturday he shot down
Yamamoto's plane.
   Holmes said fights broke out after other pilots challenged their
account of the number of Zeros shot down.
   Kenji Yanagiya, the lone Zero pilot at Saturday's gathering,
added to the controversy when he said through an interpreter that
all six Zeros made it back to base safely. That brought jeers from
a crowd of about 400.
   Of the 16 Americans on the mission, one was listed as missing in
action, two died during later combat and five have died since the
war.
   Items once belonging to Yamamoto were unveiled in a new exhibit
Saturday at the Nimitz Museum here, including swords Yamamoto gave
to his men with the inscription, ``The fate of Japan's future
depends on the outcome of this war.''
   The items were loaned by Kansas City, Mo., resident Bernard
Brannon, whose brother, attorney John Brannon, acquired them after
World War II.
   John Brannon, who died last year, defended Japanese naval
officers charged with war crimes. In return for his services, the
Japanese officers gave him some of Yamamoto's personal items, said
Bruce Smith, superintendent of the Admiral Nimitz State Historical
Park.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880416-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-88 2153EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i TradeMinistersOfFourNationsMeetInSeclusion     04-16 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>Trade Ministers Of Four Nations Meet In Seclusion</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trade ministers from the
United States, Canada, Japan and the European Community met in
seclusion Saturday for talks on issues ranging from patent
protection to Japanese quotas on U.S. beef.
   The weekend quadrilateral meeting, held twice annually, took
place at a lodge on Quadra Island near Vancouver. The ministers
hold a final news conference Sunday.
   A dozen peaceful protesters against the U.S.-Canada Free Trade
Agreement, negotiated last year but not yet ratified, stood on the
road outside the lodge.
   The focus of Saturday's meeting was progress in the current
round of talks within the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade,
the 95-nation body governing world trade that was set up in 1948.
   The trade negotiations, involving 15 sub-groups, began in
September 1986 and are scheduled for a comprehensive review in
Montreal in December.
   Those talks have ``the most ambitious negotiating agenda in the
history'' of the world trade group, U.S. Trade Representative
Clayton Yeutter said in a prepared text for a speech delivered
Friday to the Vancouver Board of Trade.
   Yeutter was joined for the quadrilateral meeting by Trade
Ministers Hajime Tamura of Japan, John Crosbie of Canada and Willy
De Clercq of the 12-national European Community.
   The Reagan administration, joined by Canada, is pressing for new
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade rules to cover services such
as insurance and computer software, trade-related investment,
agriculture and protection for patents, copyrights and trademarks.
   ``Increasingly, countries are resorting to export subsidies and
non-tariff import barriers to achieve advantages over their
competitors,'' Yeutter said.
   Yeutter said he also is looking for prompt Japanese action to
relax tough quotas for U.S. beef and citrus products, or Washington
will press a formal complaint with the 95-nation group.
   Canadian trade official Sylvia Ostry said the erosion of open
trading principles made the current General Agreement on Tariffs
and Trade round critical.
   ``The outcome of this round will determine the outcome of the
multilateral trading system, period,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880416-0144 </DOCNO>
