<1ST_LINE>u a AM-No-NewsSheriff 1stLd-Writethru a0663 04-16 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-No-News Sheriff, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0663,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jefferson Parish Sheriff Extends News Blackout to All Media</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `In testimony ...' to CORRECT circulation to
280,000 sted 1 million.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>METAIRIE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sheriff of Louisiana's second-largest
parish, told by a federal judge he may no longer withhold news
exclusively from New Orleans' daily newspaper, extended his news
blackout Saturday to all media.
   Sheriff Harry Lee said in a statement that none of his Jefferson
Parish employees will talk with any reporter, except in an
emergency, until his lawyers examine the injunction issued Friday
by U.S. District Judge Robert Collins.
   ``Until this problem has been resolved, the sheriff's office
shall communicate with the press in the form of written press
releases,'' Lee said.
   Collins ruled that the sheriff cannot adopt a policy of treating
the newspaper's reporters any differently than those from other
news organizations. The injunction was obtained by The
Times-Picayune, which has been the target of a news embargo by Lee
since January, when the newspaper refused to change a story the
sheriff objected to.
   In testimony Friday, Lee also complained the newspaper,
Louisiana's largest daily with a weekday circulation of about
280,000, published inaccurate stories about him and his department.
   Because of Lee's news blackout, Times-Picayune reporters
sometimes were physically barred from news conferences.The
newspaper also got news releases a day or so after the news
happened in a parish with a population of nearly half a million,
equal almost to that of New Orleans.
   The sheriff also filed a $1 million defamation suit against the
newspaper.
   Lee made headlines more than a year ago when he announced he
would have deputies stop and question blacks traveling in white
neighborhoods. The furor from civil rights groups prompted him to
withdraw the order the next day and apologize.
</TEXT>
