<1ST_LINE>u p AM-SouthCarolina-Democrats 1stLd-Writethru a0617 04-16
0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Carolina-Democrats, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0617,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Forces Fail To Take Over South Carolina Democratic Party</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOPS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with state convention results;
PICKS UP 6th graf pvs bgng, `Columbia attorney'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TRIP DuBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson's supporters failed to take
control of the South Carolina Democratic Party on Saturday, but did
pick up nearly two-thirds of its delegates to the national
convention.
   The Jackson forces lost in their attempt to block the election
of Frank Holleman as state party chairman and lost in races for
several other leadership posts.
   The feuding leading up to the state convention had become
heated, but Kevin Gray, state campaign coordinator for Jackson,
said the party was not damaged.
   ``No one's walking out of this convention mad,'' he said.
   Jackson's support slipped somewhat since the March 12 precinct
caucuses, when his 54 percent showing appeared to be strong enough
to win him as many as 33 national convention delegates. When the
final step in the process was completed Saturday at the state
convention, Jackson had won 28 delegates.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, whose 7 percent finish in
the precinct caucuses was too weak to claim any national convention
delegates, won seven delegates chosen Saturday.
   Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr., whose 18 percent support in the
precinct caucuses was enough to bring him eight national convention
delegates, managed to win nine delegates in Saturday's balloting.
   The state's political infighting erupted over a list of demands
by Gray, who wanted assurances that the state party would work
toward a black-majority congressional district and consult with the
Jackson campaign on hiring party employees.
   Holleman had been considered a shoo-in, but that fell apart when
he refused to support the changes sought by the Jackson campaign.
   Columbia attorney Tom Turnipseed then entered the race, saying
he would honor the Jackson camp's requests. But within 24 hours,
Turnipseed withdrew after several leading black legislators, who
also support Jackson, expressed their satisfaction with Holleman.
   Gray subsequently struck six black legislators from the list of
Jackson delegates eligible to attend the national convention. He
later returned four of them to the list of delegates, saying it was
a ``gesture of conciliation.''
   ``I've got a little apprehension,'' House Speaker Bob Sheheen,
D-Kershaw, said before the convention opened. ``Obviously, if the
Jackson camp's going to be in turmoil, the convention's going to be
in turmoil,'' he said.
</TEXT>
