<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-88 2349EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SovietPlane     04-16 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Plane,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets claim first in flight of liquid hydrogen-fueled plane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet plane fueled by liquid hydrogen has
completed a test flight in a major development in aviation, the
official Tass news agency reported Saturday.
   ``A new page has thus been turned in the history of the aircraft
industry in the U.S.S.R. and the whole world,'' Tass said.
   It reported a Tupolev-154 aircraft with jet engines modified to
burn liquid hydrogen had flown sucessfully Friday but did not say
where the flight occurred.
   The evening television news program Vremya showed a videotape of
the flight, that it said was conducted at an airport outside Moscow
but did not identify the airfield.
   Tass said the converted Tu-154, renamed Tu-155, is a significant
advance in aviation because it will not pollute the atmosphere like
conventional jet aircraft with engines that burn oil-based fuels
and produce hydrocarbon pollutants.
   Vremya showed the aircraft's takeoff and landing and a segment
of what it said was the 21-minute flight. The tape showed the
refitted jet accompanied by a conventional Tu-154, and in the
footage the conventional plane's exhaust was black smoke while
Vremya said the Tu-155 emitted harmless steam.
   In an interview with Vremya, V.K. Orlov, the chief engine
designer of the Tu-155, said the engines combined aviation and
rocket technology. He said the liquid hydrogen was stored in tanks
aboard the plane at subfreezing temperatures.
   Most U.S. and Soviet space rocket boosters burn liquid hydrogen
and liquid oxygen.
   Neither Tass nor Vremya said how the engines operated, gave any
cost estimates or said if they would be installed on commercial
jetliners.
   Tass said special fire and explosion safety devices had to be
designed for the plane and ground support equipment.
</TEXT>
