<DOCNO> AP880416-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-88 2343EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Labor-TexasAir 2ndLd-Writethru a0685 04-16 0959</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Labor-Texas Air, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0685,940</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Air Probe Long Sought by Labor</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 12 graf pvs bgng, `On Sunday,' to UPDATE with ad
published in several major newspapers</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After four years of bitter conflict with Frank
Lorenzo and his airline empire, aviation labor is getting the
sweeping government investigation it wanted.
   But Transportation Department officials reject suggestions by
Lorenzo and his Texas Air Corp. that the probe announced Wednesday
is union-inspired.
   Officials say instead a series of financial ``red flags'' and
Texas Air's own request for approval to spin off Eastern Airline's
lucrative Northeast shuttle put senior department analysts on the
alert.
   With that backdrop, the deciding factor that triggered the
unprecedented investigation, say department officials, was word
from the Federal Aviation Administration of continuing safety
violations at Eastern Airlines.
   ``Other carriers have been in precarious financial positions in
the past and others have had safety violations in the past, but
we're not aware of a carrier having both come together this way at
the same time,'' said Matthew Scocozza, whose DOT office monitors
the major airlines.
   The broad investigation of Texas Air and its two subsidiary
airlines, Eastern and Continental, stunned executives at the
Houston-based airline company. Texas Air stock dropped $1.50 per
share, to $10.25, in two days and executives at both Eastern and
Continental worried what impact the publicity would have on
customers.
   But the turmoil surrounding Texas Air has been years in the
making.
   Lorenzo gained the wrath of organized aviation labor in 1983
when he shut down Continental Airlines, threw out its labor
contracts and within days started a new airline with employees
earning 50 percent less. Since Texas Air purchased Eastern Airlines
in 1986, there have been continuous and rancorous confrontations
over management demands for deep labor concessions.
   Lorenzo blames his troubles with labor for the government probe.
   ``There is no question that this issue is founded in an
old-fashioned labor dispute,'' said a corporate statement. ``The
union leaderships ... have mounted a continuing campaign of
distortion and lies. It is unfortunate that this campaign has
swayed others into action.''
   Eastern Airlines put advertisements into major newspapers the
day after the investigation was announced, saying it welcomed the
probe and hoped it would clear the air about the union's charges
and ``show unfair treatment of Eastern'' by the FAA.
   On Sunday, Texas Air put a full-page advertisement in several
major newspapers that featured an editorial from Friday's New York
Times. The editorial concluded: ``Texas Air has offended organized
labor, the industry establishment and a lot of important people in
Washington. The airline has also irritated a lot of travelers....
It would be a pity, though, if these complaints distracted
attention from Texas Air's constructive role in forcing a
self-satisfied, cartel-minded industry to come to terms with
competition.''
   Ironically, the order to investigate Texas Air came from a
Transportation Department that over the years has been considered
anything but friendly to labor. In nearly two dozen airline
mergers, the department not once has approved formal
labor-protection provisions sought by the unions.
   While the department denies being forced into action by labor,
there is little doubt that the unions' well-financed and determined
campaign drew the government's attention.
   The FAA's intense look at Eastern Airlines last year, for
example, was in part prompted by union reports of alleged
maintenance and safety violations, including charges repeated at
congressional hearings that management was trying to force crews to
fly unsafe aircraft.
   Pilots began sending postcards to aviation committees in
Congress, the FAA and its parent DOT whenever there were
maintenance problems with Eastern planes.
   Labor challenges in court to the transfer of the Northeast
shuttle from Eastern into a separate Texas Air subsidiary also
caused DOT officials concern after a federal judge came down on the
side of the unions.
   When the judge stopped the transfer and found Texas Air in
contempt of court for violating an earlier court injunction, the
department began to question the airline's attitude about complying
with government requirements, said Wayne Vance, the DOT's general
counsel.
   ``We had been aware of what was going on within the world of
Texas Air Corp.,'' said Vance. But he added that with the court
decision on the shuttle ``concern grew and grew.''
   An internal department ``alert memo'' was prepared noting Texas
Air's record losses of $466 million in 1987, and its debts of more
than $5 billion _ requiring $600 million in interest payments.
   New filings, meanwhile, by Texas Air with the Securities and
Exchange Commission raised additional ``red flags,'' Vance and
Scocozza noted. The SEC filings provided more details on a series
of bothersome transactions between Texas Air and Eastern that
suggested assets were being drained from Eastern.
   Texas Air had moved Eastern's valuable computer reservation
system into a separate subsidiary in exchange for a note likely
worth less than the system's fair market value; Texas Air charged
``substantial fees'' for various services to Eastern; and the
parent company never paid Eastern $16 million it promised as a
reimbursement from costs incurred during its 1986 acquisition of
the airline.
   Amid this backdrop came word from the FAA that a year after
Eastern agreed to pay $9.5 million in fines for safety violations,
many of the same violations seemed to persist. Eastern faces an
additional possible fine of $823,000, and a new round of special
inspections.
   That, say Scocozza and Vance, sealed the case for a broader
inquiry into the Lorenzo aviation empire.
   ``The ball is now in the government's court,'' said Jack Bavis,
head of the pilots union at Eastern. ``We know what the problems
are. What remains to be seen is how well the DOT and FAA follow
through on their announcements.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880416-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-88 0608EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Army-Mormons     04-16 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Army-Mormons,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Balks at Separate Space at Base For Mormon Church</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite congressional pressure, the Army said
Friday it won't provide the land or help build a large church for
the exclusive use of Mormon employees at a Utah military
installation.
   ``The Army is opposed in principle to the construction and
exclusive use of a private house of worship by any religious
organization on a military installation,'' Assistant Army Secretary
Delbert L. Spurlock wrote in a letter to congressional committees.
   Some 700 Mormon workers at the isolated Dugway Proving Ground
are asking for their own religious facility, claiming the building
now shared by all the installation's religious demominations is too
small.
   Sen. Jake Garn, R-Utah, has argued that better space is needed
because so many members of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day
Saints work at the isolated base.
   But Spurlock said in his letter, ``No statutory authority exists
which would permit this at Dugway and, if such authority were
proposed (by Congress), it would likely'' violate constitutional
provisions against the government establishment of religion.
   Moreover, while the Army building now being used by Mormon
employees at Dugway as their church is ``substandard,'' that
building by itself ``is more than twice the religious education
facility size authorized for the entire Dugway population,'' the
service said.
   If the Army obtains money to build new religious facilities at
Dugway, those buildings would have to be shared by all
denominations and will certainly be smaller than the buildings now
used, the Army said.
   Spurlock's comments were contained in a cover letter that
accompanied a special report to the House and Senate Appropriations
Committees on Friday. The report was requested by Congress in
December at the urging of Garn, who is a Mormon.
   The Mormons at the base are currently allowed exclusive use of a
warehouse they have renovated as a chapel, but would like to build
a larger, modern facility at the base.
   Dugway is a research and test site for chemical weapons located
about 90 miles west of Salt Lake City and about 40 miles from the
nearest town. There are about 700 Mormons at Dugway, which employs
roughly 1,700 people. Most of the workers are civilians.
   The Mormon workers turned to Garn for help after the Army
rejected the church's request for a long-term lease on 2.5 acres of
land to construct a building. Garn has said through a spokeswoman
that if the Army doesn't come up with an acceptable plan to provide
adequate space, he will ask Congress to order the Army to issue a
lease.
   Laurie Snow, the senator's spokeswoman, declined comment Friday,
saying Garn had not yet seen the report.
   The report, however, hardly appears likely to satisfy the Mormon
workers.
   Given the ``current austere budget conditions,'' it says, ``it
is not anticipated'' any money could be requested from Congress
during the next five years to upgrade the existing facilities at
Dugway.
   There are at least 55 ``critical Army religious projects'' with
a higher priority, the report states.
   ``And the Army is opposed, on principle, to construction of a
private house of worship by any religious organization on any
military installation,'' the service concluded.
   ``To allow such construction favors religious groups with the
financial resources to build. It also places religious groups that
are without those resources at a disadvantage.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
