<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Colombia-Emergency     04-16 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Emergency,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State of Siege Declared in Northern Region</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Virgilio Barco declared a
state of siege in the Uraba region, scene of several massacres of
peasants, and gave an army general broad powers to end the violence.
   Barco announced the action Thursday night. The president has
special powers under a state of emergency that has been in effect
throughout Colombia for 30 years because of leftist guerrilla
violence.
   Under the siege, which goes beyond a state of emergency, Barco
gave Gen. Fernando Gomez Barros military, political and civil
control of Uraba, authorizing him to take whatever steps necessary
to bring peace to the rich agricultural and ranching area of
northern Colombia.
   ``The entire nation has followed with an enormous sense of pain
and with complete rejection the situation of unbridled violence in
the prosperous region of Uraba,'' the president said.
   He also announced measures to alleviate the ``deep social and
economic roots'' of the violence.
   Leaders of peasant unions blame the Uraba massacres on ``death
squads'' created by landowners to expel thousands of peasant
squatters. Justice Minister Enrique Low Murtra has attributed the
bloodshed to ultra-rightist groups.
   In the past two months, more than 100 people have been killed in
attacks by armed groups on peasants, workers and others in Uraba
and other eastern and northern sections of Colombia.
   Uraba is in the department of Antioquia and has a Caribbean
coastline extending to Panama, about 550 miles north of Bogota.
</TEXT>
