<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Mecham     04-16 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mecham Gives His `Plain, Old Ordinary Swan Song'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Evan Mecham announced Friday
he will not fight his Senate impeachment conviction or the
cancellation of Arizona's gubernatorial recall election but will
remain politically active.
   ``We would have to go to the Supreme Court of the U.S., and the
legal costs make that prohibitive,'' Mecham said on KTSP-TV's
``Face the State'' program, which was taped Friday to be aired on
Sunday.
   Mecham, 63, said he plans to write a book about his
accomplishments in office and take a vacation with his wife.
   He also said he will keep his Glendale office open and establish
two politial action committees to help elect candidates who
represent ``the people.''
   ``It's a plain, old ordinary swan song,'' he told reporters
outside the studio where the taping was held.
   Mecham was ousted by the Senate April 4 on charges that he
obstructed justice and misused state money, becoming the first U.S.
governor impeached and removed from office in 59 years.
   Arizona's Supreme Court earlier this week ordered the
cancellation of a May 17 recall election because its target,
Mecham, already had been removed. The former governor had said he
would run in the election unless barred by law.
   Mecham said during the interview Friday he has ``no intention of
plea-bargaining'' in his upcoming criminal trial on charges of
concealing a $350,000 campaign loan, and added, ``I expect to be
acquitted.''
</TEXT>
