<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GlobalForum     04-16 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Global Forum,0580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Religious Leaders and Lawmakers To Collaborate For `Better World'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An international forum of religious
leaders and legislators declared Friday that the 140 delegates from
60 nations will strive together for ``a fundamentally changed and
better world.''
   A statement at the end of the five-day Global Forum of Spiritual
and Parliamentary Leaders on Human Survival pledged to work against
the perils of armaments, for balancing resources and populations,
and in aid of ``vulnerable groups, particularly women and
children.''
   ``This meeting is a timely convergence of hearts, minds and
events,'' the statement said. ``Human society is in a period of
intense introspection, gripped by fear, uncertainty and confusion.
   ``We therefore now affirm our shared vision of survival, and we
commit ourselves to work for a fundamentally changed and better
world.''
   The five main religions _ Buddhism, Christianity, Hinduism,
Islam and Judaism _ were represented along with African religions,
the Jainism offshoot of Hinduism, and Shinto and Sikhism.
   Among the many speakers were the Archbishop of Canterbury Robert
Runcie, spiritual head of the Church of England and worlwide
Anglican communion; American astronomer Carl Sagan; Mother Teresa,
the Nobel Peace Prize winner whose organization cares for the poor
and dying in 80 countries; Yevgeny Velikhov, vice president of the
Soviet Academy of Sciences, and the Dalai Lama, the exiled Buddhist
god-king of Tibet.
   ``This meeting was very important and another sign of the change
from confrontation to cooperation after the Soviet-U.S. agreements
on intermediate nuclear missiles and Afghanistan,'' Velikhov said.
   Paul N. Temple, chairman of Energy Development Corp., a U.S.
company sponsoring the forum, said: ``It developed almost a family
spirit across the enormous diversity of religion and national
affiliations. Channels of dialogue are opening that never existed
before.''
   Ayman Abdelkader Ahwal of the Moslem World League's London
office said, however: ``Although it might have been unintentional,
it has been a Christian-orientated conference, as is perhaps the
tone of world politics.
   ``The conference ignored the situation in the Middle East, which
is terribly dangerous. Religion is politics and they cannot be
separated to a truly religious person.''
   Dean James Parks Morton of the Episcopal Cathedral of St. John
the Divine in New York, said China did not attend because of the
Dalai Lama's presence, but organizers left two seats vacant on the
leadership body in hopes of obtainig representatives of Taoism and
Confucianism.
   The conference was the idea of Akio Matsumura, a Japanese expert
on population who lives in New York and spent 15 years promoting
this week's meeting.
   On the last day, conference delegates gave a standing ovation to
two American Indian leaders in traditional costume who said their
ancestors foretold the ills of the modern world long ago.
   Thomas Banyacya, a Hopi elder from Arizona, held up a
reproduction of an ancient rock painting near Oraibi, east of the
Grand Canyon, that he said appears to predict nuclear destruction,
space travel and the ravaging of the environment.
   Chief Oren R. Lyons of the Onandaga nation, a history professor
at the State University of New York in Buffalo, read a letter Chief
Seattle wrote to President Franklin Pierce in 1855 that said the
white man's hunger for land would ``eat the Earth bare and leave
only a desert.''
   ``Continue to soil your bed and one night you will suffocate in
your own waste,'' the chief declared.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
