<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia-Fascist     04-16 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Fascist,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yugoslavs Claiming To Be Ex-Fascists Ask For Italian War Pensions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 140 people claiming they
backed fascist Italy's occupation forces in Yugoslavia during World
War II say they should receive Italian war pensions, newspapers
reported Friday.
   The state-run press said the claimants are trying to fight a
sharp drop in living standards by trying to receive the Italian
military pensions, which it said are about three times higher than
the average Yugoslav pension of about $100 a month.
   Communist Yugoslavia is faced with a 170 percent inflation rate,
Europe's highest.
   The citizens from Ljubusko, a town near the central Adriatic
coast, have submitted documentary evidence proving that they
belonged to ``a volunteer anti-communist militia'' formed by
Italian occupation authorities to fight partisans during the war,
the NIN weekly said.
   Media reports said the citizens of Ljubusko got the idea after
several thousand Yugoslavs from the northern region of Istria
recently received back payments from Italy for wartime service.
   The Istria residents were forcibly mobilized by the Italian army
during the war.
   In a critical commentary titled, ``I Request To Be Declared An
Enemy,'' the Borba daily said the fascist Italian militia committed
atrocities and terrorized the local population during World War II.
   Nazi Germany and Italy invaded Yugoslavia in 1941 and fought
Yugoslav partisan troops until 1945, when they were driven from the
country.
   But thousands of Yugoslavs joined the occupation forces and
fought the partisans.
   The Ljubusko citizens submitted their request for Italian
pensions to Yugoslav authorities, said the NIN newspaper. It said
local authorities told the applicants to address their requests
directly to Italy.
   But the press said there was little chance for the claimants to
get Italian war pensions even if it is proved they joined the
Italian occupation troops, because they belonged to a volunteer
body of anti-partisan fighters and not to a regular army unit.
   The Italian Embassy in Belgrade said only Italian pension
officials could decide on the claims.
</TEXT>
