<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Newspapers     04-16 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Newspapers,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Threatens To Close Three Publications</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Friday
warned two anti-apartheid newspapers and a magazine that they would
be shut down if they continue to print material it consideres
subversive.
   Home Affairs Minister Stoffel Botha, who has state-of-emergency
powers to close publications considered subversive, issued the
threats in a government gazette published Friday.
   Receiving the warnings were Grassroots and Saamstaan, two
community newspapers, and Out of Step, a magazine published every
two months by the End Conscription Campaign that opposes the
mandatory military service for white males.
   Botha said the publications were ``a threat to public safety.''
   He recently closed one black-oriented weekly newspaper, The New
Nation, for 12 weeks and has told several other anti-apartheid
publications they face similar action.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
   Alistair Teeling-Smith, national secretary of the End
Conscription Campaign, said shutting down his magazine would be
pointless.
   ``Even if the publications are silenced, the issue of
conscription and its problems remains,'' he said. ``A more
satisfactory way of addressing these problems would be to provide a
reasonable system of alternative service.''
   White South African males must serve two years of military
service initially and then are liable for annual training camps.
   The anti-draft group says it particularly opposes the deployment
of conscripts in black townships and in wars in South-West Africa,
also known as Namibia, and in neighboring Angola.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
