<HEAD>Bangladesh To Release Political Prisoners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Friday it will free
all 1,000 political prisoners to help create a ``congenial
atmosphere.'' Opposition leaders claimed at least 8,000 people are
imprisoned for political reasons.
   State-run Radio Bangladesh quoted Interior Minister Abdul Matin
as saying opposition political activists arrested during
anti-government protests will be freed soon.
   Matin did not give a time schedule or specify how many prisoners
were being held, but an Interior Ministry official said the process
had begun to free the prisoners.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said at least
5,000 political prisoners had been detained since the opposition
launched its anti-governmnent campaign on Nov. 10. But he said that
some 4,000 were released before the March 3 parliamentary elections.
   President Hussain Muhammad Ershad's Jatiya Party won the
elections that were boycotted by opposition leaders.
   ``We will release all political detainees to create a congenial
atmosphere,'' the radio broadcast quoted Matin as telling police
officials meeting in Dhaka.
   The announcement followed the lifting of a 4-month-old state of
emergency on April 12.
</TEXT>
