<2ND_LINE>AM-Wander Dog, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0815,0445</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Clark The Wander Dog Likes Vacant Plant Site, Won't Leave</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to CORRECT name of transportation site to
Horizon sted Clark, which was former name, CLARIFY that dog roams
two adjacent properties. Pickup 7th graf pvs, `More than ...' SUBS
10th graf pvs, `Reed said ...' to CORRECT to Horizon's new owners,
sted site's.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BATTLE CREEK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of offers to adopt Clark the
wander dog have been made since the story of the mutt who hangs out
at a now-vacant transportation complex was circulated, but Clark is
staying put.
   Attempts by Leora Reed to coax Clark from the complex to a new
life with a new owner have been fruitless.
   Clark has been roaming the former Horizon Transportation
Services Corp. site and the adjacent former Clark Equipment Co.
property. Workers at both companies provided a dog house and food
until Clark Equipment closed last fall, followed by Horizon's
demise in March.
   When Horizon's last employee, Barbara Renbarger, left last
month, Clark was alone except for Reed, his new friend. She noticed
the dog several weeks ago and began trying to find him a home.
   ``I have a great love for dogs and I just sort of felt sorry for
the little guy,'' she said. ``I fell in love with him.''
   Clark has returned the friendship through approving wags of the
tail when Reed brings food to him. But he has frustrated her
attempts to capture him or coax him off the properties. She even
hired a veterinarian to use a dart to tranquilize Clark, but two
attempts have failed. Clark was scared and maintained his practice
of keeping his distance from all humans.
   More than 25 people wanted to adopt the dog, including one woman
in Louisville, Ky., who offered to fly Clark to her home.
   The publicity that brought the adoption offers has also brought
Clark a local windfall of edible contributions.
   ``Some have brought prime rib bones or hamburger or chicken,''
Reed said. ``He has at least a 10-course meal every day.''
   Reed said she has given up trying to get Clark to leave.
Horizon's new owners, who have asked that the name of the company
be kept secret for now, have told her Clark can stay and she can
visit him anytime.
   ``I have learned that possibly my way is not the best way,''
Reed said. ``Even though he is living in the wild, he is capable of
taking care of himself. I hate to take his freedom away.''
   Clark will still have his dog house and can wander the property.
</TEXT>
