<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-88 0715EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a AM-ColumbiaProtest 1stLd-Writethru b0327 04-16 1211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Columbia Protest, 1st Ld - Writethru, b0327,1238</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thu AMs, April 21, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Images of Takeover, Cigars in President's Office, Fresh After 20
Years</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 22nd graf pvs, `Few, if ...' to CORRECT first name to
Douglas sted Thomas and CORRECT spelling to Ginsburg sted Ginsberg.
Note April 23 anniversary date.</NOTE>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty years later, the Columbia University
student uprising is remembered less for issues than images:
   The statue of Alma Mater with a ``RAPED'' sign around her neck.
   A student sitting at the president's desk, puffing one of the
president's cigars.
   Police vans rolling across College Walk.
   For a time it seemed revolution had come to the Ivy League. The
dean was held hostage. A professor lost a decade's research when a
protester torched his files. Two students were married in an
occupied building by a minister who crawled through the window.
   About 1,000 people, mostly students, barricaded themselves
inside five campus buildings for a week, closing the college and
drawing international attention to their opposition to racism, the
Vietnam War and the status quo in general.
   Columbia was just one stop on the bumpy road from Berkeley to
Kent State, but a memorable one. ``The atmosphere was like the
French Revolution,'' said Fred Friendly, a journalism professor and
former CBS News producer. ``You expected to see Robespierre on the
next block.''
   Today, Mark Rudd, chairman of Students for a Democratic Society
at Columbia in 1968, still refers to university officials as ``war
criminals.'' And Paul Vilardi, who as a student led opposition to
the revolt, characterizes the protesters as ``nobodies, loners and
oddballs.''
   The rebellion began almost by accident: 500 students, led by the
SDS and the Student Afro-American Society, tried to invade the
administration building April 23, but found the doors locked.
   Someone in the crowd urged a march to the site of a gymnasium
the school had started to build in Morningside Park, a buffer
between elite, white Columbia and impoverished, black Harlem.
   For months, three issues had festered: the gym, which became a
symbol of Columbia's neighborhood expansion; Columbia's links to
the Institute for Defense Analyses, which commissioned military
research, and school disciplinary action against SDS leaders for
previous demonstrations.
   At the gym site, the students tore down a construction fence and
fought with police. Then they marched back to campus, into Hamilton
Hall and up to the door of Acting Dean Henry Coleman.
   When Coleman refused to discuss the students' demands under
those circumstances, the students told him he could not leave.
Later that night, SDS left the building to the black students and
went off to seize Low Library, the domed administration building
whose steps provided a stage for the ensuing drama.
   Coleman was released after about 24 hours, but other groups of
students seized three more buildings. Faculty members ringed the
buildings to prevent violence and tried to negotiate a settlement.
   The rebellion quickly became a happening, with extensive news
coverage and appearances by Tom Hayden, Abbie Hoffman, Rap Brown,
Stokely Carmichael, William Kunstler, Herbert Marcuse, Allen
Ginsberg and the Grateful Dead.
   Columbia President Grayson Kirk called in the police April 30.
They cleared the buildings and made 692 arrests, about 75 percent
of them Columbia students or teachers. Hospitals treated 103
patients, 85 of them students or teachers.
   A student strike ensued, and a month later students again
occupied Hamilton Hall to protest the discipline of protest
leaders; again the police moved in, this time with fewer arrests
(68) and more injuries (177).
   Today, those who fought the battle of Columbia reminisce like
the veterans of any war.
   ``We feel good about what we did, and under the same
circumstances we'd do it again,'' said Andrea Egan, 44, who was
married in occupied Fayerweather Hall. ``Some people talk about the
strike now as if it was a panty raid, but it's important for those
of us who were there to say, `It had great significance.'''
   Working from an old arrest list, Ms. Egan has organized a
protest reunion on campus April 22-23.
   ``My guess is that nine out of 10 still put their principles
into practice in some way,'' she said. ``Not many of us can afford
to be full-time activists, but you see the strikers' convictions in
the type of law or medicine they practice, the films they make, or
the way we raise our children.''
   Few, if any, have run for political office. ``Most of us could
not stand the scrutiny candidates get,'' Ms. Egan said. ``Not only
the strike, but sex and drugs and rock 'n' roll. We couldn't do a
(U.S. Circuit Judge Douglas H.) Ginsburg and say, `I only did it
twice.'''
   After the rebellion, the veterans scattered. Cicero Wilson, a
black student leader, wound up at the conservative American
Enterprise Institute. Ted Gold, a member of the radical Weather
Underground, was killed when a homemade bomb exploded in a
Greenwich Village townhouse. David Gilbert is serving a 75-year
prison sentence for his role in a 1981 armored car robbery.
   Rudd, the most celebrated protest leader, resurfaced from the
underground in 1977 and now lives in Albuquerque, N.M., where he is
writing his autobiography and working against U.S. involvement in
Central America.
   Today, he claims victory: ``What we did wasn't futile. We won.
We stopped the war.''
   To Vilardi, leader of the anti-protest Majority Coalition, that
is nonsense. ``I don't really see where anything happened (as a
result of the rebellion),'' said Vilardi, a surgeon in Huntsville,
Texas. ``You'd have to be incredibly naive to think that the people
who made the decisions in Washington cared what a bunch of jerks
were doing up in New York.''
   Orest Ranum, the professor whose papers were burned, moved to
Johns Hopkins University in 1969. He says he's glad he spoke
against the occupation: ``I got out of the library and took a step
further into the types of human experiences that change the world.''
   Coleman, now an educational consultant, says he later wrote law
school recommendations for some of the students who held him
captive. Bill Sales, one of the black students who took over
Hamilton Hall, is back on campus, finishing a stint as a Revson
fellow.
   Columbia ``has changed a whole lot, and not for the better,''
said Sales, who lives in Harlem. ``There's less sense of social
responsibility among students and faculty, and more separation of
town and gown.''
   The university eventually dropped its criminal case against most
students. School disciplinary measures bogged down for months in
the trial-like proceedings established after the uprising.
   A few students were suspended. ``Permanent Censure'' was stamped
on some transcripts. Fellowships were lost, law school admissions
denied.
   Columbia severed its link with the Institute for Defense
Analyses, although some professors continue to do classified
military research. The university regularly incurs the wrath of
some neighbors in its role as a large institutional lanlord and
developer.
   Columbia eventually built a gym on the other side of campus. The
Parks Department says it finally plans to erase the uprising's last
physical scar _ the gym's foundation hole on a rocky hillside in
Morningside Park, unfilled these 20 years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thu AMs, April 21</NOTE>
</DOC>
