<1ST_LINE>d f PM-EconomyRdp     04-16 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inflation Shows First Jump of Year in March Wholesale Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Wholesale prices rose at an annual rate of 7 percent in March,
according to a government report that heightened fears of inflation
and sent interest rates up to levels not seen in three months.
   Market reaction to the bad news was restrained Friday. Although
interest rates climbed back to January levels, the dollar held its
ground with the support of central banks, and stock prices were
mixed.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 blue-chip stocks dropped 101.46
points on Thursday, but rose 8.29 on Friday even though stocks in
the broader market were down by a 9-to-5 ratio.
   The Labor Department said its producer price index for finished
goods rose 0.6 percent last month, marking the biggest increase
since April 1987 and more than erasing a 0.2 percent decline in
February.
   Energy and food prices shot up, as did wholesale prices for a
wide marketbasket of other consumer goods and capital equipment.
   The price report came on the heels of Thursday's surprising
Commerce Department report that the nation's trade deficit expanded
by $1.4 billion to $13.8 billion in February.
   The twin reports raised speculation that the Federal Reserve
would act to curb inflation fears and support the dollar by
tightening credit, which would raise interest rates.
   Lawrence Hunter, an economist for the U.S. Chamber of Commerce,
expressed fears that the Fed will ``overreact to perceived
inflationary pressures that some see in the recent data'' and
stymie economic growth
   ``Oversteering in the face of monthly price swings can only feed
fears of inflation,'' Hunter said, referring to figures that show
the annual wholesale price increases of just 3.1 percent when
averaged over the past three months.
   However, Donald Ratajczak, a Georgia State University economist
who specializes in wholesale price trends, said increases in April
will match, if not exceed, those in March.
   ``This isn't a one-month aberration,'' Ratajczak said. ``Strong
increases in raw material prices that have been going on for six
months are widening and spreading. It's not runaway inflation, but
it's a little worrying.''
   In another report Friday, the Commerce Department said that
businesses planning to increase their capital spending by 8 percent
this year after raising it by only 1.7 percent in 1987.
   The Commerce report reflected increasing optimism about the
economy among businessmen who, when last surveyed in December, said
they planned to increase their capital spending by 7.3 percent this
year.
   Meanwhile, the Federal Reserve reported that industrial
production edged up just 0.1 percent in March. Analysts said that
report was the only indication that the economy is not overheating
following a long string of data suggesting that it is.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
