<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-88 0652EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-Speakes-Future     04-16 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Speakes-Future,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PR Expert Larry Speakes Makes Big PR Miscalculation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Speakes Resigns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writers</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Larry Speakes slalomed through 2,000 press
briefings during his six-year stint as White House spokesman, but
he made a major public relations miscalculation when it came to his
own foray into self-promotion.
   The president's former PR man quit his lucrative job as chief
spokesman for Merrill Lynch & Co. on Friday following the
revelation in his upcoming book, ``Speaking Out,'' that he
concocted quotes for President Reagan.
   Fabricating quotes is not an offense of such magnitude to lock
Speakes out of the public relations profession altogether, but his
credibility has been severely damaged and it probably will be
reflected in his paycheck, PR people said.
   One New York public relations executive, speaking on the
condition of anonymity, said clients would be very reluctant to
hire Speakes because he showed ``a certain amount of
insensitivity'' in confession to the creation of quotes.
   ``If we went out and said we did this or that for a client, it
would make anyone else look at us twice before trusting us with
confidential information,'' the executive said.
   Industry insiders said Speakes is going to have a hard time
matching his $200,000-plus Merrill Lynch salary.
   ``There aren't that many $250,000 jobs around in my
profession,'' said Howard J. Rubenstein, president of an
influential New York-based public relations firm that bears his
name.
   But because Speakes remains a ``major name in the business with
powerful connections,'' he probably won't be standing in
unemployment lines, said Pamela Talbot, manager of the Chicago
office of the public relations firm Daniel J. Edelman Inc.
   She predicted Speakes would find a job, ``but not one with as
high a profile or at such a high level.''
   Lawrence W. Fisher, president and chief executive of the Los
Angeles public relations firm Braun & Co., agreed that Speakes
``will not have any trouble finding a job _ but maybe not in the
communications field.''
   Meanwhile, industry executives recommend Speakes jump on the
lecture circuit, where he can make a fine living ``just like Spiro
Agnew,'' one insider said.
   Ultimately, his peers predicted, Speakes will be absolved, just
as Richard Nixon and Gary Hart regained some public dignity.
   Quitting Merrill Lynch ``will probably hype sales of his book
and that's fortunate for him, because it may be a long time before
he finds a job as lucrative as the one he gave up,'' said one New
York-based public relations executive, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880416-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-88 0653EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-SpeakesResigns     04-16 0725</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Speakes Resigns,0756</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Speakes' `PR Man's License' Comes Back to Get Him</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The phony quotes that Larry Speakes ascribed to
President Reagan while running the White House press office have
come back to shatter his 14-month-old Wall Street career as chief
spokesman for Merrill Lynch & Co.
   The 48-year-old senior vice president of communications at the
investment giant quit Friday after creating an uproar by admitting
in a new book that he twice concocted quotes for Reagan.
   The confession had raised serious questions about his
credibility as a communicator for Merrill Lynch, which like other
Wall Street firms have become extremely sensitive to their public
image since the stock crash six months ago.
   Sources inside Merrill Lynch, who spoke on the condition they
not be identified, said the company's senior management was alarmed
over the impact of Speakes' disclosure and relieved when he told
them he was resigning.
   ``We took the attitude that he, being the communicator, knew
very well what this torrent of publicity was doing to him as our
chief spokesman and the image of Merrill Lynch as its chief
spokesman,'' one source said.
   Speakes said in a brief written statement that his decision was
``the best course of action for Merrill Lynch and for me
personally. Merrill Lynch is a great firm and the industry leader,
and I've enjoyed being part of it.''
   Merrill Lynch said in the statement: ``We accept Larry Speakes'
resignation with regret. Larry has made a significant contribution
to our firm during his time here, and we wish him well in every
regard.''
   Fred Yager, a Merrill Lynch spokesman, declined to elaborate on
Speakes' resignation, saying: ``I think the statement speaks for
itself. I'm not going to veer from the statement.''
   Speakes was not in Merrill Lynch's New York headquarters when
the announcement was made and company officials said they did not
know his whereabouts.
   He joined Merrill Lynch with much fanfare in February 1987,
earning an annual salary that sources said tripled the $77,400 he
made at the White House. He oversaw a staff of about 70 people with
responsibility over Merrill Lynch's press relations, corporate
advertising and in-house communications.
   The controversy began Monday when Speakes disclosed that in his
upcoming book ``Speaking Out'' he recounted two occasions when he
attributed to Reagan quotes that the president never said.
   ``In restrospect, it was clearly wrong to take such liberties,''
he wrote in the book. But, he added, ``I had been able to spruce up
the president's image by taking a bit of liberty with my P.R. man's
license.''
   In one instance, Speakes recalled, he quoted Reagan as saying
after Soviet gunners shot down a Korean Air Lines passenger jet in
1983 that the incident didn't pose a Soviet-U.S. problem, but a
``Soviet versus the world problem.''
   Speakes said that comment really came from Secretary of State
George Shultz. Speakes said he also credited Reagan with some
suggestions for possible retaliatory measures, which also had been
made by Shultz.
   In the other instance, Speakes said, he quoted Reagan as telling
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev during their Geneva summit,
``There is much that divides us, but I believe the world breathes
easier because we are talking here together.''
   He said in the book that he and a press aide, Mark Weinberg,
concocted this quotation.
   The disclosures created an uproar among the present White House
press office staff and was criticized by a broad range of
professionals in the public relations business, who said it damaged
his credibility.
   Although Speakes said he had told Reagan about the phony quotes,
Reagan denied it Wednesday and expressed anger over what he called
a ``kiss & tell'' piece of fiction. Reagan said ``no comment''
Friday when asked for a reaction to Speakes' resignation.
   Speakes' successor Marlin Fitzwater, who had denounced Speakes
earlier in the week for the bogus quotes, told reporters Friday,
``I'm sorry for him, personally.'' Fitzwater said he would comment
no further.
   Asked for reaction to his resignation, some public relations
executives said he might have trouble finding another prestigious
PR job.
   ``Credibility is requirement number one in this business. When
you have lost your credibility you have lost a hell of a lot,''
said Lawrence W. Fisher, president and chief executive of Braun &
Co. in Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
